115	1	3	01/28/2026-00118	CTAP-42746	2026-01-28	\N	Integration / Validation	IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Architectural validation initiative executed to compare and confirm EPS Fallback behavior across Rx and N5 implementation paths within the IoT lab environment. The observed behavior required verification that SMF Γåö PCF Γåö CHF signaling and fallback procedures aligned correctly under both Rx-based and N5-based policy interaction models. Expected behavior was full architectural consistency between lab-validated fallback sequences and production-grade design expectations, ensuring IoT service continuity under EPS Fallback conditions. The technical context involved end-to-end validation of SMF, PCF, and charging interaction flows, with specific focus on the coexistence of legacy Rx and 5GC-native N5 interfaces. The affected flow spans the E2E EPS Fallback path including SMF ΓåÆ PCF policy binding, CHF charging interaction, and Rx/N5 signaling convergence within IoT service scenarios.	Validation activities have been successfully completed and the ticket is closed. Architecture and signaling behavior alignment was confirmed across SMF, PCF, charging interactions, and EPS Fallback procedures. Testing confirmed that EPS Fallback behavior operated correctly under validated scenarios for both Rx and N5 paths. During the investigation, a root cause was identified: the CHF offshore team inadvertently removed the 311180 PLMN configuration from Azure-CHF_E2E01 (107.121.213.16) during a deployment change, which introduced a disruption requiring correction. Once the configuration was restored, full architectural alignment was achieved and the validation was completed successfully. No outstanding issues remain.	Architecture Validation & IoT Enablement Risk ΓÇö Critical architectural validation for IoT environments requiring precise alignment between lab and production policy/charging models. Failure to validate EPS Fallback behavior across Rx and N5 paths would have introduced significant risk to future IoT production onboarding scenarios and undermined confidence in fallback behavior continuity. The inadvertent PLMN removal further highlighted the fragility of configuration governance during deployment changes.	Isolated root cause of PLMN misconfiguration introduced by CHF offshore deployment, preventing prolonged diagnostic cycles across multiple teams. Validated architectural alignment between Rx and N5 EPS Fallback implementations, eliminating ambiguity in fallback behavior and establishing a reusable baseline for future IoT onboarding. Prevented future rework by confirming architectural assumptions early in the integration lifecycle. Enabled cross-domain confidence across SMF, PCF, and CHF teams by delivering a validated reference model for production-grade fallback behavior.	Preserve validated findings as the architectural baseline for future EPS Fallback validations across IoT and production environments. Reuse confirmed Rx vs N5 behavior patterns for upcoming IoT onboarding and integration scenarios. Continue alignment efforts between lab and production charging/policy models to ensure configuration parity. Implement configuration governance controls to prevent unauthorized PLMN removal during CHF deployment changes. No further action required on this specific ticket.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and architecture impact ΓÇö This initiative directly de-risks IoT production onboarding by establishing a validated architectural baseline for EPS Fallback behavior across Rx and N5 interfaces. The early detection of the PLMN misconfiguration reinforces the need for configuration governance during cross-domain deployments, contributing to platform resiliency and release certification readiness for IoT service scenarios.	EPS Fallback behavior was validated as architecturally consistent across both Rx and N5 policy interaction models within the IoT lab environment. During validation, the CHF offshore team inadvertently removed the 311180 PLMN from Azure-CHF_E2E01 (107.121.213.16) during a deployment change, introducing a configuration disruption. The root cause was a configuration-layer issue ΓÇö not an application or infrastructure defect. Once the PLMN was restored, SMF ΓåÆ PCF ΓåÆ CHF signaling and fallback procedures operated as expected under both Rx-based and N5-based paths. This confirms that the EPS Fallback architecture is sound, but highlights a governance gap in deployment change management for CHF configurations.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{CHF,PCF,SMF}		f	2026-05-27 20:49:57.211998+00	2026-05-27 20:49:57.211998+00	f	Root cause confirmed: CHF offshore team inadvertently removed the 311180 PLMN configuration from Azure-CHF_E2E01 (107.121.213.16) during a deployment change. Once the PLMN was restored, EPS Fallback behavior across Rx and N5 paths validated successfully with full architectural alignment.
