itiatives, enabling executive-level trend analysis and strategic prioritization. Accelerated QBR preparation by maintaining real-time traceability across all network functions and problem domains. Prevented misclassification and duplication of efforts by enforcing consistent RCA evolution methodology, ownership governance, and impact categorization across every tracked initiative from Task ID 2026-01-20-0049 through end of March 2026.	1. Continue cataloging all new platform initiatives through March 31, 2026 with full field completion and executive narrative transformation. 2. Perform quarterly trend analysis across problem types, network functions, and resolution timelines to identify systemic risks. 3. Prepare 1Q 2026 QBR executive summary with strategic relevance mapping and key technical insights aggregated from all individual initiatives. 4. Identify top recurring root causes and recommend preventive actions for 2Q 2026 planning. 5. Validate governance accuracy ΓÇö confirm led_by and tier1_involvement fields reflect actual ownership for all tracked initiatives.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö This master historical registry is a TPM-owned governance artifact maintained exclusively by C├⌐sar Villagra for executive reporting and strategic program management purposes.	Cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö This master registry directly supports quarterly business review readiness, platform resiliency trend analysis, and architecture impact assessment. It provides the foundational data layer for all strategic decisions regarding release certification readiness, OEM onboarding enablement, observability readiness, charging platform integrity, and infrastructure stabilization across the entire 1Q 2026 portfolio.	The master historical task registry for 1Q 2026 is not a single technical investigation but rather the aggregated intelligence layer across all network functions and problem domains. Its value lies in surfacing cross-domain patterns that individual tickets cannot reveal ΓÇö such as recurring infrastructure connectivity issues on specific FEXN paths, systematic observability gaps in the CHF ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain, or repeated failover behaviors in BSF ΓåÆ PCF flows that are consistently validated as working-as-designed. The registry enables the TPM to distinguish between systemic platform defects requiring architectural intervention and transient or configuration-level issues that can be addressed through operational tuning, preventing unnecessary escalations and focusing engineering resources on genuinely impactful root causes.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{CHF,PCF,SMF,UPF,UDM,BSF,SBC,ACC,Kafka,Cookies,HSS,CNRO,Infrastructure,FEXN,GLS,ISBUS}		t	2026-05-26 18:14:50.750667+00	2026-05-26 20:20:09.133527+00	f	\N
3	1	3	2026-01-20-00003	CTAP-42746	2026-01-20	\N	Integration / Validation	IoT Lab Environment	Closed	End-to-end architectural validation initiative comparing EPS Fallback behavior across Rx (Diameter-based) and N5 (SBI-based) signaling interfaces within the IoT Lab environment. The objective was to validate whether EPS Fallback procedures ΓÇö triggered when a UE transitions from 5GC to EPC ΓÇö behave consistently across both legacy Rx and converged N5 implementations. This validation is critical to ensure that policy-driven session handling (PCF-originated rules via N5) and legacy PCRF-driven Rx interactions produce equivalent fallback outcomes. The affected flow spans the UE ΓåÆ gNB ΓåÆ AMF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ PCF (N5) path versus the UE ΓåÆ eNB ΓåÆ MME ΓåÆ PGW ΓåÆ PCRF (Rx) path, with focus on how session continuity and QoS policy adherence are maintained during inter-RAT mobility events in IoT-optimized network slices.	Validation activities have been completed and the initiative is now closed. The lab team executed a structured comparison of EPS Fallback behavior between Rx and N5 signaling paths within the IoT Lab environment. Architecture and behavior alignment activities confirmed that the N5-based EPS Fallback implementation in the lab mirrors production-expected behavior. Key findings include: (1) EPS Fallback triggers consistently across both Rx and N5 for the validated IoT use cases; (2) QoS policy adherence during inter-RAT handover was confirmed for both signaling interfaces; (3) No discrepancies were identified between lab behavior and production architectural expectations. The RCA classification is working-as-designed ΓÇö both implementations align with 3GPP-compliant EPS Fallback procedures, and the lab configuration accurately reflects the target production architecture.	Release Certification Risk ΓÇö This validation was a critical architectural gate for IoT environment readiness. Failure to confirm behavioral parity between Rx and N5 EPS Fallback implementations would have introduced ambiguity into production deployment decisions, potentially delaying IoT platform certification and creating risk for inter-RAT mobility in live traffic scenarios. Successful completion removes a key dependency from the IoT production readiness milestone.	Eliminated architectural ambiguity around EPS Fallback behavior parity between Rx and N5 signaling interfaces, enabling confident production readiness decisions for IoT environments. Established a validated behavioral baseline that can be reused for future regression and certification cycles, reducing future validation effort and cycle time. Prevented potential misclassification of implementation differences as defects by confirming design-compliant behavior across both interfaces. Accelerated cross-domain alignment between lab validation teams and production architecture stakeholders, ensuring that IoT deployment planning proceeds on validated technical foundations rather than assumptions.	1. Archive validated EPS Fallback behavioral baseline (Rx vs N5 comparison matrix) as a reference artifact for future IoT regression and certification cycles. 2. Distribute findings to production architecture and deployment teams to confirm lab-to-production alignment is documented and traceable. 3. Leverage validated baseline to accelerate any future EPS Fallback regression testing triggered by PCF or SMF software upgrades in IoT environments. 4. Monitor for any 3GPP specification updates that may alter EPS Fallback procedures and trigger re-validation against this established baseline.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Architecture impact ΓÇö This initiative directly validates the architectural parity between legacy Diameter-based (Rx) and SBI-based (N5) EPS Fallback implementations, which is foundational for IoT production readiness. The validated baseline de-risks future production deployment decisions and establishes a reusable certification artifact. This is a key enabler for release certification readiness and OEM onboarding enablement in IoT-optimized network environments, ensuring that inter-RAT mobility behavior is validated and traceable before production traffic is onboarded.	EPS Fallback behavior was confirmed to be functionally equivalent across both Rx (Diameter/PCRF-driven) and N5 (SBI/PCF-driven) signaling paths within the IoT Lab environment. The validation confirmed that inter-RAT mobility from 5GC to EPC preserves QoS policy adherence and session continuity regardless of which signaling interface mediates the fallback. No behavioral divergence was detected ΓÇö both implementations are working as designed per 3GPP EPS Fallback specifications. The critical insight is that the lab architecture accurately mirrors production expectations, meaning this environment can serve as a trusted validation baseline for future IoT certification activities. No application, infrastructure, or configuration defects were identified; the outcome is a clean architectural alignment confirmation.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	working_as_designed	{PCF,SMF}		t	2026-05-26 18:15:18.664748+00	2026-05-27 15:08:50.375824+00	f	\N
146	1	3	2026-04-05-00149	CTAP-74344	2026-04-05	\N	Charging / CHF / PCF / ACC Visibility	Darkstar ΓÇô Line Up 4 | Instance: rd2wa65 | Rivian DNN: rvtech-core-5g	Closed	Charging visibility disruption identified in the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain affecting the Rivian DNN rvtech-core-5g in Darkstar Line Up 4. Observed behavior: charging flows from SMF completed successfully through CHF, but no usage information was reflected in ACC (Control Center), creating a full observability gap for Rivian charging validation. Expected behavior: CDRs generated by CHF should be streamed via Kafka and rendered visible in ACC for OEM charging verification. Technical context: the E2E charging path spans SMF (rdmwa65esme01 eSMF) ΓåÆ CHF (107.121.213.16) ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC. Investigation scope encompassed PCF charging configuration, CHF processing, CDR generation, Kafka streaming, and ACC integration layers. Affected flow: Rivian OEM E2E charging validation including APP ID verification, charging visibility checks, and end-to-end charging observability.	Issue fully resolved and ticket formally closed. Investigation confirmed the SMF ΓåÆ CHF charging path was operational, with usage reporting from rdmwa65esme01 eSMF toward CHF (107.121.213.16) completing successfully. This narrowed the root cause downstream from CHF. Two contributing conditions were identified and remediated: (1) PCF Configuration Issue ΓÇö Tushar identified that Rivian charging configuration in PCF was incorrectly set to Offline instead of Online; correction was applied to rd2wa65 cpcf1 and rd2wa65 cpcf2. (2) CHF Kafka Integration Issue ΓÇö a Kafka integration problem within the CHF environment prevented CDR forwarding and delivery toward ACC. After both corrections were applied, ACC visibility was restored successfully and Rivian validation activities completed. Charging visibility behavior confirmed correct post-remediation.	Charging Visibility Loss | OEM Enablement Risk | E2E Flow Disruption. The issue directly impacted ACC charging visibility for the Rivian DNN, blocking OEM charging validation activities. E2E charging observability was disrupted, preventing confirmation of correct charging behavior for Rivian-specific APP IDs. OEM validation continuity was at risk until both root causes were addressed and ACC reporting was restored.	Isolated root cause across multiple domains by differentiating PCF charging configuration behavior from downstream CHF Kafka streaming failures. Validated the SMF ΓåÆ CHF charging path as operational, effectively eliminating SMF and application-layer charging as investigation targets. Identified incorrect PCF charging mode (Offline vs. Online) as a contributing factor and isolated the primary reporting failure to the CHF Kafka integration layer. Accelerated restoration by enabling parallel remediation of PCF configuration and Kafka integration. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward SMF, application-layer charging, or ACC domains, saving cross-team investigation cycles and preserving OEM validation timelines.	No additional actions required. PCF charging mode corrected successfully on rd2wa65 cpcf1 and rd2wa65 cpcf2. CHF Kafka integration issue resolved. ACC visibility restored and validated. Rivian OEM charging validation activities completed successfully. Ticket closed.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Directly supports Rivian OEM charging validation and onboarding enablement. Demonstrates cross-domain RCA capability spanning PCF configuration, CHF Kafka integration, and ACC visibility layers. Highlights the critical dependency on CHF Kafka integration for end-to-end charging observability. Improves organizational understanding of Online vs. Offline charging configuration impacts within PCF. Contributes to charging observability stabilization and platform integrity for OEM certification readiness.	Cross-domain charging visibility issue with dual root causes. The SMF ΓåÆ CHF charging path was validated as fully operational (rdmwa65esme01 eSMF ΓåÆ CHF 107.121.213.16), confirming the failure existed downstream. Contributing factor: PCF charging configuration for Rivian was incorrectly set to Offline instead of Online on rd2wa65 cpcf1 and rd2wa65 cpcf2 ΓÇö corrected by Tushar. Primary root cause: CHF Kafka integration issue prevented CDR forwarding to ACC, meaning charging records were generated but never streamed to the visibility layer. The combination of a configuration-layer defect (PCF) and an observability-layer failure (CHF Kafka) created a compound visibility gap that required multi-domain analysis to resolve. Classification: cross-domain charging visibility issue spanning configuration and observability layers.	Tier 1	t	configuration	{CHF,PCF,SMF,ACC,Kafka}		f	2026-05-27 21:03:48.764261+00	2026-05-27 21:03:48.764261+00	f	Root cause confirmed: dual contributing factors caused ACC visibility loss for Rivian DNN rvtech-core-5g. PCF charging configuration was incorrectly set to Offline instead of Online on rd2wa65 cpcf1 and rd2wa65 cpcf2, and a concurrent CHF Kafka integration issue prevented CDR forwarding to ACC. Both issues were remediated, restoring full charging visibility and completing Rivian OEM validation.
7	1	3	2026-01-20-00007	CTAP-45723	2026-01-20	\N	Validation / Testing	IoT Labs	Closed	IoT validation continuity initiative requiring cross-team coordination to sustain ongoing test execution cycles. Observed behavior indicated potential fragmentation in validation workflows across multiple teams operating within the IoT Labs environment. Expected behavior demanded seamless, uninterrupted validation execution aligned with scheduled test cycles. Technical context involved coordination of IoT-specific network functions and lab infrastructure to ensure end-to-end validation coverage. Affected flow encompassed the full IoT validation pipeline, from test case orchestration through execution and results consolidation across distributed team domains.	Validation activities have been successfully completed and the ticket is now closed. Cross-team coordination was identified as the primary challenge impacting execution continuity. Troubleshooting and alignment efforts focused on synchronizing validation procedures across participating teams to eliminate scheduling conflicts and dependency gaps. RCA evolution confirmed that the disruption risk was not due to a technical defect but rather to process-level fragmentation in multi-team validation orchestration. After coordination interventions and targeted re-testing, all validation cycles were completed as planned with no residual issues. Final outcome: validation continuity fully maintained with no test cycle losses.	Release Certification Risk ΓÇö Disruption of IoT validation cycles threatened to delay certification readiness by fragmenting test execution across teams, potentially introducing gaps in validation coverage and impacting downstream release timelines.	Enabled cross-domain coordination between IoT validation teams, preventing execution fragmentation and preserving scheduled test cycle integrity. Accelerated resolution by identifying process-level coordination gaps rather than pursuing unnecessary technical root cause investigations. Ensured release certification readiness by maintaining uninterrupted validation continuity across the IoT Labs environment. Established procedural baseline for future multi-team validation cycles, reducing risk of recurrence.	Formalize and document validated coordination procedures as a repeatable playbook for future IoT validation cycles. Conduct lessons-learned review with participating teams to identify further optimization opportunities in cross-team orchestration. Integrate coordination checkpoints into standard IoT validation planning to proactively mitigate continuity risks in upcoming release cycles. Archive test results and coordination artifacts for traceability and audit readiness.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Release certification readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly safeguarded IoT validation continuity, a critical dependency for on-time release certification. Cross-team coordination gaps, if left unaddressed, would have introduced downstream schedule risk and coverage gaps impacting overall platform certification posture. The procedural improvements established through this effort strengthen organizational readiness for future multi-team validation campaigns.	The root cause of the continuity risk was not a technical defect in any specific network function or infrastructure layer, but rather a process-level coordination gap across multiple validation teams operating in the IoT Labs environment. No application, infrastructure, or configuration failures were identified. The resolution was achieved through structured cross-team alignment and re-testing, confirming that all IoT validation scenarios executed successfully once orchestration was synchronized. This case demonstrates the importance of treating multi-team validation coordination as a first-class risk vector in lab environments, particularly during high-density test cycles where team dependencies can silently fragment execution continuity.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	conf