5	1	3	2026-01-20-00005	CTAP-44334	2026-01-20	\N	POLICY / PCF	IoT Lab	Closed	Policy enforcement behavior was observed to deviate from expected norms during charging interaction validation in the IoT Lab environment. The observed behavior indicated potential inconsistencies in how PCF policy decisions propagated through downstream charging flows, specifically within the PCF ΓåÆ CHF interaction path. Expected behavior required seamless policy-driven charging enforcement with consistent session-level attributes being honored across the E2E policy-to-charging chain. Technical investigation focused on validating the PCF policy output and its downstream effect on CHF charging logic, ensuring that policy rules were correctly translated into charging instructions without data loss or misinterpretation. The affected flow encompasses the PCF policy decision point through to CHF charging enforcement, including any intermediary signaling or session binding that bridges policy and charging domains.	Investigation has been completed and the ticket is closed. The troubleshooting effort initially focused on determining whether the observed charging inconsistency originated at the policy layer (PCF) or the charging layer (CHF). Through systematic isolation, the root cause was narrowed down to a configuration-level issue within the PCF policy framework that was producing unexpected policy outputs under specific session conditions. Infrastructure and application-layer defects were ruled out early in the investigation. After targeted configuration adjustments were applied to the PCF policy rules, retesting confirmed that policy decisions were being correctly enforced and that downstream charging behavior normalized. The RCA was finalized as a configuration gap at the policy layer, not a software defect or infrastructure failure. Full regression validation was completed, confirming stable E2E policy-to-charging flow behavior post-fix.	Policy Routing Issue | Charging Impact ΓÇö The policy enforcement deviation introduced risk of charging inconsistency in the IoT Lab environment, potentially undermining the integrity of policy-driven charging flows. If left unresolved, this could have propagated incorrect charging behavior during broader E2E validation cycles and delayed release certification readiness for policy-charging integration scenarios.	Isolated root cause to the PCF policy configuration layer, preventing unnecessary escalation to the CHF charging domain and avoiding cross-domain troubleshooting overhead. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope exclusively to policy enforcement logic. Validated that charging infrastructure was operating correctly, thereby preserving confidence in CHF platform integrity. Enabled targeted configuration remediation that restored policy-to-charging flow stability without requiring application-level code changes or infrastructure intervention.	Continue monitoring policy-to-charging interaction consistency across subsequent IoT Lab test cycles to confirm sustained stability. Validate that the configuration adjustments applied to PCF policy rules do not introduce regressions in adjacent policy scenarios. Document the configuration gap and remediation steps as a reference for future PCF deployments. Include this finding in the policy configuration baseline review to prevent recurrence in pre-production and production environments.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Charging platform integrity and cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö This initiative validated the critical interface between policy enforcement (PCF) and charging execution (CHF) in the IoT Lab. Ensuring policy-to-charging consistency at the configuration level is foundational for release certification readiness and OEM onboarding enablement, as any policy-driven charging deviation would directly undermine platform trustworthiness in production scenarios.	The root cause was a configuration gap within the PCF policy framework that produced unexpected policy outputs under specific IoT session conditions, leading to downstream charging inconsistency at the CHF layer. The CHF application and infrastructure layers were confirmed to be operating correctly ΓÇö the defect was entirely isolated to the PCF configuration plane. This was not a software defect or infrastructure failure, but a configuration-level issue that was resolved through targeted policy rule adjustments. Post-fix retesting confirmed that the PCF ΓåÆ CHF interaction path was fully restored, with policy decisions correctly translating into charging enforcement. The key learning is that policy configuration baselines must be validated holistically against all session types prior to E2E charging integration testing.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{PCF,CHF}		t	2026-05-26 18:16:09.761941+00	2026-05-27 15:08:45.637915+00	f	\N
6	1	3	2026-01-20-00006	CTAP-44776	2026-01-20	2026-02-27	Authentication / Enterprise	Enterprise PODs	Closed	CHAP (Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol) authentication is not currently supported for specific Enterprise SMF/UPF DNN configurations on the AT&T 5G SA NR RAN platform. The expected behavior is that enterprise customer devices requesting CHAP-based authentication should be able to successfully authenticate and attach through the designated Enterprise DNN. However, the current platform configuration only supports alternative authentication mechanisms, creating a gap for enterprise customers whose devices are configured to negotiate CHAP. The affected E2E flow spans from the NR RAN ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ UPF path within Enterprise PODs, where the DNN-specific authentication negotiation fails to complete when CHAP is requested by the customer equipment. Platform planning has identified that the strategic migration path to Aqua-based Enterprise PODs will address this authentication protocol gap as all Enterprise PODs are eventually launched or converted to the Aqua architecture.	Investigation has confirmed that CHAP authentication is not supported on the current Enterprise SMF/UPF DNN configuration within the 5G SA NR RAN environment. The limitation is isolated to specific Enterprise POD configurations where customer devices negotiate CHAP during the authentication phase. Platform architecture planning has determined that all Enterprise PODs are on a trajectory to be either newly launched or converted to the Aqua platform, which will natively support CHAP authentication. The current scope of impact is confined to the on-going specific Enterprise SMF/UPF DNN where customer devices are configured to use CHAP. RCA assessment indicates this is a configuration and architecture-level limitation rather than a software defect ΓÇö the existing platform was not designed to accommodate CHAP for these specific DNN profiles. The resolution path is aligned with the broader Aqua migration strategy rather than a retroactive fix on the legacy Enterprise POD architecture.\n[Update 05/26/26] As per Moqu Li on 04/20/26: "We can see the ePCO encapsulated within PDU 5GS PDU into SMF having the CHAP. And later to AMF we saw SMF included the mDNS IP addresses by SMF. We shall be good on existing DS E/// SMFs so we can conclude that E/// SMF does not have the same issue as MSFT SMFs." As per Vinothkumar Kamalanathan this Jira can now be closed.	Enterprise Onboarding Limitation ΓÇö The absence of CHAP authentication support on the current Enterprise POD architecture creates a direct onboarding blocker for enterprise customers whose devices are configured to negotiate CHAP. This restricts the addressable market for 5G SA enterprise services and introduces a dependency on the Aqua migration timeline for enabling these customers. The limitation affects the SMF/UPF DNN authentication flow and poses an OEM Enablement Risk for enterprise device ecosystems that default to CHAP-based authentication.	Identified and validated the architectural root cause of the CHAP authentication gap, preventing misclassification as a software defect and avoiding unnecessary troubleshooting cycles on the existing platform. Established the strategic onboarding path for CHAP-dependent enterprise customers through alignment with the Aqua Enterprise POD migration roadmap. Enabled cross-domain visibility between enterprise onboarding, authentication architecture, and platform evolution planning, ensuring that the limitation is tracked as a known architecture constraint with a defined resolution trajectory rather than an open-ended defect.	1. Continue alignment and tracking of Aqua Enterprise POD migration timeline to ensure CHAP authentication support is included in the Aqua DNN configuration baseline. 2. SMF/UPF team to validate that Aqua-based Enterprise PODs natively support CHAP authentication negotiation for the target DNNs. 3. Enterprise onboarding team to maintain registry of