49	1	3	02/04/2026-00049	CTAP-45933	2026-02-04	\N	ACC / Visibility	ACC / Control Center / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Charging visibility disruption identified across the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center reporting chain during IoT validation activities. Session visibility and charging reporting inconsistencies were observed, where charging signaling appeared partially successful but corresponding records were either incomplete or absent in ACC and Control Center downstream platforms. The issue impacted the ability to correctly visualize session information, validate charging records, and confirm usage reporting behavior end-to-end. Investigation scope encompassed multiple potential failure domains: charging record generation at the CHF layer, ACC ingestion pipeline integrity, reporting synchronization mechanisms, and downstream Control Center rendering. The affected E2E flow spans SMF session establishment ΓåÆ CHF charging record generation ΓåÆ ACC ingestion ΓåÆ Control Center visibility, with the root cause ultimately traced to a UPF IPPE layer dependency requiring reboot and PFD vector refresh inconsistency tied to a known platform version deficiency (Lab 8 running 5.1.0.15 versus the fix available in 5.1.0.18).	Investigation concluded and issue fully resolved. Initial observations indicated that charging signaling appeared partially successful, but corresponding visibility in ACC and Control Center was incomplete or inconsistent. Coordinated validation was conducted between SMF, CHF, ACC, and testing teams to systematically isolate whether charging records were being generated correctly, whether they were reaching downstream systems, and whether ACC ingestion and reporting behavior was functioning properly. Through structured domain isolation, the issue was narrowed away from CHF processing and ACC ingestion layers. Microsoft's root cause analysis confirmed the visibility disruption originated from a UPF IPPE condition requiring reboot and an inconsistent PFD vector refresh behavior, a known deficiency in platform version 5.1.0.15 that was resolved in version 5.1.0.18. Kiranmai performed retesting and confirmed that the Landing page was successfully displayed, session visibility was restored in Control Center, and no additional visibility inconsistencies were observed post-resolution.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Missing session and charging visibility in Control Center disrupted end-to-end IoT validation activities. Incomplete reporting reduced confidence in the charging and session visibility pipeline, creating a Critical Testing Blocker for IoT certification workflows. The inability to validate charging records downstream introduced delays in validation timelines and risked misclassification of the issue toward unrelated network functions (CHF, ACC) when the root cause resided at the UPF infrastructure layer.	Successfully isolated the root cause across multiple failure domains ΓÇö charging generation, downstream ingestion, and ACC visibility layers ΓÇö preventing unnecessary escalation toward CHF or ACC teams when the deficiency resided at the UPF IPPE layer. Accelerated root cause identification through structured domain isolation methodology, systematically ruling out CHF processing and ACC ingestion before converging on the UPF platform version dependency. Enabled cross-domain coordination between SMF, CHF, ACC, and Microsoft UPF teams, ensuring that troubleshooting efforts were directed toward the correct failure domain. Prevented misclassification of a UPF infrastructure deficiency as a charging or observability defect, preserving platform integrity confidence in the CHF ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain.	Continue monitoring ACC stability and ingestion behavior post-resolution to confirm sustained visibility integrity. Validate that Lab 8 UPF upgrade path to 5.1.0.18 or later is tracked to permanently resolve the PFD vector refresh inconsistency. Preserve troubleshooting findings and domain isolation methodology for reuse in future visibility-related investigations across IoT and charging validation workflows. Confirm with Microsoft that the IPPE reboot requirement is documented as a known operational consideration for environments running pre-5.1.0.18 UPF versions.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative validated the integrity of the end-to-end charging visibility pipeline (SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center) and confirmed that the reporting chain functions correctly when the underlying UPF infrastructure is at the required platform version. The structured domain isolation approach demonstrated cross-domain troubleshooting maturity, preventing unnecessary remediation efforts against charging or observability components. The findings reinforce platform resiliency awareness by identifying version-dependent UPF behaviors that directly impact downstream visibility and IoT validation certification readiness.	The visibility disruption was not caused by a defect in the charging generation (CHF), ACC ingestion pipeline, or Control Center reporting layer. The root cause was traced to a UPF IPPE condition in Lab 8 (running version 5.1.0.15) that required a reboot, combined with an inconsistent PFD vector refresh behavior ΓÇö a known deficiency resolved in UPF version 5.1.0.18. This meant that while charging signaling appeared partially successful at the CHF layer, the upstream UPF session context was not properly established, resulting in incomplete or absent records propagating downstream. The critical distinction is that the observability chain (CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center) was functioning as designed ΓÇö the failure originated at the infrastructure/application layer of the UPF, not within the visibility platform. After Kiranmai retested following the IPPE reboot, the Landing page displayed successfully and session visibility was fully restored, confirming the version-specific UPF dependency as the sole root cause.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	infra