116	1	3	2026-01-30-00119	CTAP-43572	2026-01-30	\N	CHARGING / CHF	IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Charging flow disruption identified during IoT validation activities impacting the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ downstream charging visibility reporting chain. Inconsistencies in charging continuity were observed across multiple IoT use cases, raising concerns about the integrity of the end-to-end charging path. The observed behavior included intermittent charging failures, incomplete transaction visibility in downstream reporting systems, and unstable charging session behavior during active validation execution. Expected behavior was seamless charging flow continuity from SMF signaling through CHF processing to downstream charging visibility platforms. Investigation scope encompassed SMF signaling integrity, CHF transaction processing, charging synchronization mechanisms, and downstream reporting pipeline stability to determine the originating domain of the disruption.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 02/02/2026. Root cause was confirmed: load testing activities on SMF pods generated an overload of charging transactions, which caused CHF to accumulate stale charging retries from expired sessions. This retry storm degraded CHF processing capacity and introduced intermittent charging inconsistencies and incomplete visibility in downstream reporting systems. Cross-functional troubleshooting across SMF, CHF, and validation teams successfully isolated the issue to SMF-originated transaction overload rather than a CHF application defect or downstream reporting failure. Resolution was achieved by coordinating with the SMF team to bounce the affected charging pods, which cleared the queued retries for obsolete sessions and restored normal charging flow behavior. Post-resolution retesting confirmed charging stability, full visibility recovery, and no residual blocking issues.	Charging Impact | E2E Flow Disruption | Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö Charging visibility inconsistencies disrupted IoT validation continuity, introduced delays in end-to-end testing execution, and reduced reliability of charging-related validations across the IoT Lab environment. The transaction overload scenario threatened to misclassify the issue as a CHF application defect, which would have triggered unnecessary escalation toward unrelated network domains.	Isolated root cause to SMF load-induced charging transaction overload, preventing misclassification as a CHF application defect or downstream reporting failure. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically narrowing investigation scope across SMF signaling, CHF processing, and downstream visibility domains. Enabled cross-domain coordination between SMF, CHF, and validation teams to execute targeted remediation (pod bounce) rather than broad platform intervention. Prevented premature and unnecessary escalation toward unrelated network domains by validating CHF processing integrity early in the investigation. Established reusable troubleshooting methodology for future charging overload scenarios in IoT validation environments.	Continue monitoring charging stability across IoT validation environments to confirm sustained resolution. Preserve troubleshooting findings and remediation playbook (pod bounce procedure for retry storm scenarios) for future CHF-related investigations. Evaluate SMF load testing procedures to implement safeguards that prevent charging transaction overload during concurrent validation activities. Reuse validated cross-domain troubleshooting approach for future charging flow investigations involving SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ downstream visibility path. Assess whether automated alerting can be implemented to detect charging retry accumulation patterns before they degrade CHF processing capacity.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Cross-functional troubleshooting coordination, root cause isolation, and remediation execution led by C├⌐sar Villagra across SMF, CHF, and validation teams.	Charging platform integrity ΓÇö This initiative validated the resilience of the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ downstream visibility charging chain under load stress conditions in the IoT Lab environment. The confirmed root cause (SMF load-induced transaction overload causing CHF retry storms) provides critical insight into charging platform behavior under stress, directly informing platform resiliency planning and IoT validation environment hardening. The established troubleshooting methodology and cross-domain coordination model strengthen operational readiness for future charging flow investigations.	Root cause was not a CHF application defect but an SMF-originated overload condition. Load testing activities on SMF pods generated excessive charging transactions that overwhelmed CHF processing capacity, causing stale session retries to accumulate and degrade charging flow integrity. The retry mechanism for expired sessions created a cascading effect that manifested as intermittent charging inconsistencies and incomplete downstream visibility ΓÇö symptoms that initially appeared to indicate a CHF processing or reporting failure. The critical differentiation was identifying that CHF was functioning correctly under normal load but was being overwhelmed by retry traffic from obsolete SMF sessions. Resolution required SMF-side intervention (pod bounce) to clear the retry queue, confirming the issue layer was infrastructure/operational rather than application logic. This pattern ΓÇö load-induced retry storms masquerading as application defects ΓÇö represents a reusable diagnostic framework for future charging platform investigations.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	infrastructure	{CHF,SMF}		f	2026-05-27 20:50:24.999173+00	2026-05-27 20:50:24.999173+00	f	Root cause confirmed: load testing activities on SMF pods caused an overload of charging transactions, generating stale session retries that degraded CHF processing capacity and disrupted downstream charging visibility. SMF team resolved the issue by bouncing the affected charging pods to clear accumulated retries for expired sessions, fully restoring charging flow stability.
147	1	3	05/06/2026-00150	CTAP-74959	2026-05-06	\N	CHARGING / CHF / ACC VISIBILITY	Northrim ΓÇô Lab 8 | All OEM DNNs | SMF / CHF / CCS / ACC / ISBUS	Closed	Platform-wide charging visibility disruption impacting all OEM DNNs in Northrim Lab 8, affecting the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ CCS ΓåÆ ISBUS ΓåÆ ACC downstream reporting chain. Observed behavior: Session information, usage records, and charging visibility were completely absent in ACC for all OEM DNNs including Honda, Rivian, and additional OEM validation environments. Charging traffic appeared to complete successfully at the CHF layer, but no downstream visibility was surfacing in ACC. Expected behavior: All charging session data generated by CHF should flow through Kafka output topics, traverse CCS integration, authenticate via ISBUS, and be ingested by ACC for full E2E charging observability across all OEM DNNs. Technical context: The investigation spanned multiple domains ΓÇö CHF charging generation, Kafka streaming layer, CCS integration path, ISBUS authentication layer, and ACC ingestion behavior ΓÇö to determine the exact point of failure in the downstream visibility chain. Affected flow: CHF ΓåÆ Kafka Output Topics ΓåÆ CCS ΓåÆ ISBUS Authentication ΓåÆ ACC Ingestion ΓåÆ OEM Charging Visibility.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed. Executive summary: Platform-wide charging visibility loss was reported across all OEM DNNs in Northrim Lab 8, with no session or usage data appearing in ACC. Troubleshooting progress: CCS/CHF team confirmed that charging generation and Kafka output topic population were functioning correctly, effectively ruling out the charging core and streaming layers as root cause. RCA evolution: (1) Initial scope included CHF, Kafka, CCS, ISBUS, and ACC ΓÇö all investigated in parallel. (2) CHF and Kafka were validated as healthy, narrowing the investigation to downstream integration. (3) Expired ISBUS client credentials were identified as the primary root cause ΓÇö new client secrets were generated and shared with ACC. (4) After credential update, Cisco still observed authentication failures post-application restart ΓÇö Cisco investigated and resolved the residual authentication issue independently. (5) After both corrections, ACC charging visibility was fully restored and all OEM E2E validation activities resumed normally. Key finding: The charging core was fully operational throughout ΓÇö the failure existed exclusively in the downstream authentication and integration layer between ISBUS and ACC.	Platform-Wide Charging Visibility Loss | All OEM E2E Validation Impacted | Charging Observability Disruption. The issue blocked ACC session visibility, charging observability, usage history validation, and E2E charging confirmation activities for all OEM DNNs in Lab 8 including Honda and Rivian. This represented a critical visibility loss across the entire Northrim Lab 8 charging platform, preventing any OEM validation activities from proceeding until downstream authentication was restored.	Successfully isolated the root cause beyond the charging core by systematically validating that CHF charging generation was functioning correctly and Kafka output topics were properly populated, confirming the failure existed exclusively within downstream authentication and integration components. This targeted investigation avoided unnecessary escalation toward SMF/PCF charging logic teams, preventing misallocation of engineering resources across multiple domains. Identified expired ISBUS client credentials as the primary root cause and accelerated cross-domain coordination across CCS, CHF, Cisco, ISBUS, and ACC teams to drive parallel resolution. Significantly narrowed the RCA scope from a five-domain investigation to a single authentication layer issue, restoring platform-wide charging observability and enabling all OEM validation activities to resume.	No additional actions required. Authentication issues resolved successfully ΓÇö expired ISBUS client credentials updated and Cisco authentication failure post-restart corrected. ACC visibility fully restored across all OEM DNNs. OEM E2E validation activities resumed normally in Northrim Lab 8. Ticket closed as of 05/07/2026.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Supports platform-wide charging observability stabilization by resolving a systemic visibility gap impacting all OEM DNNs. Demonstrates cross-domain RCA analysis capability spanning CHF, Kafka, CCS, ISBUS, and ACC layers. Highlights critical dependency on ISBUS authentication and credential lifecycle management for downstream charging visibility. Improves ACC visibility troubleshooting governance by establishing a validated isolation methodology that distinguishes charging generation health from downstream integration failures. Reinforces the architectural distinction between charging generation layer and downstream visibility/authentication layer ΓÇö a key insight for platform resiliency and future incident triage.	The investigation validated that CHF charging generation and Kafka output topic population were fully operational, confirming the charging core was healthy throughout the incident. The primary root cause was identified as expired ISBUS client credentials ΓÇö the client ID/password configured on ISBUS had expired, breaking the authentication chain required for ACC to ingest charging data. After new client secrets were generated and shared with ACC, a secondary contributing factor emerged: Cisco observed persistent authentication failures after application restart, which Cisco investigated and resolved independently. Impacted domains spanned CHF streaming, CCS integration, ISBUS authentication, and the ACC visibility layer. The critical architectural insight is that the downstream visibility chain (ISBUS auth ΓåÆ ACC ingestion) operates as a separate failure domain from the charging core (CHF ΓåÆ Kafka), and credential expiration in the authentication layer can cause complete platform