117	1	3	02/02/2026-00120	CTAP-44334	2026-02-02	\N	POLICY / PCF	IoT Lab Environment	Closed	A policy and charging interaction inconsistency was identified within the IoT Lab environment, involving the PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ CHF execution chain. Observed behavior indicated that policy decisions generated by the PCF were not correctly aligned with expected downstream charging execution, resulting in charging rule mismatches and runtime behavior deviations during IoT flow validations. Expected behavior required proper policy enforcement at the PCF layer, consistent charging triggering across the SMF path, and full alignment between policy logic and runtime charging execution. The technical investigation spanned the PCF policy configuration, SMF session management, UDR provisioning data, and charging interaction dependencies, with the objective of determining whether the root cause resided in the policy logic layer, charging execution layer, or upstream provisioning domain. The affected E2E flow encompassed the UDR ΓåÆ PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ CHF charging and policy enforcement path for IoT service scenarios.	Issue has been resolved and the ticket is closed as of 09/02/2026. Cross-domain validation activities were coordinated between PCF, SMF, and charging-related domains to systematically isolate the source of the inconsistency. Initial troubleshooting ruled out CHF-side and core charging domain defects, narrowing the investigation scope from a broad multi-domain issue to a specific upstream provisioning problem. The RCA evolution progressed from suspected PCF configuration or policy logic defect, through charging interaction dependency analysis, ultimately converging on a UDR provisioning data issue as the confirmed root cause. After the UDR provisioning correction was applied, policy flow was re-validated end-to-end, charging behavior normalized, and no additional inconsistencies were observed during comprehensive re-testing cycles.	Charging Impact | Policy Routing Issue | E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö The inconsistency between policy application and charging triggering posed a direct risk to charging integrity for IoT validation scenarios. Incorrect runtime behavior during policy enforcement threatened downstream charging visibility, service continuity, and the reliability of IoT lab validation outcomes. Without resolution, the issue carried potential to delay IoT onboarding certification and undermine confidence in the policy-to-charging execution chain within the lab environment.	Successfully isolated the root cause to the UDR provisioning layer, preventing unnecessary escalation toward CHF and core charging domains that would have consumed cross-team engineering cycles without resolution. Improved troubleshooting accuracy by systematically differentiating between policy logic defects, runtime behavioral anomalies, and charging execution failures ΓÇö enabling precise domain isolation. Accelerated validation cycles through structured cross-domain coordination between PCF, SMF, and charging teams, reducing mean time to resolution. Established validated configuration baselines and documented troubleshooting findings reusable for future IoT policy-related investigations and onboarding activities.	Continue validation of policy consistency across expanded IoT scenarios to confirm no residual inconsistencies exist beyond the corrected provisioning scope. Preserve and catalog troubleshooting findings and RCA documentation for future policy-related investigations as a knowledge base artifact. Reuse validated UDR provisioning and PCF configuration baselines for upcoming IoT onboarding activities to prevent recurrence of similar provisioning misalignment. Coordinate with UDR provisioning team to establish a provisioning verification checkpoint in the IoT onboarding workflow to mitigate upstream data quality risks.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Cross-domain troubleshooting, RCA isolation, and validation coordination were driven end-to-end by C├⌐sar Villagra across PCF, SMF, UDR, and charging domains.	Charging platform integrity and OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This initiative validated the end-to-end policy-to-charging execution chain within the IoT Lab environment, directly supporting IoT onboarding certification readiness. The resolution reinforced provisioning data quality as a critical dependency for platform resiliency and established reusable troubleshooting baselines that strengthen cross-domain stabilization for future IoT service validations.	Root cause was confirmed at the UDR provisioning layer, not within PCF policy logic or CHF charging execution as initially suspected. The UDR provisioning data was not configured as required, causing the PCF to generate policy decisions based on incorrect subscriber profile attributes, which propagated downstream as charging rule mismatches and runtime behavior deviations across the PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ CHF path. The PCF policy engine, SMF session management, and CHF charging execution were all operating correctly given the data they received ΓÇö the defect was upstream in the provisioning domain. This distinction is critical: the application and infrastructure layers were working as designed, and the issue was purely a configuration/provisioning data quality problem. After UDR provisioning was corrected, the entire policy and charging flow stabilized without any code or configuration changes to the NFs themselves.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{PCF,SMF,CHF,UDR}		f	2026-05-27 20:50:53.658796+00	2026-05-27 20:50:53.658796+00	f	Root cause confirmed: UDR provisioning data was not configured as required, causing misaligned policy decisions at the PCF layer that propagated as charging inconsistencies across the PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ CHF execution chain. Issue resolved after UDR provisioning was corrected, with full policy flow stabilization and normalized charging behavior confirmed through end-to-end re-testing.
148	1	3	05/07/2026-00151	CTAP-75206	2026-05-07	\N	POLICY / BSF / PCF	Darkstar ΓÇô Line Up 4 | BSF / PCF | rdmwa25 / RD2WA65 | Policy Discovery & Routing	Closed	BSF-driven PCF discovery behavior investigation in Darkstar Line Up 4. The BSF returned rdmwa25 PCF instead of the expected RD2WA65 PCF during policy establishment flows, raising concerns about potential PCF binding inconsistency, BSF routing defect, or locality misconfiguration. The investigation was scoped to validate whether this represented a genuine PCF discovery failure or an expected failover/fallback mechanism within the Darkstar architecture. The affected E2E flow involved BSF ΓåÆ PCF discovery ΓåÆ policy establishment routing, where the BSF selects the appropriate PCF instance based on binding, locality, and availability. The expected behavior was for BSF to route to RD2WA65 PCF as the preferred instance; the observed behavior was BSF routing to rdmwa25 PCF as an alternate available instance due to the preferred PCF being suspended.	Investigation concluded and ticket closed. Initial observations flagged a potential PCF discovery anomaly when Darkstar Line Up 4 BSF consistently returned rdmwa25 PCF instead of RD2WA65 PCF. Collaborative validation with SMF support confirmed that the preferred PCF instance (RD2WA65) was in a suspended state. When the preferred PCF became unavailable, BSF automatically selected another available PCF instance (rdmwa25) containing equivalent configuration. Further validation confirmed that locality had been correctly assigned since Day 1 and that this behavior aligned with the overall Darkstar project design. The RCA evolution progressed from suspected PCF binding defect ΓåÆ suspected BSF routing defect ΓåÆ suspected locality misconfiguration ΓåÆ confirmed working-as-designed failover behavior. Test case execution continued successfully with policy establishment maintained through the alternate PCF, confirming routing continuity and platform operational stability. No service interruption or policy delivery failure was observed.	PCF Discovery / Failover Validation ΓÇö No Functional Service Impact. The anomaly generated initial confusion regarding expected PCF binding behavior but did not result in service interruption, policy establishment failure, or routing disruption. The platform maintained routing continuity, policy delivery integrity, and operational stability through automatic BSF failover behavior. Classification: No E2E flow disruption; behavior validated as design-compliant failover mechanism.	Successfully differentiated actual PCF discovery defects from expected BSF failover behavior, preventing unnecessary escalation toward BSF or PCF development teams. Validated platform resiliency mechanisms by confirming that BSF automatically routes to an equivalent alternate PCF instance when the preferred instance is unavailable. Confirmed locality configuration consistency since Day 1, eliminating configuration drift as a potential concern. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope from four potential root cause hypotheses to confirmed working-as-designed behavior. Improved cross-team understanding of Darkstar failover architecture, PCF selection logic, and operational troubleshooting governance for future incidents.	No additional actions required. Failover behavior validated successfully. BSF-driven PCF discovery and routing continuity confirmed as working as designed. Locality assignment verified as consistent since initial deployment. Ticket closed with full RCA documentation for future reference in Darkstar platform resiliency validation.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Validates BSF resiliency mechanisms and PCF failover continuity behavior within the Darkstar architecture. Confirms that BSF-driven PCF discovery logic correctly handles preferred instance unavailability through automatic alternate routing with equivalent configuration. Prevents false-positive escalation toward PCF discovery or BSF routing logic, preserving engineering bandwidth for genuine defects. Contributes to platform resiliency validation and improves operational troubleshooting governance for the Darkstar program. Directly supports cross-domain stabilization and release certification readiness by documenting validated failover behavior.	BSF returned rdmwa25 PCF instead of the expected RD2WA65 PCF in Darkstar Line Up 4. Root cause confirmed: the preferred PCF instance (RD2WA65) was in a suspended state. BSF automatically exercised its failover logic and selected another available PCF instance (rdmwa25) with equivalent configuration. Locality assignment was verified as correctly configured since Day 1, ruling out configuration drift. The alternate PCF path maintained full policy establishment and routing continuity ΓÇö test cases executed successfully without failure. The behavior was classified as working as designed, confirming that BSF failover architecture in Darkstar operates as intended when a preferred PCF instance becomes unavailable. The investigation validated three critical dimensions: locality assignment integrity, BSF failover selection logic, and PCF routing continuity under instance unavailability. No application, infrastructure, or configuration defect was identified. Impacted domains: BSF / PCF discovery and failover architecture.	Tier 1	t	working_as_designed	{BSF,PCF,SMF}		f	2026-05-27 21:04:46.507548+00	2026-05-27 21:04:46.507548+00	f	Root cause confirmed: preferred PCF instance RD2WA65 was in a suspended state. BSF automatically selected alternate PCF instance rdmwa25 with equivalent configuration, maintaining policy establishment and routing continuity. SMF support confirmed this behavior aligns with the overall Darkstar project design, with locality correctly assigned since Day 1. Classified as working as designed ΓÇö no defect identified.
15	1	3	2026-03-24-00015	CTAP-59373	2026-03-24	\N	SMS / ACC	ACC	In Progress	SMS Mobile-Terminated (MT) visibility disruption identified in the ACC reporting layer for the Ford OEM integration. While MO (Mobile-Originated) SMS transactions are being captured and displayed correctly within the ACC Control Center, MT SMS events are absent from the logging and reporting pipeline. Expected behavior is that both MO and MT SMS events are fully ingested, correlated, and visible in ACC for end-to-end SMS validation. The affected flow spans the SMS delivery path through to the ACC observability and ingestion chain, impacting the ability to certify complete SMS functionality for the Ford OEM onboarding.	Investigation is actively in progress with the following findings: MO SMS records are confirmed visible and correctly logged in ACC, establishing that the ACC ingestion pipeline is partially functional. However, MT SMS records are entirely absent from ACC logs, indicating a gap either in the MT event generation, event forwarding to ACC, or ACC-side ingestion filtering. The RCA has been narrowed from a broad SMS platform issue to a visibility-layer-specific problem, ruling out end-to-end SMS delivery failure. Current hypothesis centers on either a missing or misconfigured MT event source feeding into ACC, or an ingestion filter that is not capturing MT-type SMS events. Further validation is required on the ACC ingestion path and MT event publication chain.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Incomplete SMS validation for the Ford OEM integration due to missing MT SMS records in ACC. This gap prevents full certification of SMS functionality, creating an OEM Enablement Risk and a Release Certification Risk. Without MT visibility, the team cannot confirm successful SMS delivery to the subscriber, undermining confidence in E2E SMS flow integrity and delaying Ford onboarding milestones.	Isolated root cause to the ACC visibility and ingestion layer, eliminating unnecessary investigation into SMS delivery infrastructure. Accelerated troubleshooting by confirming MO path integrity early, narrowing the investigation scope exclusively to MT event capture and ACC ingestion. This targeted approach prevented unnecessary escalation to SMS platform teams and enabled focused cross-domain coordination between SMS and ACC observability teams.	1. Validate MT SMS event generation at the source ΓÇö confirm that MT events are being published to the expected Kafka topics or event streams. 2. Inspect ACC ingestion configuration for MT SMS event type filtering ΓÇö verify that MT event types are not being excluded by ingestion rules. 3. Cross-reference Kafka topic message counts for MT vs MO to determine if the gap is pre-ACC or within ACC processing. 4. Engage ACC platform team to review ingestion logs and identify any dropped or rejected MT records. 5. Upon resolution, execute full MO + MT SMS validation cycle for Ford and confirm both directions are visible in ACC Control Center. 6. Document findings for OEM onboarding certification evidence.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Observability readiness and OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö ensuring complete SMS visibility in ACC is critical for Ford OEM certification. This initiative directly supports charging platform integrity by validating that all billable SMS events (both MO and MT) are captured in the reporting layer, and reinforces cross-domain stabilization between SMS delivery and ACC observability systems.	The ACC observability layer is exhibiting a selective ingestion gap: MO SMS events are captured successfully while MT SMS events are entirely absent. This asymmetry points to a layer-specific issue in either the MT event publication chain (upstream of ACC) or ACC ingestion configuration (filtering or topic subscription), rather than a systemic SMS platform failure. The MO path functioning as expected confirms that the ACC pipeline itself is operational, isolating the defect to the MT event source or ACC MT-type event handling. Root cause hypothesis at this stage is a misconfigured or missing MT event feed into the ACC ingestion pipeline, potentially a Kafka topic subscription gap or an event-type filter excluding MT records.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{ACC,Kafka}		t	2026-05-26 18:20:35.662162+00	2026-05-27 15:08:23.727597+00	f	\N
13	1	3	2026-03-24-00013	CTAP-59151	2026-03-24	\N	CHARGING / ACC	Azure (Lab 8)	In Progress	Charging visibility disruption identified within the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain for Enterprise DNN d50012.etr (Honda). Sessions established on the Enterprise DNN are not generating visible usage or session information within the ACC (Amdocs Control Center), indicating a potential break in the end-to-end charging data pipeline. Expected behavior is that all sessions traversing the SMF trigger CDR generation at the CHF layer, which are subsequently ingested by the ACC platform for real-time visibility and reporting. The observed behavior suggests either CDR generation failure at the CHF level, a pipeline ingestion gap between CHF and ACC, or an ACC-side filtering/configuration issue specific to this Enterprise DNN. The affected E2E flow is: UE ΓåÆ SMF (Enterprise DNN d50012.etr) ΓåÆ CHF (CDR Generation) ΓåÆ ACC (Ingestion & Visibility).	Investigation is actively in progress to isolate the break point in the charging data pipeline for Enterprise DNN d50012.etr (Honda). Initial triage has confirmed that session information and usage data are absent from the ACC platform, indicating the charging flow between SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC is incomplete. A recurring ACC ingestion issue pattern has been identified, suggesting this may not be an isolated incident but rather a systemic gap in how Enterprise DNN CDRs are processed or forwarded. RCA is currently focused on two parallel tracks: (1) validating whether the CHF is generating CDRs for sessions on this specific DNN, and (2) assessing the ACC ingestion pipeline for filtering rules, DNN-specific configurations, or queue/topic-level issues that could prevent Enterprise DNN data from surfacing. SMF-side session establishment has not been ruled out but is considered lower probability given the DNN is operationally active.	Charging Impact | Visibility Loss ΓÇö Complete loss of session and usage visibility in ACC for Enterprise DNN d50012.etr (Honda). This directly affects charging observability for enterprise customer onboarding validation, blocks OEM/Enterprise certification testing that depends on ACC-based usage verification, and introduces risk to revenue assurance workflows that rely on accurate CDR-to-ACC pipeline integrity. If unresolved, this pattern could extend to other Enterprise DNNs, compounding the visibility gap across the charging platform.	Identified recurring ACC ingestion issue pattern, accelerating troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope to the CHF ΓåÆ ACC pipeline boundary rather than broad E2E diagnosis. Proactive pattern recognition enabled focused cross-domain coordination between CHF and ACC teams, preventing unnecessary escalation into SMF or network-layer investigations. Early isolation of the ingestion pattern positions the team to apply a systemic fix rather than a per-DNN workaround, improving long-term platform reliability.	1. Validate CDR generation at the CHF layer ΓÇö confirm whether CDRs are being produced for sessions on DNN d50012.etr by reviewing CHF transaction logs and CDR output directories. 2. Inspect ACC ingestion pipeline ΓÇö verify Kafka topic health, consumer group lag, and any DNN-specific filtering rules that may be suppressing Enterprise DNN records. 3. Cross-reference with known ACC ingestion issue pattern ΓÇö determine if this matches previously observed ingestion failures and whether the same root cause applies. 4. Engage CHF team to confirm CDR format compliance for Enterprise DNNs ΓÇö ensure no schema mismatch between CHF output and ACC ingestion expectations. 5. Engage ACC team to validate ingestion configuration for d50012.etr ΓÇö confirm DNN is registered and mapped correctly in ACC's data model. 6. Upon pipeline restoration, execute end-to-end retest with a controlled session on d50012.etr and confirm usage appears in ACC within expected SLA.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Charging platform integrity and Observability readiness ΓÇö This ticket directly impacts the ability to validate Enterprise DNN charging flows end-to-end, which is a prerequisite for OEM onboarding enablement and revenue assurance certification. A systemic ACC ingestion gap for Enterprise DNNs represents a platform-level observability risk that, if unresolved, undermines confidence in the charging data pipeline during QBR-level reporting and enterprise customer go-live readiness.	The break in visibility is localized to the CHF ΓåÆ ACC data pipeline for Enterprise DNN d50012.etr (Honda), with the most probable failure point being either CDR non-generation at the CHF layer for this specific DNN or an ACC ingestion pipeline issue (Kafka topic misconfiguration, consumer lag, or DNN-specific filtering). The identification of a recurring ACC ingestion issue pattern suggests this is not a one-off failure but a systemic gap in how Enterprise DNN charging records are propagated through the observability stack. The infrastructure and application layers (SMF session establishment, CHF processing) are presumed functional pending CDR generation validation ΓÇö making this primarily an observability-layer issue until further evidence shifts the RCA toward application or configuration root causes.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{SMF,CHF,ACC,Kafka}		t	2026-05-26 18:19:46.991109+00	2026-05-27 15:08:27.312897+00	f	\N
