cessary, narrowing the scope to platform architecture evolution.	Enterprise Onboarding Limitation ΓÇö CHAP authentication capability gap restricts onboarding for enterprise customers whose IoT devices and DNNs require CHAP-based authentication on AT&T 5G SA with NR RAN. This creates delays in validating specific Enterprise IoT use cases and introduces a dependency on the Aqua Enterprise POD migration roadmap for full remediation. The limitation affects the broader Enterprise IoT enablement strategy and certification readiness for CHAP-dependent customer segments.	Isolated root cause to a platform architecture limitation rather than a device, provisioning, or individual NF defect ΓÇö preventing unnecessary troubleshooting escalations across SMF, PCF, provisioning, and charging domains. Accelerated resolution path identification by framing the issue as an architecture evolution requirement tied to Aqua Enterprise POD migration. Enabled strategic alignment discussions across Enterprise POD planning teams to incorporate CHAP support into the Aqua migration roadmap. Defined future onboarding strategy for CHAP-dependent enterprise customers, ensuring clear expectation-setting and dependency tracking against the platform evolution timeline.	{"Continue alignment activities toward Aqua-based Enterprise POD deployment and conversion to ensure CHAP authentication support is included in the architecture baseline.","Monitor Enterprise POD evolution roadmap milestones and validate CHAP capability enablement as Aqua migrations are completed.","Re-evaluate and validate CHAP authentication support end-to-end once Aqua-based Enterprise PODs are operational in the target environments.","Support future Enterprise IoT customer onboarding validations requiring CHAP authentication, coordinating with SMF/UPF and Enterprise POD teams for E2E certification.","Document lessons learned and update onboarding playbook to flag CHAP authentication as a platform prerequisite tied to Aqua POD availability."}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and architecture impact ΓÇö this initiative directly affects the Enterprise IoT onboarding strategy on AT&T 5G SA. The identification of CHAP authentication as a platform architecture limitation rather than a point defect reframes the remediation as a strategic migration activity (Aqua Enterprise POD evolution) rather than a tactical fix. This has implications for Enterprise customer acquisition timelines, platform certification readiness, and the overall 5G SA Enterprise service portfolio maturity.	The CHAP authentication failure was not caused by any individual network function defect (SMF, PCF, UPF) or by a provisioning/configuration error. The root cause was a platform capability limitation inherent to the pre-Aqua Enterprise POD architecture model. Current Enterprise PODs operating on AT&T 5G SA with NR RAN lack the architectural support for CHAP authentication mechanisms required by specific Enterprise IoT DNNs. The remediation path is structural: all Enterprise PODs must be launched as or converted to Aqua-based environments to support CHAP. This distinction ΓÇö architecture limitation vs. NF defect ΓÇö is critical because it prevented misclassification and unnecessary multi-domain troubleshooting, and it correctly positioned the issue as a platform evolution dependency rather than an operational incident.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{SMF,UPF,PCF}		f	2026-05-27 20:51:22.872886+00	2026-05-27 20:51:22.872886+00	f	Root cause confirmed: CHAP authentication is not supported on current pre-Aqua Enterprise POD architecture operating on AT&T 5G SA with NR RAN. The limitation is structural to the Enterprise POD implementation model, not attributable to any individual NF, device, or provisioning defect. Remediation requires migration to Aqua-based Enterprise PODs, which are architecturally designed to support CHAP authentication mechanisms.
