defined (DS26.04 + enablement MOP), and architecture alignment discussions are actively ongoing to resolve the coexistence and migration strategy between observability models.	Observability Validation Blocked | Architecture Migration Decision Pending | Release Certification Risk. The absence of summary trace support in the current AON UDM release directly blocks UDM ΓåÆ BSA validation, observability readiness certification, and production migration planning. Downstream impacts include potential delays to Chicago and Detroit FFA testing timelines (targeted June/July), DS26.02 migration readiness, and the long-term observability architecture evolution for AON environments. Without resolution, the platform lacks validated UDM log-based troubleshooting capability, forcing continued reliance on probe-based observability and delaying the observability modernization roadmap.	Identified and elevated a critical observability dependency from a simple logging validation task into a strategic architecture discussion, ensuring executive visibility into the DS26.04 blocking dependency and its cascading impact on production migration planning. Accelerated stakeholder alignment by clearly separating short-term operational needs (probe-based FFA testing in Chicago/Detroit) from long-term architecture goals (UDM log-based observability migration). Enabled cross-domain coordination between UDM, BSA, and observability architecture teams, framing the migration path and coexistence strategy between probe-based and UDM log-based solutions. Prevented potential misalignment between DS26.02 migration activities and DS26.04 observability enablement timelines through proactive dependency mapping.	1. Await deployment of DS26.04 release in AON lab environments (Darkstar and Blackrim). 2. Execute enablement MOP post-DS26.04 deployment to activate summary trace capability as specified by Bic Nguyen. 3. Validate UDM summary trace log generation end-to-end. 4. Execute UDM ΓåÆ BSA integration testing