19	1	3	2026-03-24-00019	CTAP-60496	2026-03-24	\N	Charging / Policy	FN-IoT	Closed	Converged charging flow disruption identified in the SMF ΓåÆ CHF signaling path within the FN-IoT environment. No CreateConvergedCharging requests were being generated from the SMF following policy changes, raising concerns of a potential charging platform failure. Initial investigation targeted the core network domains (SMF, CHF, PCF) as possible sources of the failure. The affected E2E flow involves SMF-initiated converged charging session establishment toward CHF, which is critical for accurate usage-based billing in 5GSA scenarios. The absence of these requests threatened charging record completeness and revenue assurance for IoT sessions.	Investigation concluded. Root cause analysis systematically ruled out core network domain failures across SMF, CHF, and associated policy elements. Network signaling behavior was validated as normal at the NF level. The issue was ultimately isolated to the probes/capture layer: the signaling between SMF and CHF was occurring but was not visible in probe captures. This confirmed that the charging flow was operational end-to-end, and the apparent gap was a visibility/observability artifact rather than a genuine charging failure. The ticket has been closed with the core network fully exonerated and the issue attributed to probe capture deficiency.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Probe capture gap created a false indication of missing converged charging signaling between SMF and CHF, which risked triggering unnecessary escalations across core network domains and misclassifying a healthy charging flow as a platform defect. Without rapid isolation, this could have resulted in wasted cross-domain investigation effort and delayed certification activities in the FN-IoT environment.	Prevented unnecessary escalation to core network domains (SMF, CHF, PCF) by rapidly isolating the root cause to the observability/probes layer. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically ruling out application-level and infrastructure-level failures, narrowing the investigation scope to the capture toolchain. Validated that the converged charging flow was functioning as expected end-to-end, avoiding misclassification of a healthy platform as defective. Protected cross-domain team bandwidth by containing the issue within the appropriate observability ownership boundary.	Probes team to investigate and resolve the capture gap affecting SMF Γåö CHF signaling visibility in the FN-IoT environment. Validation required to confirm probe captures accurately reflect CreateConvergedCharging request flows post-remediation. Retest of converged charging capture completeness should be scheduled once the probes fix is deployed. Lessons learned to be documented to prevent recurrence of observability-layer issues being misattributed to core network failures.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative highlights the critical dependency between charging platform integrity validation and the accuracy of the observability/probes layer. Misattribution of probe capture gaps to core network failures poses a systemic risk to release certification readiness and cross-domain stabilization efforts. Ensuring probe fidelity is essential for maintaining confidence in charging flow validation across 5GSA environments, particularly for IoT use cases where converged charging accuracy directly impacts revenue assurance.	The apparent absence of CreateConvergedCharging requests from SMF was not a core network defect. The SMF ΓåÆ CHF signaling path was fully operational; however, the probes/capture infrastructure failed to record the transactions, creating a false negative in the observability layer. This is a classic observability-layer failure pattern where toolchain gaps masquerade as application-level defects. The root cause resides entirely in the probe capture mechanism within the FN-IoT environment, not in any NF application logic, policy configuration, or infrastructure connectivity. Key differentiation: the charging flow was working as designed ΓÇö the monitoring of that flow was not.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{SMF,CHF}		t	2026-05-26 18:22:35.237814+00	2026-05-27 15:08:14.593784+00	f	\N
17	1	3	2026-03-24-00017	CTAP-59948	2026-03-24	\N	Policy / Charging	On-Prem	In Progress	Data consumption limit enforcement failure observed for Toyota trial SOC profile. Users are able to consume data beyond the 3GB threshold defined in the trial SOC without triggering any policy action (throttle, block, or redirect). Expected behavior is that PCF policy rules enforce a hard or soft cap at 3GB, coordinated with CHF quota tracking to ensure real-time threshold enforcement. The affected E2E flow spans the PCF (policy decision) ΓåÆ CHF (quota management and threshold monitoring) ΓåÆ SMF (enforcement action) path, with potential dependency on accurate usage reporting from the charging domain to trigger the policy update. This represents a critical gap in the quota enforcement lifecycle where either the CHF is not emitting the threshold breach notification or the PCF is not acting on it to instruct the SMF to apply the appropriate enforcement action.	Investigation is actively underway to isolate whether the enforcement failure originates in the policy domain (PCF rule configuration or evaluation logic) or the charging domain (CHF quota threshold trigger mechanism). Initial analysis confirms that data consumption exceeds the 3GB boundary without any observable policy enforcement action being applied. The RCA is currently focused on two hypotheses: (1) the CHF is not detecting or reporting the threshold breach to the PCF, possibly due to misconfigured quota thresholds or missing grant-level tracking for the Toyota trial SOC; or (2) the PCF is receiving the threshold notification but failing to evaluate or apply the corresponding enforcement rule. Session-level trace analysis and CHF quota grant inspection are in progress to narrow the scope. No transient behavior has been observed ΓÇö the issue is consistently reproducible across multiple test sessions.	Charging Impact | Policy Routing Issue | E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Failure to enforce the 3GB data limit on Toyota trial SOC profiles introduces direct billing risk through unmetered data consumption, policy compliance failure affecting OEM contractual SLA adherence, and potential revenue leakage. If left unresolved, this undermines the integrity of the quota enforcement framework for all OEM-specific SOC profiles and jeopardizes OEM onboarding confidence in the platform's ability to honor usage-based policy contracts.	Identified failure in quota enforcement lifecycle spanning PCF-CHF coordination, accelerating root cause isolation by narrowing the investigation to the threshold trigger mechanism and policy rule evaluation chain. Prevented misclassification as a simple configuration error by initiating cross-domain analysis across policy and charging functions. Proactive RCA approach reduces exposure to billing risk and prevents unnecessary escalation by systematically validating each component in the enforcement path before engaging vendor support.	1. PCF team to validate that Toyota trial SOC policy rules are correctly configured with a 3GB threshold enforcement action (throttle/block/redirect) and confirm rule evaluation is being triggered upon threshold breach notification. 2. CHF team to inspect quota grant allocation for affected sessions and verify that the 3GB threshold is properly configured at the rating group level with the correct trigger mechanism (e.g., usage monitoring, quota exhaustion callback). 3. Correlate PCF session logs with CHF CDR/quota grant records to confirm whether the threshold breach notification is being emitted by the CHF and received by the PCF. 4. If threshold notification is confirmed as missing from CHF, escalate to CHF vendor with session-level evidence. 5. If PCF is receiving the notification but not enforcing, escalate to PCF team for rule evaluation debugging. 6. Upon fix implementation, execute E2E retest with Toyota trial SOC profile consuming exactly 3GB and beyond to validate enforcement action is applied at the correct boundary.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Charging platform integrity and OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacts the platform's ability to enforce usage-based policy contracts for OEM partners. Failure in quota threshold enforcement undermines the credibility of the policy-charging integration framework and introduces systemic billing risk. Resolution is critical for Toyota OEM certification readiness and establishes the validation pattern for all future SOC-based quota enforcement profiles.	The enforcement failure lies in the PCF Γåö CHF quota threshold coordination lifecycle. The 3GB trial SOC cap requires the CHF to accurately track cumulative usage at the rating group level and emit a threshold breach notification (e.g., via Nchf_SpendingLimitControl or quota exhaustion trigger) to the PCF, which must then evaluate the corresponding policy rule and instruct the SMF to apply the enforcement action. The current failure indicates a break in this chain ΓÇö either the CHF quota grant is not configured with the correct threshold trigger for the Toyota trial SOC, or the PCF rule set does not contain or properly evaluate the enforcement condition upon receiving the breach notification. The issue is consistently reproducible, ruling out transient behavior. The root cause hypothesis at this stage centers on a configuration gap in the CHF threshold trigger mechanism for this specific SOC profile, with PCF rule misconfiguration as the secondary hypothesis.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{PCF,CHF,SMF}		t	2026-05-26 18:21:35.730333+00	2026-05-27 15:08:20.032628+00	f	\N
119	1	3	2026-04-02-00122	CTAP-45723	2026-04-02	\N	Validation / Testing	IoT Labs / Northrim / Darkstar	Closed	Observed behavior: IoT end-to-end validation activities across multiple lab environments (Northrim, Darkstar) faced execution continuity risks due to environment dependencies, integration constraints, and multi-domain troubleshooting activities running in parallel. A specific issue was identified where updated PFD (Packet Flow Descriptors) were not being enforced in the IPPEs after the initial PFD fetching issue was resolved, causing landing page test case failures. Expected behavior: IoT E2E validations should execute continuously without interruption, with PFD updates propagating and being enforced automatically across IPPEs without manual intervention. Technical context: The validation chain involved coordination across integration teams, testing teams, network function owners, and operational support groups operating in constrained lab environments. The PFD enforcement failure in IPPEs was a known software limitation requiring manual IPPE restart by the MSFT team. Affected flow: IoT E2E validation pipeline ΓÇö PFD fetching ΓåÆ IPPE enforcement ΓåÆ landing page validation, with broader impact on cross-domain IoT validation continuity across Northrim and Darkstar environments.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed. IoT validation continuity was successfully maintained through proactive cross-domain coordination and targeted troubleshooting. The investigation initially focused on a PFD fetching issue, which was resolved. However, a secondary failure was identified: updated PFDs were not being enforced in the IPPEs ΓÇö a known software deficiency slated for correction in a future software update. The MSFT team executed IPPE restarts to force PFD enforcement, after which the landing page test case executed successfully. Multiple parallel validations were managed under constrained environment availability, with active dependency tracking preventing execution delays. All IoT E2E validation activities resumed and completed without further critical interruptions.	E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Risk of IoT validation pipeline interruption due to PFD enforcement failure in IPPEs and high cross-domain dependency. Potential delay to Lab Exit readiness activities and E2E execution timelines. Without coordination intervention, parallel validation streams across Northrim and Darkstar environments were at risk of environment conflicts and cascading schedule delays.	Isolated root cause of PFD enforcement failure in IPPEs, accelerating resolution by identifying the known software limitation and coordinating the MSFT team for targeted IPPE restart. Enabled cross-domain coordination between integration, testing, network function, and operational support teams to maintain uninterrupted IoT validation execution across multiple constrained lab environments. Prevented unnecessary escalation and environment conflicts through proactive dependency tracking and validation scheduling. Established reusable coordination and escalation models for future IoT E2E validation cycles, increasing operational maturity and reducing future execution risk.	Preserve and formalize coordination and dependency tracking procedures established during this effort for reuse in future IoT validation cycles. Continue improving alignment between testing, integration, and operational support teams to reduce manual coordination overhead. Track the upcoming software update that will resolve the PFD enforcement limitation in IPPEs, eliminating the need for manual IPPE restarts. Reuse the escalation and cross-domain coordination models developed here for future E2E validation efforts across Northrim and Darkstar environments.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Release certification readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly protected IoT E2E validation continuity, a prerequisite for Lab Exit certification. The identification of a known PFD enforcement software limitation and the establishment of cross-domain coordination models contribute to platform operational maturity and de-risk future validation cycles. Strengthens OEM onboarding enablement by ensuring IoT validation pipelines remain stable and predictable across multi-environment execution.	The primary technical failure was a two-stage PFD issue: Stage 1 involved a PFD fetching problem that was resolved through initial troubleshooting. Stage 2 revealed that even after successful PFD fetching, the updated PFDs were not being enforced in the IPPEs ΓÇö a known software deficiency in the current release. The workaround required the MSFT team to manually restart the IPPEs to force PFD enforcement, after which the landing page test case passed successfully. This is a confirmed software limitation, not a configuration or infrastructure defect, and is tracked for resolution in a future software update. The broader operational challenge was maintaining parallel IoT validation execution across Northrim and Darkstar under constrained environment availability, which required active dependency management to prevent cascading delays.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{Infrastructure}		f	2026-05-27 20:51:48.264191+00	2026-05-27 20:51:48.264191+00	f	Root cause confirmed: After the initial PFD fetching issue was resolved, updated PFDs were not being enforced in the IPPEs due to a known software limitation. MSFT team restarted the IPPEs to force PFD enforcement, after which the landing page test case executed successfully. A permanent fix is planned for a future software update.
150	1	3	2026-05-15-00154	CTAP-78745	2026-05-15	\N	NEO / PROVISIONING / HSS	NEO Core QA Environment ΓÇö ACM / OUA Provisioning ΓÇö FX HSS / HP6 HSS ΓÇö Subscriber Management Domain	In Progress	Provisioning failure disrupting NEO Core SIM activation workflow in the QA environment, impacting the ACM ΓåÆ OUA ΓåÆ HSS subscriber management chain. During SIM provisioning attempts through the ACM/OUA flow, transactions consistently fail with error FXHLR-ERR-2045, preventing NEO Core SIM activation and blocking downstream E2E validation activities. The affected path involves ACM provisioning requests targeting FX HSS and HP6 HSS, where the provisioning transaction cannot complete successfully. The core technical question has evolved beyond a simple HSS error: the investigation now centers on whether IoT IMSI provisioning is being routed to the correct target HSS instance. The NEO OUA team is testing IoT provisioning, which requires specific feature support on dedicated IoT 3/4 HSS instances ΓÇö not the general-purpose FX HSS. If provisioning requests are being sent to FX HSS instead of the designated IoT composite HSS, the test scenario itself is invalid. This mirrors a pattern already resolved for ACC devices in the lab by SWC, where composite HSS filtering and log routing to different target destinations was successfully implemented. The expectation was that NEO would replicate this same configuration for ACM subscribers, but it remains unclear whether IoT subscribers in the lab are still being provisioned against FX HSS and, if so, why.	NEO Core SIM activation requests are failing consistently in QA with error FXHLR-ERR-2045 during ACM/OUA provisioning transactions involving FX HSS and HP6 HSS. Initial RCA investigation successfully ruled out charging, PCF, and transport-layer components, narrowing the scope to the HSS/subscriber-management domain. However, the RCA has evolved significantly: the current working hypothesis is that this is not a traditional HSS provisioning logic failure but rather a provisioning routing misconfiguration ΓÇö IoT IMSI provisioning may be directed to the wrong HSS target. Kevin Ibrahim confirmed that IoT team should be provisioning all IoT devices in the lab to IoT 3/4 HSS, not FX HSS. The intended test objective is to validate the new composite HSS architecture and the capability to filter and route HSS logs to different target destinations ΓÇö a capability SWC has already operationalized for ACC devices. If NEO OUA is still provisioning IoT subscribers to FX HSS, the entire test is invalid by design. Shailesh Patel is following up with the NEO OUA team to clarify the current provisioning target configuration and confirm whether the test setup aligns with the composite HSS architecture requirements.	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö NEO Core SIM provisioning is completely blocked in QA, halting SIM activation, IoT onboarding validation, and all downstream E2E certification activities dependent on successful provisioning. Beyond the immediate provisioning failure, there is an OEM Enablement Risk: if the provisioning routing is misconfigured (IoT IMSIs targeting FX HSS instead of IoT 3/4 HSS), the entire NEO OUA IoT provisioning test campaign is invalid, potentially wasting test cycles and delaying composite HSS architecture validation. This also represents a Release Certification Risk for the new composite HSS filtering and log-routing capability that was the primary objective of this test phase.	Accelerated troubleshooting by rapidly isolating the failure domain to HSS/subscriber-management infrastructure, eliminating charging, PCF, and transport-layer components from the investigation scope. Identified a critical test validity concern: surfaced the architectural question of whether IoT IMSI provisioning is being routed to the correct composite HSS target (IoT 3/4 HSS vs. FX HSS), preventing the team from spending additional cycles troubleshooting an HSS error that may stem from an invalid test configuration rather than a genuine provisioning defect. Enabled cross-domain coordination between NEO OUA, IoT, and HSS teams by escalating the composite HSS routing question to the appropriate stakeholders (Kevin Ibrahim, Shailesh Patel), ensuring alignment on the intended test architecture before further execution.	{"Shailesh Patel to follow up with NEO OUA team to clarify current IoT IMSI provisioning target ΓÇö confirm whether subscribers are being routed to FX HSS or IoT 3/4 HSS","Validate whether NEO OUA provisioning configuration mirrors the composite HSS setup already implemented by SWC for ACC devices in the lab","If provisioning target is confirmed as FX HSS, reconfigure ACM/OUA provisioning flow to route IoT IMSIs to the designated IoT 3/4 HSS instances","Review FX HSS and HP6 HSS logs to determine whether FXHLR-ERR-2045 is a consequence of unsupported IoT feature requests on a non-IoT HSS","Validate ACM/OUA provisioning request payloads to confirm correct IMSI routing parameters","Verify subscriber data consistency across HSS instances after routing correction","Execute provisioning retests targeting IoT 3/4 HSS to validate composite HSS filtering and log-routing capability","Confirm successful SIM activation and E2E provisioning flow completion","Close JIRA after stable provisioning validation across multiple test cycles"}	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support. Cross-domain coordination across NEO OUA, IoT team (Kevin Ibrahim), HSS team, and SWC facilitated by TPM to ensure alignment on composite HSS architecture and provisioning routing requirements.	Directly supports NEO Core onboarding readiness and composite HSS architecture validation ΓÇö a strategic platform capability enabling differentiated HSS log filtering and routing to multiple target destinations. This initiative highlights a critical dependency on correct provisioning routing governance: ensuring IoT subscribers are provisioned against the appropriate composite HSS instances rather than legacy FX HSS. Successful resolution validates the same pattern already proven for ACC devices by SWC, establishing a repeatable operational model for subscriber-management modernization. Contributes to QA certification continuity, subscriber-management operational stability, and cross-domain provisioning governance maturity.	Observed error FXHLR-ERR-2045 during ACM/OUA SIM provisioning in QA initially pointed to an HSS provisioning logic or integration failure. However, deeper investigation revealed a more fundamental issue: the NEO OUA team is testing IoT provisioning, which requires specific feature support available only on dedicated IoT 3/4 HSS instances. The current hypothesis is that IoT IMSI provisioning requests are being routed to FX HSS ΓÇö which lacks the required IoT feature support ΓÇö instead of the designated composite HSS targets. This would render the entire test scenario invalid rather than indicative of a genuine HSS defect. SWC has already successfully implemented this composite HSS routing for ACC devices in the lab, establishing the architectural precedent. The critical distinction is between a provisioning infrastructure defect (HSS logic failure) and a test configuration misalignment (wrong HSS target for IoT workloads). Kevin Ibrahim confirmed IoT devices should be provisioned to IoT 3/4 HSS; Shailesh Patel is validating whether NEO OUA's current configuration reflects this requirement. Resolution depends on confirming and correcting the provisioning routing target before any further test execution.	Tier 1	t	configuration	{HSS,Infrastructure}		f	2026-05-27 21:06:26.34302+00	2026-05-27 21:06:26.34302+00	f	
22	1	3	2026-03-24-00022	CTAP-61094	2026-03-24	2026-04-20	Redirection	Lab	Closed	Redirection flow disruption impacting Stellantis OEM landing page delivery. The expected behavior is that subscriber sessions are redirected to the Stellantis MyVehicle landing page upon triggering the captive portal flow. Instead, the redirection chain terminates prematurely at the SNAP portal, preventing the correct OEM-specific landing page from rendering. The affected E2E flow involves the UPF redirection mechanism, SNAP portal logic, and the OEM-specific URL mapping configuration that should route traffic from the generic SNAP endpoint to the Stellantis MyVehicle destination. This indicates a potential breakdown in the redirection mapping layer between SNAP and the OEM landing page target.	Investigation is in progress to determine why the redirection chain halts at the SNAP portal instead of completing the full hop to the Stellantis MyVehicle landing page. Initial observations confirm that the subscriber session is being intercepted and redirected, but the final destination resolution fails. The SNAP portal renders successfully, indicating that the UPF-level redirection trigger is functional; however, the downstream mapping from SNAP to the OEM-specific URL is not being honored. RCA is currently focused on two hypotheses: (1) a misconfiguration in the SNAP-to-OEM URL mapping table, or (2) a UPF rule that does not carry the correct redirect target through the full chain. Infrastructure-level connectivity to the MyVehicle endpoint has not yet been ruled out.\n[Status 04/20/26] MSFT had to reboot the IPPEs. This issue is related with CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348, where the PFD modification is not taken into account by the ippe because the PFDM PFD is not being part of multiple PDRs due to a code vector incomplete deletion. That issue was found in UC 5.1.0.15 and the fix is in UC 5.1.0.18.	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö Stellantis OEM landing page validation is completely blocked. The inability to render the correct MyVehicle page prevents end-to-end certification of the Stellantis redirection use case in the Lab environment. This directly impacts OEM onboarding timelines and delays release certification readiness for the Stellantis integration.	Isolated the redirection breakdown to the SNAP-to-OEM mapping layer, accelerating troubleshooting by narrowing the investigation scope away from UPF trigger logic and focusing on the downstream URL resolution chain. Prevented unnecessary escalation to infrastructure teams by confirming that the initial redirection hop is functional. Enabled cross-domain coordination between the portal configuration team and UPF policy team to jointly validate the full redirection path.	1. Validate the SNAP-to-OEM URL mapping configuration to confirm the Stellantis MyVehicle target is correctly defined and active. 2. Verify UPF redirection rules to ensure the full redirect target URL (not just the SNAP endpoint) is being passed through the session context. 3. Confirm network-level reachability from the SNAP portal to the MyVehicle landing page endpoint ΓÇö rule out DNS resolution or firewall issues. 4. If mapping is corrected, execute end-to-end retest of the Stellantis redirection flow in the Lab environment. 5. Document findings and update OEM onboarding validation tracker upon successful resolution.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö Stellantis redirection validation is a prerequisite for certifying the OEM-specific captive portal flow. Failure to resolve this blocks the Stellantis integration milestone and introduces risk to the broader OEM onboarding program timeline. Additionally impacts release certification readiness as redirection use cases are a core validation gate.	The UPF-level redirection trigger is functioning correctly, as evidenced by the successful rendering of the SNAP portal. The failure occurs downstream in the SNAP-to-OEM URL mapping resolution layer, where the redirect chain should complete its final hop to the Stellantis MyVehicle landing page. This is a configuration-layer issue rather than an infrastructure or application defect. The root cause hypothesis centers on either a missing or incorrect entry in the SNAP portal's OEM URL mapping table, or a UPF policy rule that terminates the redirect target at the SNAP endpoint without propagating the full OEM-specific destination URL. The distinction is critical: the redirection mechanism itself is working as designed ΓÇö it is the destination configuration that is incomplete.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{UPF}		t	2026-05-26 18:24:00.440102+00	2026-05-27 15:08:07.319396+00	f	\N
21	1	3	2026-03-24-00021	CTAP-31749	2026-03-24	\N	UPF / IPPE	UPF	In Progress	Honda OEM landing page failure caused by Packet Flow Description (PFD) inconsistency originating from the IPPE component. The UPF is not receiving correctly updated PFD rules from IPPE, resulting in a breakdown of traffic classification and HTTP redirection logic. Expected behavior: IPPE should propagate accurate PFD definitions to the UPF so that subscriber traffic matching Honda-specific application detection rules is properly classified and redirected to the designated landing page. Observed behavior: PFD entries are stale or malformed, causing the UPF to fail traffic classification, which in turn prevents the redirection flow from triggering. Affected E2E flow: IPPE ΓåÆ PFD provisioning ΓåÆ UPF traffic classification ΓåÆ HTTP redirection ΓåÆ Honda landing page rendering.	Root cause has been identified and attributed to a bug in the IPPE component that prevents proper PFD updates from being propagated to the UPF. The IPPE is either failing to push updated PFD rules or is pushing inconsistent rule sets that the UPF cannot apply correctly. As a result, traffic that should be classified under Honda-specific application detection is not being matched, and the subsequent redirection to the Honda landing page is not executing. The issue has been narrowed to the IPPE software layer ΓÇö UPF forwarding and redirection logic itself is not suspected. A Use Case (UC) patch has been identified as the remediation path. Awaiting patch application and revalidation.	E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Traffic classification failure at the UPF layer due to stale or malformed PFD rules from IPPE, directly breaking Honda OEM landing page redirection. This constitutes an OEM Enablement Risk as Honda-specific subscriber experience is degraded, and a Policy Routing Issue as PFD-driven classification is non-functional. If unresolved, this blocks OEM service certification and impacts the commercial readiness of Honda-integrated use cases on the platform.	Isolated root cause to a specific IPPE software defect in PFD update propagation, preventing misattribution to UPF forwarding or redirection logic. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope exclusively to the IPPE layer, avoiding unnecessary UPF-side debugging cycles. Enabled targeted remediation strategy by identifying the UC patch as the precise fix, reducing mean time to resolution and preventing broader platform disruption.	1. Coordinate application of the identified UC patch to the IPPE component to restore correct PFD provisioning behavior. 2. Validate post-patch that PFD rules are correctly propagated from IPPE to UPF by inspecting PFD table state on the UPF. 3. Execute end-to-end retest of Honda landing page redirection flow to confirm traffic classification and HTTP redirect are functioning as expected. 4. Confirm with Honda OEM integration team that the landing page renders correctly from the subscriber perspective. 5. Monitor for PFD consistency over a sustained period post-fix to rule out recurrence or transient regression.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacts the ability to deliver certified, production-ready Honda use cases on the charging and traffic management platform. Resolution validates the IPPE-to-UPF PFD provisioning chain, which is a foundational dependency for all OEM-specific traffic classification and redirection services. Successful remediation strengthens platform resiliency and cross-domain stabilization by ensuring the PFD lifecycle is robust and patch-resilient.	The root cause is an IPPE software bug that prevents correct Packet Flow Description (PFD) updates from being pushed to the UPF. The UPF's traffic classification engine relies on accurate PFD definitions to match subscriber flows against OEM-specific application detection rules. When IPPE fails to update these rules, the UPF cannot classify Honda-targeted traffic, and the redirection chain breaks entirely ΓÇö the landing page never loads because the triggering condition (correct traffic match) is never met. The defect is at the application layer within IPPE, not at the UPF forwarding or infrastructure layer. The identified UC patch targets this specific PFD propagation logic. This is a genuine software defect, not a configuration issue or transient failure.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,IPPE}		t	2026-05-26 18:23:34.166109+00	2026-05-27 15:08:09.330594+00	f	\N
