39	1	3	2026-05-14-00036	CTAP-78097	2026-05-14	\N	Policy / Charging / Infrastructure	Lab	In Progress	CreateSMPolicy requests initiated by PCF are failing with 503 and 500 error responses originating from CHF during Tech Dev 26.06 release validation. The expected behavior is successful policy creation via the PCF ΓåÆ Cookies VIP ΓåÆ CHF path, enabling end-to-end session management policy establishment. The failure disrupts the CreateSMPolicy flow across the PCF Γåö Cookies Γåö CHF connectivity chain, specifically impacting the infrastructure routing layer between Cookies VIPs and Azure-hosted CHF VIPs. Two key paths are involved: Cookies VIP 107.121.213.19 ΓåÆ CHF VIP 107.239.26.135 and Cookies VIP 107.121.234.37 ΓåÆ CHF VIP 107.126.29.7. Jaeger traces confirm the failure pattern aligns with infrastructure-level connectivity disruption rather than application-layer logic errors.	Investigation has progressed through multiple troubleshooting phases and significantly narrowed the root cause scope. Initial connectivity validation confirmed that ICMP (ping) succeeds between Cookies VIPs and CHF VIPs, but TCP-level connectivity (telnet) fails, indicating a transport or routing-layer obstruction rather than a complete network outage. Jaeger distributed traces corroborate the same connectivity failure pattern. A critical isolation step was performed by migrating test SUPIs from Group ID 58 to Group ID 59, which restored successful PCF Γåö CHF transactions. This conclusively narrows the issue to the specific Cookie path 107.121.213.19 ΓåÆ CHF VIP 107.239.26.135 associated with Group ID 58. LabOps ticket LS-76397 has been raised for infrastructure remediation. The infrastructure team identified missing MT CHF routes on the FEXN fabric. Corrective routes were applied on the X-LEAF layer; however, the issue persists post-fix, indicating either incomplete route propagation, additional missing route entries at other FEXN layers, or a residual firewall or ACL obstruction that has not yet been addressed. RCA has evolved from a generalized CHF application failure hypothesis to a confirmed infrastructure routing deficiency isolated to a specific FEXN path.\n[Status 05/26/26] SUPIs having chfGroupID=58 are still experiencing connectivity issues between the F5's cookies VIP and the CHFs VIP. instead, SUPIs having chfGroupID=59 are not having connectivity issues any more. However, for these SUPIs with chfGroupID=59, the CHF is not reporting usage to the CC (Control Center).	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö CreateSMPolicy failures directly block Tech Dev 26.06 release certification activities. The inability to establish session management policies via the affected path prevents end-to-end validation of policy and charging flows, putting the release timeline at risk. Secondary impact includes E2E Flow Disruption across the PCF Γåö Cookies Γåö CHF domain and potential Release Certification Risk if the infrastructure path is not restored within the certification window.	Isolated root cause from a broad CHF application failure assumption to a specific infrastructure routing deficiency on a single FEXN path, dramatically accelerating troubleshooting by narrowing the investigation scope from application-wide to path-specific. Enabled cross-domain coordination between PCF, CHF, Cookies, and Infrastructure teams by providing clear evidence (Group ID 58 vs 59 behavior differential, ping-vs-telnet analysis, Jaeger trace correlation) that the defect resides in the infrastructure layer. Prevented unnecessary application-level escalation to CHF development teams by demonstrating that CHF transactions succeed when routed through the healthy path. Proactively raised LabOps ticket LS-76397 to engage infrastructure remediation, maintaining momentum on the release certification timeline.	1. Await LabOps update on ticket LS-76397 regarding FEXN route remediation status and root cause for persistence of failure after X-LEAF route correction. 2. Infrastructure team to perform comprehensive FEXN route audit across all leaf and spine layers for the affected path (Cookies VIP 107.121.213.19 ΓåÆ CHF VIP 107.239.26.135) to identify any remaining missing or misconfigured routes. 3. Validate whether firewall rules or ACLs are blocking TCP traffic on the affected path despite ICMP success. 4. Once routing is confirmed restored, execute telnet validation from Cookies VIP to CHF VIP on the affected path to confirm TCP-level connectivity. 5. Re-run CreateSMPolicy test cases using SUPIs assigned to Group ID 58 to validate end-to-end flow restoration. 6. If successful, proceed with full Tech Dev 26.06 certification test execution across both paths. 7. Document FEXN routing gap as a known infrastructure risk item for future release environment provisioning.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Infrastructure stabilization and release certification readiness ΓÇö this initiative directly impacts the ability to certify Tech Dev 26.06 on schedule. The discovery of FEXN routing gaps exposes a systemic risk in lab environment provisioning for Azure-hosted CHF deployments, with implications for future release certification cycles and cross-domain infrastructure reliability. Resolution will strengthen platform resiliency posture and establish a precedent for proactive FEXN route validation during environment build-out.	The CreateSMPolicy 503/500 failures are not caused by CHF application logic but by an infrastructure routing deficiency at the FEXN fabric layer. ICMP connectivity succeeds while TCP connectivity fails between Cookies VIP 107.121.213.19 and CHF VIP 107.239.26.135, confirming a transport-layer obstruction. The Group ID 58 ΓåÆ 59 SUPI migration test provides definitive proof that the issue is path-specific: transactions routed through the alternate Cookies VIP 107.121.234.37 ΓåÆ CHF VIP 107.126.29.7 path succeed, while those traversing the 107.121.213.19 ΓåÆ 107.239.26.135 path fail. Missing MT CHF routes were identified on the FEXN