35	1	3	2026-05-06-00035	CTAP-74959	2026-05-06	\N	CHARGING / CHF / VISIBILITY	NR Lab 8	Closed	Platform-wide charging visibility disruption affecting all OEMs across all DNNs in NR Lab 8. ACC was unable to display session information or usage flow data, indicating a break in the end-to-end observability chain spanning CHF ΓåÆ CCS ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ISBUS ΓåÆ ACC. The expected behavior is that all session and usage data generated by CHF flows through the CCS processing layer, is published to the appropriate Kafka output topics, ingested by ISBUS, and rendered in ACC for real-time and historical visibility. The failure affected every OEM and every DNN, confirming a systemic issue in the downstream data pipeline rather than an NF-specific or DNN-specific fault. The scope of the disruption elevated this to a platform-level observability incident requiring cross-domain investigation across charging, messaging infrastructure, and analytics teams.	Ticket is closed with full resolution confirmed. The root cause analysis evolved through multiple investigation phases: initial suspicion focused on CHF-level data generation, which was ruled out after the CCS team confirmed that usage records were successfully flowing to the Kafka output topic. Investigation then shifted downstream to the ISBUS ingestion layer, where it was discovered that ISBUS credentials (client secret) had expired, severing the authenticated connection between ISBUS and the Kafka/ACC pipeline. A new client secret was shared and updated, partially restoring the flow. A residual authentication issue on the Cisco side was subsequently identified and resolved by the Cisco team. Following both remediations, ACC visibility was fully restored across all OEMs and all DNNs. The incident is confirmed resolved with no outstanding actions.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Platform-wide E2E observability disruption affecting all OEMs and all DNNs in NR Lab 8. The inability to view session information and usage data in ACC constituted a complete loss of charging visibility, blocking OEM validation activities, usage-based testing certification, and real-time operational monitoring. This directly impacted OEM onboarding enablement timelines and release certification readiness for any charging-dependent test scenarios.	Accelerated cross-domain root cause isolation by systematically narrowing the investigation scope from CHF application-layer behavior through CCS processing to the downstream ISBUS authentication and Kafka integration chain. Prevented unnecessary escalation to CHF and NF application teams by validating that upstream data generation was functioning correctly. Enabled coordinated remediation across CCS, ISBUS, and Cisco teams by identifying the exact failure point ΓÇö expired ISBUS credentials ΓÇö and facilitating the credential rotation process. Restored platform-wide charging observability for all OEMs, unblocking dependent testing and certification activities. Demonstrated proactive pipeline-level RCA methodology that prevented prolonged visibility outage and avoided misclassification of the issue as a CHF application defect.	No further actions required. Ticket is closed with full resolution confirmed. Recommended preventive measures for future operational hygiene include: (1) Implement credential expiration monitoring and automated alerting for ISBUS client secrets and all service-to-service authentication tokens in the Kafka/ACC pipeline; (2) Establish a credential rotation calendar with proactive renewal 30 days before expiration; (3) Document this incident as a known failure pattern in the observability runbook for NR Lab environments to accelerate future triage if similar symptoms recur.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Cross-domain investigation and coordination driven end-to-end by C├⌐sar Villagra across CCS, ISBUS, and Cisco teams to isolate and remediate the root cause.	Observability readiness and OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This incident exposed a critical vulnerability in the charging observability pipeline where credential lifecycle management gaps can silently sever the entire ACC visibility chain. Resolution restored platform-wide charging analytics for all OEMs and all DNNs, directly supporting release certification readiness and cross-domain stabilization. The incident reinforces the need for infrastructure-level credential governance as a foundational requirement for sustainable observability at scale.	The end-to-end ACC visibility failure was not caused by any NF-level application defect or CHF data generation issue. The CCS layer was confirmed to be successfully publishing usage data to the Kafka output topic, which ruled out all upstream components. The root cause was an expired ISBUS client secret that broke the authenticated connection between ISBUS and the Kafka/ACC ingestion pipeline. This credential expiration silently severed the observability chain at the messaging infrastructure layer, causing a platform-wide symptom (no session info or usage visible in ACC for any OEM or DNN) that superficially resembled a CHF or application-layer failure. A secondary authentication issue on the Cisco side compounded the outage and required separate remediation. The failure pattern demonstrates that observability pipeline availability is critically dependent on service credential lifecycle management ΓÇö a layer often overlooked during infrastructure health assessments. The fix was non-application: credential rotation for ISBUS and Cisco-side authentication remediation, both operating at the infrastructure/configuration boundary.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{CHF,ACC,Kafka,ISBUS}		t	2026-05-26 18:31:02.106728+00	2026-05-27 15:07:38.843151+00	f	\N
