ö Cisco investigated independently and resolved the remaining issue. After both corrections, charging visibility toward ACC was fully restored, and OEM E2E validation activities resumed normally. RCA confirmed: the charging core (CHF, Kafka) was functioning as designed; the failure existed exclusively within the downstream authentication and integration layer (ISBUS credential expiration + Cisco post-restart authentication anomaly).	Platform-Wide Charging Visibility Loss | All OEM E2E Validation Impacted. The issue caused a complete loss of ACC session visibility, charging observability, usage history validation, and E2E charging confirmation activities across all OEM DNNs in Lab 8 ΓÇö including Honda, Rivian, and additional OEM environments. This blocked OEM onboarding validation workflows and eliminated the ability to confirm charging accuracy through ACC, creating an OEM Enablement Risk and Visibility Loss condition across the entire Northrim Lab 8 environment.	Isolated the root cause beyond the charging core by systematically validating CHF charging generation and Kafka output topic population ΓÇö confirming the charging pipeline was functioning correctly and narrowing the investigation exclusively to the downstream authentication and integration layer. This prevented unnecessary escalation toward SMF/PCF/CHF charging logic teams, avoiding misdirected troubleshooting cycles. Identified the expired ISBUS credentials as the primary failure point and enabled cross-domain coordination across CCS, CHF, Cisco, ISBUS, and ACC teams to drive concurrent resolution. The structured RCA approach significantly accelerated time-to-resolution and restored platform-wide charging observability for all OEM validation activities.	No additional actions required. Authentication issues fully resolved ΓÇö ISBUS credentials updated and Cisco post-restart authentication anomaly addressed. ACC visibility restored across all OEM DNNs in NR Lab 8. OEM E2E validation activities resumed successfully. Recommend establishing a proactive ISBUS credential expiration monitoring mechanism to prevent recurrence of downstream authentication-driven visibility failures.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Supports platform-wide charging observability stabilization and reinforces the critical distinction between charging generation integrity and downstream visibility layer health. Demonstrates cross-domain RCA capability spanning CHF, Kafka, CCS, ISBUS, and ACC ΓÇö highlighting the dependency chain that underpins OEM charging validation. Exposes the operational risk of ISBUS credential lifecycle management and its cascading impact on ACC visibility and OEM onboarding enablement. Strengthens ACC visibility troubleshooting governance and informs future observability readiness assessments for production-bound charging pipelines.	CHF charging generation and Kafka output topic population were validated as fully operational ΓÇö the charging core was functioning as designed throughout the incident. The primary root cause was identified as expired ISBUS client credentials, which prevented ACC from authenticating against the data ingestion pipeline, resulting in a complete platform-wide visibility blackout. A secondary contributing factor was a Cisco authentication failure that persisted after application restart even after the credential update ΓÇö Cisco investigated and resolved this independently. The failure existed exclusively at the downstream authentication and integration layer (ISBUS ΓåÆ ACC), not at the charging generation or streaming layers (CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ CCS). Impacted domains: CHF streaming path, CCS integration, ISBUS authentication, and ACC visibility layer. Classification: Downstream charging visibility / authentication integration issue ΓÇö not a charging defect. This incident highlights the fragility of the observability pipeline when credential lifecycle management is not proactively governed.	Tier 1	t	observab