aintaining the NEO platform launch timeline and demonstrating provisioning integrity across the HSS integration boundary.	The provisioning failure is localized to the FX HSS / HP6 HSS layer, with error FXHLR-ERR-2045 consistently returned during NEO Core SIM activation attempts. Upstream ACM and NEO OUA components are functioning correctly through the provisioning request chain ΓÇö the rejection occurs specifically at the HSS processing boundary. The current RCA hypothesis centers on either a provisioning parameter validation failure (mismatched or missing mandatory fields in the SIM profile request) or an HSS-side configuration deficiency where NEO Core SIM subscription templates may not be properly instantiated. This is not a transient issue; it is reproducible and requires HSS domain intervention. No infrastructure or connectivity layer involvement has been identified ΓÇö the failure is application-level within the HSS provisioning logic.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{HSS,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-26 18:33:24.340148+00	2026-05-27 15:07:28.092814+00	f	\N
87	1	3	03/18/2026-00088	CTAP-58892	2026-03-18	\N	PROVISIONING / IMS	IoT Labs / Multiple OEM Validation Environments	Closed	SMS Mobile Originated (MO) and Mobile Terminated (MT) flows were failing consistently across all OEM IoT validation scenarios, indicating a systemic provisioning disruption rather than an isolated network function defect. The failure impacted end-to-end SMS delivery chains spanning provisioning, IMS feature enablement, and SIM configuration domains. Expected behavior required SMS traffic to be successfully delivered, properly provisioned, and correctly processed across all involved network domains. The root cause was traced to incomplete SMS provisioning within the MIND platform during SUPI onboarding ΓÇö the first SIM carried legacy provisioning inconsistencies in MIND, and the second SIM was provisioned as legacy, causing fallback to LTE for SMS completion, which explained successful behavior when moved from NR Only to NR/LTE. This represented a provisioning completeness gap in the MIND SMS configuration layer, not an application or transport domain failure.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 04/20/2026. Root cause analysis confirmed that the SMS failure was driven by incomplete SMS provisioning in MIND during SUPI setup. The first SIM had prior provisioning inconsistencies in MIND, and the second SIM was provisioned under a legacy profile, causing it to fall back to LTE to complete SMS ΓÇö which is why SMS succeeded when the device was moved from NR Only to NR/LTE. Investigation systematically ruled out SMF, PCF, charging, and transport domains. Structured troubleshooting across provisioning, IMS, and SMS support teams narrowed the scope to SIM setup and MIND provisioning completeness. SMS MO/MT functionality was restored after corrective provisioning actions, and all OEM validation activities resumed normally with no further inconsistencies observed during retest.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö SMS validation was blocked across all OEM IoT scenarios, halting end-to-end testing continuity and delaying IoT onboarding and certification activities. The provisioning inconsistency in MIND created a systemic SMS delivery failure affecting both MO and MT flows, with potential risk of misclassification as a network function defect if not properly isolated. The disruption directly threatened IoT OEM validation timelines and release certification readiness for SMS-dependent use cases.	Isolated root cause to incomplete SMS provisioning in MIND during SUPI onboarding, preventing unnecessary escalation toward SMF, PCF, charging, and transport domains. Accelerated RCA identification through structured cross-domain troubleshooting that systematically narrowed the investigation scope from a broad multi-NF failure hypothesis to a specific provisioning completeness gap. Enabled effective coordination between provisioning and SMS support teams, ensuring corrective action was targeted and efficient. Validated that the NR/LTE fallback behavior was a direct consequence of legacy provisioning ΓÇö not a radio access or transport anomaly ΓÇö avoiding misclassification and preserving investigative resources. Established a reusable troubleshooting baseline for future SMS-related provisioning investigations across OEM onboarding scenarios.	Continue monitoring SMS provisioning consistency across OEM scenarios to detect any recurrence of incomplete MIND configurations during SUPI onboarding. Preserve the validated SIM and provisioning baseline established during this investigation as a reference standard for future IoT onboarding activities. Recommend provisioning team implement a verification checkpoint for SMS feature completeness within MIND during SUPI setup to prevent similar gaps. Reuse the structured troubleshooting findings and RCA documentation for future SMS-related investigations, particularly for scenarios involving NR Only versus NR/LTE fallback behavior. Validate that all currently active OEM SIMs have complete SMS provisioning in MIND to preempt latent failures.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö this initiative exposed a systemic provisioning completeness gap in the MIND platform that directly blocked IoT SMS validation across all OEM scenarios. The resolution established a reusable troubleshooting methodology and provisioning verification baseline that strengthens future onboarding resilience. The RCA findings carry direct implications for provisioning process maturity and release certification readiness for SMS-dependent IoT use cases.	The SMS MO/MT failure was not a network function or transport layer defect ΓÇö it was rooted in incomplete SMS provisioning within the MIND platform during SUPI onboarding. The first SIM carried legacy provisioning inconsistencies in MIND, and the second SIM was provisioned as a legacy profile, causing the device to fall back to LTE to complete SMS transactions. This fallback behavior explained why SMS succeeded when the device was moved from NR Only to NR/LTE ΓÇö the LTE path compensated for the missing NR SMS provisioning. The failure layer was purely configuration/provisioning, not application, infrastructure, or IMS signaling. This distinction was critical to preventing unnecessary escalation to SMF, PCF, charging, and transport teams, and highlights the need for a provisioning completeness gate during SUPI setup in MIND to ensure SMS feature enablement is fully configured before OEM validation begins.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{HSS,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27 19:11:47.145419+00	2026-05-27 20:42:12.684204+00	f	\N
