lows, with potential downstream risk to IMS/SMS provisioning consistency and OEM certification timelines.	Successfully isolated root cause to SIM setup and MIND provisioning configuration domains, preventing unnecessary escalation toward SMF, PCF, charging, and transport teams. Accelerated RCA identification through structured cross-domain troubleshooting methodology that systematically ruled out NF-level and transport-level faults. Enabled targeted remediation by identifying the exact provisioning gap (incomplete SMS component in MIND) and the legacy SIM fallback behavior. Improved coordination between provisioning and SMS support teams, establishing a validated provisioning baseline reusable for future OEM onboarding activities.	Continue monitoring SMS provisioning consistency across OEM scenarios to detect any recurrence. Preserve the validated SIM/provisioning baseline configuration as a reference standard for future IoT onboarding activities. Incorporate troubleshooting findings and MIND provisioning validation checkpoints into the standard OEM onboarding playbook to prevent similar provisioning gaps. Recommend MIND provisioning workflow enhancement to enforce SMS feature completeness validation at SUPI provisioning time.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacted IoT OEM validation readiness by blocking SMS MO/MT testing across all OEM scenarios. The resolution established a validated provisioning baseline and exposed a gap in the MIND provisioning workflow that, if left unaddressed, could recur during future onboarding campaigns. The structured RCA and cross-domain coordination approach demonstrated platform-level provisioning governance maturity critical for scaling IoT onboarding operations.	Root cause was a provisioning completeness gap in MIND: when the SUPI was provisioned, the SMS component was left incomplete, causing SMS MO/MT failures on NR Only. The first SIM had pre-existing provision