37	1	3	2026-05-07-00037	CTAP-75933	2026-05-07	\N	Logging / UDM / Observability	AON	In Progress	Validation effort for UDM summary trace and logging integration toward BSA is currently blocked due to a platform release dependency. The objective is to verify that UDM-generated summary traces are properly ingested and rendered within BSA for the Darkstar and Blackrim service contexts in the AON environment. This initiative is part of a broader architectural migration from legacy probe-based observability to native UDM log-based telemetry, which carries significant implications for long-term observability strategy, platform simplification, and operational cost reduction. Affected flow: UDM ΓåÆ Summary Traces ΓåÆ BSA ingestion pipeline. The current UDM release deployed in AON does not support the summary trace capability required for this validation, creating a hard dependency on the DS26.04 release.	Testing remains blocked due to the absence of summary trace support in the currently deployed UDM release within the AON environment. Stephen Ledsham confirmed that the current AON UDM release does not include the summary trace functionality required for BSA integration validation. Bic Nguyen identified DS26.04 as the enabling release that will introduce this capability. In parallel, Tushar has raised a strategic question regarding the broader migration path from probe-based observability to a UDM log-based solution, signaling that this ticket is not merely a testing task but a foundational step toward an architectural observability transformation. No workarounds are available; the dependency is binary on the DS26.04 deployment. RCA status: Not a defect ΓÇö this is a feature availability dependency tied to the release roadmap.\n[Status 05/26/26] As per Bic Nguyen, to support the summary traces in the UDM: "For AON UDM, we will need DS26.04 software.  Once this has been deployed we will need to follow up with enablement MOP".	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö UDM-to-BSA observability validation for Darkstar and Blackrim cannot proceed until the DS26.04 release is deployed in AON. This blocks the certification of the UDM native logging path as a viable replacement for legacy probe-based monitoring, delaying the observability architecture migration timeline and preventing the team from retiring legacy tooling dependencies. Extended delay risks misalignment with broader program milestones tied to observability modernization.	Maintained proactive visibility into the observability roadmap by identifying and documenting the exact release dependency (DS26.04) blocking validation. Enabled cross-domain coordination between UDM platform owners (Stephen Ledsham), release management (Bic Nguyen), and architecture stakeholders (Tushar) to align on the migration path from probe-based to UDM log-based observability. Prevented premature test execution against an unsupported release, avoiding wasted cycles and false-negative results. Elevated the conversation from a tactical logging test to a strategic architecture migration discussion, ensuring leadership awareness of the broader implications.	1. Monitor DS26.04 release schedule and confirm deployment timeline into the AON environment with Bic Nguyen and the release management team. 2. Upon DS26.04 availability, execute UDM summary trace validation against BSA for both Darkstar and Blackrim service contexts. 3. Define and document the migration approach and timeline for transitioning from probe-based observability to UDM log-based telemetry, incorporating Tushar's strategic input. 4. Coordinate with the BSA ingestion team to confirm readiness for UDM summary trace consumption. 5. Establish success criteria for the validation (trace completeness, latency, format compliance) prior to test execution. 6. Report findings and migration recommendation to leadership for QBR alignment.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö C├⌐sar is driving coordination across UDM platform, release management, and architecture stakeholders to ensure alignment on both the tactical validation and the strategic observability migration path.	Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly supports the platform's observability modernization strategy by validating the feasibility of replacing legacy probe-based monitoring with native UDM log-based telemetry. Successful execution de-risks the architecture migration, reduces operational complexity, and positions the platform for scalable, NF-native observability. The outcome of this validation will influence the long-term observability architecture roadmap and has direct implications for platform simplification and cost optimization discussions at the QBR level.	The current UDM release deployed in AON lacks summary trace support, which is the core capability required for BSA integration validation. This is not a defect but a feature availability gap tied to the DS26.04 release. The broader strategic question ΓÇö raised by Tushar ΓÇö is whether the platform should migrate from probe-based observability (external, infrastructure-dependent) to UDM log-based observability (native, application-embedded). This represents a fundamental architectural shift: probes operate at the network layer and require separate infrastructure, while UDM-native logging operates at the application layer and integrates directly into the NF telemetry pipeline. The DS26.04 release is the first enabler for validating this new path. If successful, it establishes the precedent for NF-native observability across the platform, reducing dependency on external probing infrastructure and improving trace fidelity.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{UDM}		t	2026-05-26 18:31:53.042299+00	2026-05-27 15:07:34.510982+00	f	\N
12	1	3	2026-03-24-00012	Iot-Toyota-landing page is not getting loaded	2026-03-24	\N	Redirection / UPF	Lab (Real UE)	Closed	Landing page redirection failure identified in the IoT Toyota use case. The control-plane signaling path (PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ UPF) appears to be functioning correctly, with policy rules and session establishment completing as expected. However, the data-plane execution ΓÇö specifically the HTTP redirection enforcement at the UPF/IPPE (Inline Packet Processing Engine) layer ΓÇö is failing to deliver the landing page to the end user equipment. The affected E2E flow spans from PCF policy decision ΓåÆ SMF session modification ΓåÆ UPF traffic detection and redirection ΓåÆ landing page delivery to the real UE. This indicates a potential breakdown in the PFD (Packet Flow Description) propagation or IPPE redirection rule application within the UPF data-plane processing pipeline.	Investigation is actively in progress with the control-plane path validated as operational. SMF session establishment and PCF policy provisioning have been confirmed to execute correctly, ruling out signaling-layer defects. The failure has been narrowed down to the data-plane domain, specifically within the UPF's IPPE redirection mechanism. The current RCA hypothesis centers on either (1) PFD rules not being correctly propagated from SMF to UPF, (2) IPPE not applying the redirection rules to matching traffic flows, or (3) a mismatch between the traffic detection filter configuration and the actual UE traffic patterns. Control-plane correctness has been ruled out as a contributing factor, focusing the investigation scope exclusively on UPF data-plane behavior.	E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Critical Testing Blocker | OEM Enablement Risk. The inability to load the Toyota landing page directly blocks the IoT redirection validation milestone for the Toyota use case. This failure prevents certification of the REDIR (redirection) feature in the lab environment using real UE equipment, which is a prerequisite for OEM onboarding progression. Until resolved, Toyota IoT redirection testing cannot advance, creating a dependency bottleneck for downstream validation activities.	Isolated root cause domain to UPF/IPPE data-plane execution, eliminating control-plane investigation overhead. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing the investigation scope from full E2E (PCF ΓåÆ SMF ΓåÆ UPF ΓåÆ UE) to a targeted UPF data-plane analysis. Prevented unnecessary escalation to PCF and SMF teams by confirming signaling-layer correctness early in the triage process. Enabled focused cross-domain coordination between UPF/IPPE engineering teams with precise fault domain identification.	1. Validate IPPE redirection behavior on the UPF ΓÇö confirm whether redirection rules are being instantiated and applied to matching traffic flows. 2. Verify PFD propagation from SMF to UPF ΓÇö check that Packet Flow Descriptions are correctly received, parsed, and installed in the UPF forwarding table. 3. Inspect UPF traffic detection filters ΓÇö confirm alignment between configured detection rules and actual UE traffic patterns (destination IP, port, protocol). 4. Capture data-plane packet traces at UPF ingress/egress to identify where the redirection flow breaks. 5. Coordinate with UPF engineering team to review IPPE logs for rule application failures or error conditions. 6. Upon resolution, execute full E2E retest with real UE to validate landing page delivery end-to-end.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This ticket directly impacts the Toyota IoT redirection capability validation, which is a critical milestone for OEM partner enablement. Successful resolution validates the platform's ability to enforce data-plane redirection policies for IoT use cases, a foundational capability for commercial IoT service delivery. Additionally, this contributes to release certification readiness by confirming UPF IPPE redirection functionality in a lab environmen