126	1	3	2026-03-19-00129	CTAP-59219	2026-03-19	\N	REGISTRATION / ATTACH	Darkstar Lab 4 / Tesla Hedy DNN	Closed	A registration and attach disruption was identified within the Darkstar Lab 4 environment targeting the Tesla Hedy DNN, where devices were unable to successfully complete attach procedures. The failure directly impacted IoT E2E validation activities, registration procedure certification, and Darkstar Line Up validation continuity. The expected behavior was a successful attach and registration into the targeted Darkstar environment. Initial troubleshooting focused on AMF selection behavior, mobility handling, TAC configuration, and N26-related inter-RAT procedures. The affected flow spans the 4G ΓåÆ N26 ΓåÆ 5G attach and mobility path, specifically the MME6 ΓåÆ N26 interface ΓåÆ AMF selection chain within the Darkstar Lab 4 integration topology.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 03/23/2026. During root cause analysis, it was determined that a 4G Idle device performing Tracking Area Update (TAU) toward 5G was being routed through N26 procedures, during which MME6 was selecting an incorrect AMF ΓÇö specifically RDM52d AMF associated with Northrim Lab 1 ΓÇö instead of the expected Darkstar Line Up 4 AMF (RD2WA65). Further investigation confirmed that TAC-related configuration was a contributing factor to the attach inconsistency. The AMF team identified that the TAC range used for the 4G-to-5G attach was incorrect and recommended a corrected TAC range. Upon retesting with the corrected TAC range and an alternative 5G direct attach approach, the device attached successfully. No further attach inconsistencies were observed post-resolution.	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö Attach validation was completely blocked in Darkstar Lab 4, interrupting IoT E2E validation activities and delaying Darkstar integration readiness. Incorrect mobility and AMF selection behavior through the N26 interface disrupted testing continuity across the 4G-to-5G inter-RAT attach flow, creating downstream risk to lab certification timelines and inter-lab mobility validation milestones.	Successfully isolated the root cause across four distinct investigation domains ΓÇö mobility handling, N26 inter-RAT behavior, AMF selection logic, and TAC configuration ΓÇö preventing unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, or policy teams. Accelerated troubleshooting through structured domain isolation, narrowing the investigation from a broad attach failure to a specific TAC/AMF selection misconfiguration within the N26 path. Improved organizational understanding of inter-lab mobility dependencies between Darkstar and Northrim environments, generating reusable troubleshooting baselines for future N26 and mobility-related investigations.	Preserve the validated TAC configuration baseline for Darkstar Lab 4 as a reference for future attach and registration validations. Continue monitoring AMF selection behavior during subsequent inter-RAT mobility validations to ensure sustained correctness. Document and socialize troubleshooting findings across mobility and AMF teams for reuse in future N26 investigations. Validate that the corrected TAC range is consistently applied across all Darkstar Lab environments to prevent recurrence.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö This initiative directly safeguards Darkstar Lab 4 integration readiness and IoT E2E validation continuity by resolving a critical inter-RAT mobility misconfiguration. The structured isolation of the root cause across AMF selection, N26 behavior, and TAC configuration domains strengthens the organization's ability to certify mobility procedures across multi-lab topologies and accelerates platform readiness for production-grade inter-RAT handover scenarios.	The attach failure was caused by an incorrect TAC range being used during 4G Idle to 5G attach procedures via the N26 interface. MME6, through N26, was selecting RDM52d AMF (associated with Northrim Lab