41	1	3	2026-05-14-00041	CTAP-80611	2026-05-14	\N	CHARGING / CHF / ACC VISIBILITY	CHF	In Progress	Charging visibility disruption identified in the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain. Despite successful end-to-end charging transactions ΓÇö with both CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy completing without errors ΓÇö session information and usage data are not being surfaced in ACC. The issue points to a breakdown in the downstream streaming and event publishing pipeline between CHF, Kafka, and the ACC observability layer. Multiple contributing factors were identified across Kafka broker connectivity, ISBUS private endpoint approval workflows, and a code-level defect in the CHF streamer component. The affected flow spans the full CHF charging event lifecycle through Kafka topic publication to ACC consumption and dashboard rendering.	Root cause analysis has converged on a multi-layered failure in the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC streaming pipeline. Initial investigation confirmed that charging transactions themselves are healthy ΓÇö CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy both complete successfully, ruling out application-layer NF defects. The CHF team identified a Kafka broker connectivity issue which was resolved. A subsequent blocker was discovered: a Private Endpoint request for the Kafka Schema Registry had not been approved by ISBUS, due to ISBUS misinterpreting the request as pertaining to Confluent Kafka broker infrastructure rather than the Schema Registry endpoint. This approval has now been completed. Additionally, a code defect was identified in the CHF streamer component responsible for publishing charging events to Kafka output topics. The development team has delivered a fix, and Kafka output topics are now confirmed to be populated. The investigation has been narrowed from a broad charging failure hypothesis to a confirmed downstream observability pipeline issue. Awaiting retest to validate full ACC visibility restoration.\n[Status 05/26/26] CHF confirmed that the CDRs are being seen in output Topics. The tester confirmed they are still unable to see the info on ACC so they are validating with Cisco.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Complete loss of session information and usage data in ACC despite successful charging transactions, creating a critical observability gap in the charging platform. This disruption prevents operational teams from validating charging accuracy, blocks end-to-end test certification that depends on ACC data confirmation, and undermines confidence in the CHF ΓåÆ ACC reporting integrity. Secondary impact includes Release Certification Risk, as any charging-dependent test scenarios requiring ACC-based evidence cannot be closed without restored visibility.	Isolated root cause to downstream CHF streaming and Kafka integration layers, preventing misattribution of the issue to CHF application logic or upstream NF failures. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope from a broad charging failure to a targeted observability pipeline defect across three distinct failure points (Kafka broker, ISBUS approval workflow, CHF streamer code). Enabled cross-domain coordination between CHF team, ISBUS, and the development team to resolve a compounded multi-team blocker. Identified a process gap in ISBUS private endpoint approval workflows where miscommunication caused unnecessary delays ΓÇö surfacing a systemic risk for future Kafka-dependent integrations. Prevented unnecessary escalation of charging NF defects by confirming transaction-layer health early in the investigation cycle.	{"Execute end-to-end retest with new charging sessions to validate that session info and usage data now appear correctly in ACC.","CHF team to confirm Kafka output topic data integrity ΓÇö verify schema compliance and message completeness post-streamer fix.","Validate ACC consumption pipeline is correctly ingesting from the now-populated Kafka topics ΓÇö confirm no additional ACC-side configuration or subscription gaps.","ISBUS team to document the Private Endpoint approval process clarification to prevent recurrence of miscommunication for future Kafka Schema Registry or similar requests.","If retest confirms restoration, close the observability gap and proceed with re-execution of any blocked charging certification test cases.","If retest fails, escalate to development team for further CHF streamer component analysis with Kafka topic payload inspection."}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö TPM-led cross-domain coordination across CHF, ISBUS, and development teams to resolve compounded observability pipeline failure.	Charging platform integrity and Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly addresses a critical gap in the CHF-to-ACC observability chain that underpins charging accuracy validation and release certification evidence. The multi-layered root cause (Kafka broker, ISBUS process gap, CHF streamer code defect) highlights systemic risks in cross-team dependency management for streaming infrastructure. Resolution strengthens platform confidence for QBR reporting and de-risks future OEM onboarding scenarios that depend on ACC-based charging visibility. The ISBUS approval process gap identified represents a reusable finding for infrastructure governance improvement.	The failure was not in the charging NFs themselves ΓÇö both CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy completed successfully, confirming CHF and PCF application layers are healthy. The root cause was a compounded three-point failure in the downstream observability pipeline: (1) a Kafka broker connectivity issue that was resolved first, (2) an unapproved Private Endpoint for Kafka Schema Registry caused by ISBUS misinterpreting the request as a Confluent Kafka broker ask rather than a Schema Registry endpoint ΓÇö a process/communication failure, not a technical denial, and (3) a code defect in the CHF streamer component that prevented proper event publication to Kafka output topics even after connectivity was restored. The critical insight is that all three failures had to be resolved sequentially for data to flow ΓÇö fixing any single point alone would not have restored ACC visibility. Kafka output topics are now confirmed populated post-fix, but end-to-end ACC rendering validation remains pending. This pattern of compounded silent failures in streaming pipelines represents a recurring risk for any Kafka-dependent observability integration in the platform.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{CHF,Kafka,ACC,ISBUS,PCF}		t	2026-05-26 18:33:58.321282+00	2026-05-27 15:07:26.060209+00	f	\N
