ectives.	The validation targets NEO Enterprise delay charging behavior over encrypted transport (TLS/QUIC) with SNI-based routing, which introduces a new routing dimension in the charging path. The SNI feature allows the platform to route charging requests based on the Server Name Indication field in the TLS handshake, enabling multi-tenant or service-differentiated charging paths. The key technical risk lies in ensuring that delay charging records are correctly generated, routed via SNI, and processed by CHF without loss or misclassification under the new transport layer. The SVT cycle must confirm that the TLS/QUIC transport does not introduce latency or failure modes in the CHF processing chain, and that SNI-based routing correctly maps to the intended charging endpoints. No defects have been identified yet ΓÇö the current phase is pre-execution validation and coordination. Any issues surfaced during testing will refine the RCA hypothesis around whether failures are application-layer (CHF/PCF logic), configuration-layer (SNI routing rules), or infrastructure-layer (TLS/QUIC transport stability).	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{CHF,PCF,ACC}		t	2026-05-26 18:32:21.042895+00	2026-05-27 15:07:32.308821+00	f	\N
34	1	3	2026-04-03-00034	CTAP-74344	2026-04-03	\N	CHARGING / CHF / PCF	Lab	Closed	Charging visibility disruption identified in the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain for the Rivian DNN (rvtech-core-5g). Usage transactions were completing successfully at the charging layer, however no corresponding usage records were surfacing in the ACC platform. The issue spanned two domains: (1) a PCF configuration deficiency where the Rivian DNN was set to Offline mode instead of Online on rd2wa65 cpcf1/cpcf2, preventing proper session-level charging initiation, and (2) a CHF-side Kafka integration failure that blocked CDR delivery to ACC even when charging records were being generated. The affected E2E flow encompasses PCF policy enforcement ΓåÆ CHF charging session creation ΓåÆ Kafka CDR pipeline ΓåÆ ACC usage reporting.	Ticket has been resolved and closed. Root cause analysis confirmed a dual-domain failure: PCF configuration for the Rivian DNN was incorrectly set to Offline mode on rd2wa65 cpcf1/cpcf2, and a concurrent Kafka integration issue within CHF prevented CDR records from being delivered to ACC. Tushar applied the PCF configuration correction, switching Rivian from Offline to Online on the affected cpcf1/cpcf2 instances. The CHF Kafka integration issue was remediated in parallel. Post-fix validation confirmed that usage visibility was fully restored in ACC, and charging records are now flowing end-to-end through the PCF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC pipeline.	Charging Impact | Visibility Loss ΓÇö Complete loss of charging usage visibility for the Rivian DNN in ACC. While charging transactions were executing successfully at the CHF layer, the absence of CDR delivery to ACC created a blind spot in usage reporting, preventing accurate billing reconciliation and OEM-level usage validation for Rivian. This dual-failure scenario (PCF misconfiguration compounded by Kafka delivery failure) represented a systemic observability gap in the charging pipeline.	Isolated root cause to