solated root cause to infrastructure layer (firewall policy change), preventing unnecessary application-level escalation to PCF or CHF software teams. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically ruling out application-layer defects and narrowing the investigation scope to environmental changes. Enabled cross-domain coordination between infrastructure and NF teams, identifying the precise FW policy delta responsible for the connectivity disruption. Validated that both PCF and CHF application behavior remained healthy, avoiding misclassification as a software defect.	No further action required ΓÇö ticket closed. Recommended follow-up actions for operational hardening: (1) Infrastructure team to implement change management controls around firewall policy modifications affecting NF-to-NF communication paths; (2) Establish proactive connectivity monitoring between PCF and Azure CHF to detect similar disruptions before they manifest as 503 errors; (3) Document this incident as a reference case for future infrastructure change impact assessments affecting the PCF Γåö CHF integration path.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Infrastructure stabilization and cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö This incident exposed a critical dependency between firewall change management processes and NF-to-NF connectivity integrity. The disruption demonstrated that infrastructure-layer modifications without adequate NF impact assessment can directly compromise policy establishment and charging integration flows. This case reinforces the need for change management governance around infrastructure modifications affecting core signaling paths, and serves as a reference for platform resiliency improvements and operational readiness posture.	The 503 Service Unavailable errors on PCF during CreateSMPolicy were not caused by an application-layer defect on either PCF or CHF. The root cause was an infrastructure connectivity failure between the PCF and Azure-hosted CHF, directly attributable to a firewall policy change ΓÇö the only identified environmental delta. Both NFs were operating correctly at the application layer; the broken layer was infrastructure (FW/network path). Once FW policies were corrected, the PCF Γåö CHF path was restored and policy establishment resumed without any application-level intervention. This confirms the failure mode as infrastructure-driven, not application-driven, and highlights the fragility of cross-cloud NF integration paths to uncoordinated infrastructure changes.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	infrastructure	{PCF,CHF}		t	2026-05-26 18:29:38.948724+00	2026-05-27 15:07:45.478013+00	f	\N
30	1	3	2026-04-03-00030	CTAP-72094	2026-04-03	\N	IMS / SBC / PROVISIONING	IMS SBC wnv5a0cncs301c	Closed	EPS Fallback validation failure observed in the IoT domain following an SBC upgrade on node wnv5a0cncs301c. Post-upgrade, GLS provisioning entries were missing from the SBC, causing EPS Fallback test cases to fail consistently. The affected flow spans the IMS/SBC signaling path where GLS provisioning is a prerequisite for proper EPS Fallback behavior. Expected behavior: EPS Fallback procedures should complete successfully with GLS provisioning intact on the upgraded SBC. Observed behavior: EPS Fallback test cases failed due to absent GLS provisioning data, breaking the IMS signaling chain required for fallback scenarios.	Root cause identified and resolved. Investigation confirmed that the SBC upgrade on wnv5a0cncs301c did not preserve GLS provisioning data, resulting in EPS Fallback test case failures. Once GLS provisioning was restored on the upgraded SBC, the test case executed as expected and passed validation. The issue has been classified as a post-upgrade configuration gap ΓÇö the upgrade process did not carry forward the required GLS provisioning state. RCA is complete: the failure was definitively traced to missing GLS provisioning post-upgrade, not to any application-level or signaling defect. No further investigation is required.	Release Certification Risk ΓÇö EPS Fallback test case failure blocked IoT validation and certification progress. The missing GLS provisioning post-upgrade introduced a configuration gap that prevented successful completion of a critical test scenario, directly impacting release readiness timelines for the IMS/SBC domain.	Isolated root cause to a post-upgrade GLS provisioning gap on the SBC, preventing misclassification as an application or signaling defect. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing the investigation scope to the provisioning layer rather than pursuing unnecessary deep-dive into EPS Fallback logic or IMS signaling