nd the  CHFs VIP. Under tshoot in CTAP-78097.	Charging Impact | E2E Flow Disruption | OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö The CHF replication inconsistency directly blocks Honda 5GSA charging validation, preventing successful OEM onboarding certification. Inconsistent Offer ID data undermines the integrity of charging records and creates instability across end-to-end testing scenarios. Until the replication mismatch is resolved, Honda 5GSA E2E validation cannot be reliably completed, posing a risk to OEM delivery timelines.	Isolated root cause to the CHF replication/synchronization layer by systematically narrowing the investigation scope across two separate blockers (CDEX-508236 and IOTQA-1154). Accelerated troubleshooting by resolving CDEX-508236 and eliminating it as a contributing factor, enabling focused investigation on the remaining CHF database mismatch. Enabled cross-domain coordination between CHF replication teams and OEM validation stakeholders, preventing unnecessary escalation paths and ensuring the correct team owns the remaining remediation effort.	1. CHF team to investigate and remediate the Offer ID replication mismatch identified under IOTQA-1154, ensuring active Offer IDs are consistently synchronized to the CHF database. 2. Upon CHF confirmation of fix deployment, execute Honda 5GSA E2E charging retest to validate that Offer IDs are correctly reflected in charging records. 3. Validate ACC reporting chain to confirm that corrected charging data flows through to downstream observability and billing systems. 4. If retest is successful, close IOTQA-1154 and proceed with Honda 5GSA OEM certification milestone. 5. If retest reveals residual inconsistencies, escalate to CHF engineering for deeper replication layer analysis.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and charging platform integrity ΓÇö This ticket directly impacts Honda 5GSA OEM validation, a key onboarding milestone. The CHF replication inconsistency exposes a syste