20	1	3	2026-03-24-00020	CTAP-60523	2026-03-24	\N	REDIRECTION / AZURE	Azure	In Progress	HTTP redirection flow failure impacting Honda5G OEM validation: subscriber traffic is being served a SNAP (default captive portal) page instead of the expected Honda-branded landing page. The expected behavior is that upon initial data session establishment, the UPF-driven redirection chain (UPF ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ Landing Page endpoint) should intercept the subscriber HTTP request and redirect it to the Honda5G-specific landing page hosted in the Azure environment. Instead, the redirection terminates prematurely or is misrouted, resulting in a generic SNAP page being rendered. The affected E2E flow spans UPF ΓåÆ IPPE redirection logic ΓåÆ PFD (Packet Flow Description) rules ΓåÆ Azure-hosted Honda5G landing page. This indicates a potential gap in the redirection policy configuration, PFD rule application at the UPF, or an IPPE processing anomaly within the Azure cloud infrastructure.	Investigation is actively in progress. The primary symptom ΓÇö SNAP page rendered instead of the Honda5G-branded landing page ΓÇö has been confirmed and reproduced. Initial analysis points to an incomplete or misconfigured redirection chain between the UPF and the IPPE layer. The RCA is currently focused on two hypotheses: (1) UPF is not correctly applying PFD rules that should trigger the Honda-specific redirection, or (2) IPPE is receiving the redirect trigger but failing to route to the correct landing page endpoint in Azure. The SNAP page appearance suggests the default captive portal logic is being invoked, meaning the Honda-specific policy or PFD entry may be missing, expired, or overridden. UPF-level packet inspection and PFD rule validation are the immediate next diagnostic steps. No infrastructure connectivity issues have been reported at this time, narrowing the scope to application/configuration layer behavior.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Honda5G partner validation is directly blocked by the inability to render the correct branded landing page. This redirection failure prevents end-to-end demonstration and certification of the Honda5G subscriber onboarding experience in the Azure environment. If unresolved, this delays OEM acceptance milestones and potentially impacts contractual timelines tied to Honda5G launch readiness.	Identified critical gap between SNAP default captive portal behavior and Honda5G-specific landing page redirection, isolating the issue to the UPF/IPPE/PFD policy chain rather than broader infrastructure failure. This accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing the investigation scope from a general Azure connectivity concern to a targeted redirection policy and PFD rule validation exercise. Prevented unnecessary escalation to Azure infrastructure teams by confirming the platform is reachable and the issue resides in the application/configuration layer of the redirection flow.	1. UPF team to validate that Honda5G-specific PFD rules are correctly provisioned, active, and matching subscriber traffic patterns in the Azure environment. 2. Confirm IPPE redirection logic is receiving the correct trigger from UPF and routing to the Honda5G landing page URL rather than falling back to SNAP default. 3. Review PFD rule precedence and expiration to ensure Honda5G entries are not being overridden or aged out. 4. Validate Azure-hosted Honda5G landing page endpoint is reachable and responding correctly from the IPPE layer. 5. Once PFD and IPPE configurations are confirmed, execute end-to-end retest of the subscriber redirection flow. 6. If retest is successful, document the root cause and coordinate with Honda5G OEM validation team to resume acceptance testing.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This ticket is directly tied to Honda5G partner launch readiness and validates the platform's ability to deliver branded subscriber experiences through the UPF redirection chain in the Azure cloud environment. Resolution is c