e device firmware behavior, preventing unnecessary escalation to core network domains (PCF, CHF, infrastructure). Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically ruling out network-side redirection, policy enforcement, and server-side landing page hosting as contributing factors. Protected OEM onboarding timeline by ensuring the defect was correctly attributed to the device layer rather than triggering cross-domain investigations across core platform teams. Validated that the full redirection chain from notification trigger through landing page delivery operates correctly, confirming platform integrity for the Subaru integration path.	{"Continue monitoring client-side landing page rendering consistency across subsequent device firmware releases on real UE endpoints.","Establish a device behavior baseline for Subaru OEM redirection flows to quickly differentiate client-side anomalies from network-side issues in future occurrences.","Coordinate with the OEM onboarding team to document the device release dependency as a known variable in redirection flow validation.","Confirm with the device/UE team that the firmware fix is persistent and does not regress with future software updates."}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and cross-domain stabilization. This ticket directly validates the integrity of the notification-triggered redirection chain critical to Subaru OEM integration. Correct root cause attribution to the device layer ΓÇö rather than core platform ΓÇö protects platform confidence metrics and prevents mischaracterization of platform health during QBR reporting. Demonstrates mature triage methodology that preserves engineering bandwidth across core domains.	The landing page error_timeout was not caused by any failure in the core redirection chain (notification trigger, PCF policy enforcement, redirection server, or infrastructure connectivity). The entire network-side redirection path was validated as functioning correctly