52	1	3	2026-03-18-00052	CTAP-58892	2026-03-18	\N	Provisioning / IMS	IoT Labs / Multiple OEM Validation Environments	Closed	SMS MO (Mobile Originated) and MT (Mobile Terminated) flows were failing consistently across all OEM IoT validation scenarios, blocking end-to-end SMS delivery and processing. The expected behavior was for SMS traffic to be successfully delivered, properly provisioned, and correctly processed across IMS and provisioning domains. The failure pattern ΓÇö impacting all OEMs uniformly ΓÇö pointed toward a systemic provisioning or SIM configuration inconsistency rather than an isolated network function defect. The affected E2E path spans SIM provisioning (MIND) ΓåÆ IMS/SMS feature enablement ΓåÆ SMS MO/MT delivery across IoT onboarding flows. Root cause was ultimately confirmed: during SUPI provisioning, the SMS component within MIND was left incomplete. The first SIM carried residual provisioning inconsistencies in MIND, and the second SIM was provisioned as legacy, causing fallback to LTE for SMS completion ΓÇö which explained why SMS succeeded when the device was moved from NR Only to NR/LTE.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 04/20/2026. Root cause was definitively isolated to the SIM/provisioning domain within MIND. Investigation confirmed that when the SUPI was provisioned, the SMS portion in MIND was left incomplete, directly causing MO/MT SMS failures. Additionally, one SIM carried legacy provisioning artifacts in MIND, and a second SIM was provisioned as legacy, triggering an LTE fallback path that masked the NR-only failure. Structured troubleshooting ruled out SMF, PCF, charging, and transport domains early in the investigation cycle. SMS MO/MT functionality was restored after correcting the MIND provisioning configuration, and all OEM validation activities resumed without further SMS inconsistencies.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö SMS validation was blocked across all OEM IoT scenarios, halting end-to-end testing continuity and delaying IoT onboarding and certification activities. The provisioning gap in MIND created a systemic failure affecting both MO and MT SMS flows, with potential to cascade into broader OEM validation schedule delays if not rapidly isolated.	Isolated root cause to SIM provisioning and IMS-related configuration domains within MIND, preventing unnecessary escalation toward SMF, PCF, charging, and transport teams. Accelerated RCA identification through structured cross-domain troubleshooting that systematically narrowed the investigation scope from a multi-NF surface to a single provisioning subsystem. Enabled coordinated resolution between provisioning, IMS, and SMS support teams, restoring OEM validation continuity and preserving onboarding timelines. Validated that the NR/LTE fallback behavior observed on the second SIM was a direct consequence of legacy provisioning ΓÇö not a network design issue ΓÇö avoiding misclassification of the defect.	Continue monitoring SMS provisioning consistency across all OEM IoT scenarios to detect any recurrence of incomplete MIND configurations. Preserve the validated SIM and provisioning baseline as a reference standard for future IoT onboarding activities. Formalize the troubleshooting findings ΓÇö particularly the MIND SMS provisioning gap and legacy SIM fallback behavior ΓÇö into a reusable knowledge artifact for future SMS-related investigations. Recommend provisioning workflow review with the MIND team to introduce validation checkpoints that ensure SMS feature completeness during SUPI provisioning, preventing recurrence at scale.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacted the ability to certify IoT SMS functionality across multiple OEM validation environments. Rapid isolation of the root cause to the MIND provisioning domain preserved onboarding timelines and demonstrated the platform's ability to resolve cross-domain provisioning gaps without unnecessary escalation. The findings strengthen provisioning integrity practices critical to scaling IoT onboarding operations.	The root cause was a provisioning gap in MIND: when the SUPI was provisioned, the SMS feature component was left incomplete, causing systematic MO/MT SMS failures across all OEM IoT scenarios on NR Only. The first SIM carried residual provisioning inconsistencies within MIND, while the second SIM was provisioned using a legacy profile, which triggered an automatic LTE fallback ΓÇö explaining why SMS succeeded when the device was moved from NR Only to NR/LTE. This is a configuration-layer defect within the provisioning subsystem, not an application or infrastructure issue. The failure was path-dependent: NR Only path failed due to incomplete SMS enablement in MIND, while the NR/LTE path succeeded because legacy provisioning caused the device to fall back to LTE where SMS could be completed through the legacy signaling path. No defects were identified in SMF, PCF, charging, or transport domains. The key takeaway is that SUPI provisioning workflows in MIND require explicit SMS feature completeness validation to prevent this class of systemic failure during OEM onboarding.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{IMS,HSS,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27 18:45:00.188519+00	2026-05-27 19:04:22.388453+00	f	\N
