130	1	3	03/20/2026-00133	CTAP-59948	2026-03-20	\N	POLICY / CHARGING	On-Prem / Toyota IoT Validation Environment	Closed	Quota enforcement disruption identified in PCF Γåö CHF Γåö SMF policy execution chain within the Toyota IoT On-Prem validation environment. A trial SOC scenario associated with OfferId 2018 was observed allowing data consumption beyond 3GB without triggering the expected quota exhaustion behavior, redirect flow, or service restriction mechanisms. Expected behavior dictated that upon reaching the 3GB threshold, the trial SOC should expire, cease normal traffic, and redirect the user accordingly. Observed behavior showed the UE continuing to download data beyond the expected quota limit without any enforcement action. The issue raised concerns across charging validation, quota enforcement behavior, and policy execution consistency within the E2E path spanning SMF ΓåÆ PCF ΓåÆ CHF policy and charging domains.	Investigation concluded with root cause confirmed. Initial troubleshooting validated that charging and session establishment were fully operational, with the investigation narrowing focus to PCF policy logic, charging threshold behavior, quota synchronization, and downstream enforcement interactions between SMF, CHF, and policy domains. Threshold enforcement initially appeared inconsistent while traffic continuity remained active beyond the expected quota limit. Upon deeper analysis, it was confirmed that OfferId 2018 is configured as an unlimited data offer with no 3GB cap, meaning the observed behavior ΓÇö data consumption beyond 3GB without enforcement ΓÇö was entirely consistent with the offer definition. The perceived quota enforcement failure was a misclassification based on incorrect assumptions about the trial SOC's data limits. Issue validated as working as designed and closed on 04/03/2026.	Policy Enforcement Validation Risk ΓÇö Incorrect assumptions about OfferId 2018 trial SOC quota limits created perceived charging and policy inconsistency, temporarily reducing confidence in quota enforcement and billing accuracy within the On-Prem Toyota IoT validation environment. Potential for misclassified defect escalation toward PCF, CHF, and SMF teams was mitigated through targeted root cause analysis.	Validated working-as-designed behavior avoiding misclassification as a platform defect, preventing unnecessary escalation toward transport, provisioning, UE connectivity, and NF development domains. Accelerated troubleshooting by isolating the investigation scope to policy enforcement, quota handling, and charging interaction domains. Identified that OfferId 2018 is an unlimited data offer, resolving the perceived quota enforcement gap at the configuration and business logic layer rather than the application layer. Increased organizational visibility into offer-level configuration dependencies impacting policy and charging validation scenarios in On-Prem environments.	No further technical remediation required ΓÇö issue confirmed as working as designed. Recommend updating trial SOC test documentation to accurately reflect OfferId 2018 unlimited data configuration and prevent recurrence of misclassified defects. Validate that test plan assumptions for all trial SOC scenarios are aligned with actual offer definitions in PCF and CHF. Socialize findings with Toyota IoT validation stakeholders to ensure consistent understanding of quota enforcement expectations per offer type. Archive RCA findings for future reference in charging and policy validation governance.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Charging platform integrity ΓÇö This initiative validated that perceived quota enforcement failures in the Toyota IoT On-Prem environment were attributable to offer-level configuration assumptions rather than platform defects. The resolution strengthens confidence in PCF and CHF policy execution correctness and reinforces the importance of aligning test plan assumptions with actual offer definitions, a crit