nt visibility of both MO and MT SMS records within Control Center is foundational for OEM validation confidence, reporting accuracy, and platform observability maturity. Resolution strengthens the charging and reporting platform's reliability posture for current and future OEM onboarding programs.	The defect was not in SMS MT execution ΓÇö MT messages were confirmed functional on other accounts, proving the transport and IMS layers were intact. The failure was isolated to the ACC ingestion / Control Center synchronization layer, where MT records were not being surfaced in the reporting interface despite successful delivery. MO records were consistently visible, indicating a divergence in how ACC processes or surfaces MO vs MT record types. This points to either an account-specific configuration gap within ACC, a Control Center synchronization filter excluding MT events for certain account profiles, or a Cisco-side reporting logic discrepancy. The critical distinction ΓÇö execution working, visibility broken ΓÇö prevented misclassification of the issue as a network or provisioning defect and directed investigation to the correct observability domain.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{ACC}		t	2026-05-27 18:46:57.474594+00	2026-05-27 19:04:13.720624+00	f	\N
54	1	3	2026-03-19-00054	CTAP-59219	2026-03-19	\N	REGISTRATION / ATTACH	Darkstar Lab 4 / Tesla Hedy DNN	Closed	A registration and attach failure was identified within Darkstar Lab 4 using the Tesla Hedy DNN, disrupting IoT E2E validation activities and Darkstar Line Up integration continuity. Devices were unable to successfully complete the attach procedure into the targeted environment. The expected behavior was seamless attach and registration into the Darkstar Lab 4 infrastructure. Initial troubleshooting scope covered AMF selection behavior, mobility handling, TAC configuration, and N26 inter-RAT handover procedures. The failure was traced to an incorrect AMF selection path where a 4G idle device performing TAU toward 5G via the N26 interface on MME6 was being directed to RDM52d AMF (associated with Northrim Lab 1) instead of the expected RD2WA65 AMF (Darkstar Line Up 4). The issue was ultimately isolated to TAC range misconfiguration influencing mobility and AMF selection logic, constituting a cross-domain registration disruption across the MME ΓåÆ N26 ΓåÆ AMF selection chain.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 03/23/2026. Root cause analysis confirmed that a 4G idle device performing Tracking Area Update (TAU) toward 5G via the N26 interface was being incorrectly routed by MME6 to the RDM52d AMF associated with Northrim Lab 1, rather than the intended RD2WA65 AMF in Darkstar Line Up 4. The AMF team identified the TAC range used during testing as the contributing factor to the incorrect AMF selection. Upon adjusting the TAC range per AMF team guidance and additionally validating a direct 5G attach approach, the device successfully attached. No further attach inconsistencies were observed after re-testing. Attach functionality fully restored and Darkstar validation activities resumed normal operations.	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö Attach validation completely blocked in Darkstar Lab 4, interrupting IoT E2E validation activities and delaying Darkstar integration readiness. Incorrect mobility and AMF selection behavior via the N26 interface disrupted testing continuity and threatened the validation timeline for the Darkstar Line Up program.	Isolated root cause across multiple candidate domains ΓÇö mobility handling, N26 inter-RAT behavior, AMF selection logic, and TAC configuration ΓÇö through structured domain elimination methodology. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, or policy domains by rapidly narrowing the investigation scope to the mobility and registration layer. Improved organizational understanding of inter-lab mobility dependencies and TAC-driven AMF selection behavior. Accelerated resolution by coordinating directly with the AMF team and validating their TAC range recommendation in real time, restoring platform validation continuity within four days.	Preserve validated TAC configuration baseline as reference for future Darkstar Lab 4 attach procedures. Continue monitoring AMF selection behavior during subsequent inter-RAT mobility validations to ensure no regression. Catalog troubleshooting methodology and findings for reuse in future N26-related mobility investigations across lab environments. Document inter-lab TAC boundary mapping to prevent recurrence of cross-lab AMF misselection scenarios.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö This initiative addressed a mobility and registration-layer failure that blocked IoT E2E validation and Darkstar integration readiness. The structured isolation of TAC-driven AMF misselection across the N26 inter-RAT boundary strengthens the organization's ability to manage inter-lab mobility dependencies and ensures continuity of lab certification activities critical to platform onboarding timelines.	The attach failure was caused by an incorrect TAC range configuration influencing AMF selection during 4G-to-5G inter-RAT mobility via the N26 interface. MME6, processing a Tracking Area Update from a 4G idle device, selected the RDM52d AMF (Northrim Lab 1) instead of the intended RD2WA65 AMF (Darkstar Line Up 4) due to overlapping or misconfigured TAC boundaries. The AMF team confirmed that the TAC range used in testing was outside the expected scope for Darkstar Lab 4, causing the N26 procedure to resolve to the wrong target AMF. Resolution was achieved by adjusting the TAC range per AMF team guidance and additionally validating a direct 5G attach path, both of which succeeded. This was a configuration-layer issue at the mobility/registration boundary ΓÇö not an application defect ΓÇö confirming that TAC planning and inter-lab boundary segregation are critical dependencies for multi-lab validation environments.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{Infrastructure,AMF}		t	2026-05-27 18:46:00.174214+00	2026-05-27 19:04:18.089217+00	f	\N
