60	1	3	2026-03-23-00060	CTAP-60496	2026-03-23	\N	CHARGING / POLICY / PROBES	FN-IoT / 5GSA / SMF / CHF / Probes Environment	Closed	A charging visibility disruption was identified within the SMF ΓåÆ CHF converged charging signaling path during FN-IoT 5GSA validation activities. Following a policy-related transition from DSSTI/DAI to DSSTI/DPRI, spending limit control began functioning successfully; however, no CreateConvergedCharging requests appeared to be generated from the SMF toward the CHF. The absence of expected charging signaling was observed across network captures and probes, impacting charging validation confidence, charging visibility analysis, and FN-IoT E2E validation continuity. Expected behavior dictates that the SMF should generate and transmit CreateConvergedCharging requests to the CHF as part of standard converged charging flows. The discrepancy between operational spending limit control and absent charging signaling triggered a multi-domain investigation spanning SMF behavior, CHF interaction, policy logic, and probes/observability integrity.	Investigation concluded with root cause successfully isolated. Initial troubleshooting focused on SMF charging generation logic, policy interaction behavior, and signaling visibility across the SMF ΓåÆ CHF path. Coordination was established between validation/testing teams, charging domain owners, and probes/trace-analysis groups. No evidence of missing or defective charging logic was found within the core network functions themselves ΓÇö SMF and CHF behavior was validated as operationally correct. The absence of expected signaling was confined to network captures and probe traces, which shifted the investigation focus toward probes visibility, packet capture integrity, and trace collection behavior. The RCA conclusively determined that the core was functioning as expected, and the observability gap originated from the Probes domain, where signaling between SMF and CHF was not being captured. The Testing Team