tion is confirmed"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Investigation led end-to-end by C├⌐sar Villagra with cross-domain coordination between validation/testing teams, charging domains, and probes/trace-analysis groups. Follow-up remediation transitioned to Testing Team Γåö Probes Team.	Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative exposed a critical gap in the probes/observability layer that masked operationally correct charging signaling, directly threatening the integrity of FN-IoT 5GSA charging validation results. The structured domain isolation approach prevented misclassification of a working core as defective, protecting cross-domain engineering bandwidth and maintaining release certification confidence. The reusable methodology established positions the program to detect and resolve observability-layer gaps proactively in future validation cycles, strengthening overall charging platform integrity and E2E validation continuity.	The converged charging signaling path between SMF and CHF was operationally intact ΓÇö CreateConvergedCharging requests were being generated and processed correctly at the core level. The root cause was isolated to the Probes/observability layer, where signaling between SMF and CHF was not being captured in network traces. This is a classic observability-layer failure pattern: the policy transition from DSSTI/DAI to DSSTI/DPRI successfully enabled spending limit control, confirming that the SMF was correctly interacting with the charging and policy domains. The absence of charging signaling in captures was a visibility gap, not a core defect. The critical differentiation between signaling generation (application layer ΓÇö validated as working) and signaling observability (probes/capture layer ΓÇö confirmed as the failure point) prevented a multi-domain false-positive escalation and preserved validation continuity.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{SMF,CHF,PCF}		t	2026-05-27 18:48:58.207255+00	2026-05-27 19:04:03.308087+0