58	1	3	03/20/2026-00058	CTAP-59948	2026-03-20	\N	POLICY / CHARGING	On-Prem / Toyota IoT Validation Environment	Closed	A quota enforcement anomaly was identified in the Toyota IoT validation environment where a trial SOC associated with OfferId 2018 allowed a UE to download beyond the initially expected 3GB threshold without triggering quota exhaustion, redirect flow, or service restriction mechanisms. The expected behavior was that upon reaching the 3GB limit, the trial SOC would expire, cease normal traffic, and redirect the user accordingly. However, the UE continued downloading data beyond the anticipated quota boundary. The investigation traversed the PCF Γåö CHF Γåö SMF policy and charging enforcement chain to determine whether the behavior constituted a genuine defect or a design-compliant response. Upon root cause analysis, it was confirmed that OfferId 2018 is provisioned as an unlimited data offer with no 3GB cap, meaning the observed behavior was consistent with the configured policy ΓÇö classifying this as working as designed. The affected E2E flow spans policy definition (PCF), charging threshold enforcement (CHF), and session management enforcement (SMF) within the On-Prem Toyota IoT domain.	The investigation has been concluded and the ticket is closed as of 04/03/2026. Initial troubleshooting focused on validating PCF policy logic, CHF threshold triggers, quota synchronization, and downstream enforcement interactions between SMF, CHF, and the policy domain. Charging and session establishment were confirmed operational throughout. The root cause analysis revealed that OfferId 2018 is configured as an unlimited data offer ΓÇö not subject to a 3GB quota cap. The observed behavior of unrestricted data download beyond 3GB was therefore validated as working as designed. The initial assumption of a quota enforcement failure was ruled out. No defect was identified in PCF policy execution, CHF threshold handling, or SMF enforcement logic. The apparent inconsistency was attributable to an incorrect expectation regarding the offer definition rather than a platform defect.	Policy Routing Issue ΓÇö Initial assessment suggested incorrect quota enforcement behavior, potential billing and policy inconsistency, and trial SOC restrictions not being properly applied, which reduced confidence in charging and policy validation scenarios. Upon RCA completion, the impact was reclassified: the behavior was confirmed as design-compliant for OfferId 2018 (unlimited data), eliminating the risk of billing inaccuracy or policy enforcement failure. The residual impact is limited to the need for improved offer-level documentation and test case alignment to prevent future misclassification of working-as-designed behavior as defects.	Isolated root cause to offer-level configuration clarity, confirming OfferId 2018 as an unlimited data plan ΓÇö preventing misclassification of design-compliant behavior as a platform defect. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically narrowing the investigation scope across PCF, CHF, and SMF enforcement domains, ruling out transport, provisioning, and UE connectivity issues early in the cycle. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward infrastructure and connectivity teams by focusing analysis on the policy and charging interaction layer. Validated working-as-designed behavior, avoiding false defect attribution and preserving engineering bandwidth. Increased visibility of the importance of offer-definition alignment in On-Prem IoT validation environments, contributing to improved test case governance for future charging and policy scenarios.	{"Document OfferId 2018 offer definition and its unlimited data classification for future test case reference","Update Toyota IoT validation test matrix to align trial SOC scenarios with correct offer-level expectations","Conduct knowledge transfer with Tier 1 and validation teams on offer-to-policy mapping to prevent recurrence of misclassified defects","Validate that other trial SOC OfferIds with actual quota caps (non-unlimited) enforce threshold, redirect, and expiration behavior correctly","Establish offer-definition pre-validation checkpoint in the test planning phase to ensure expected behavior aligns with provisioned offer parameters"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö RCA investigation, cross-domain analysis across PCF/CHF/SMF, and final working-as-designed determination were driven by C├⌐sar Villagra.	Charging platform integrity and release certification readiness ΓÇö this investigation validated that the PCF Γåö CHF Γåö SMF quota enforcement chain operates correctly when aligned with the provisioned offer definition. The outcome reinforces the need for offer-level governance in IoT validation environments to prevent false defect attribution that could delay release certification cycles. Additionally, the finding contributes to cross-domain stabilization by establishing a precedent for offer-definition pre-validation in policy and charging test scenarios.	The perceived quota enforcement failure was not a defect in PCF policy logic, CHF threshold handling, or SMF enforcement behavior. Root cause analysis confirmed that OfferId 2018 is provisioned as an unlimited data offer ΓÇö meaning there is no 3GB quota cap to enforce. The UE's ability to download beyond 3GB was fully consistent with the offer configuration. The failure point was in the test expectation layer, not the platform execution layer. No NF failed ΓÇö PCF correctly applied the policy associated with OfferId 2018, CHF correctly processed charging without triggering a non-existent threshold, and SMF correctly maintained the session without restriction. The classification is working as designed. The key learning is that offer-definition alignment must be validated prior to test execution to avoid misattribution of design-compliant behavior as a platform defect, particularly in On-Prem IoT environments where offer catalogs may differ from lab or cloud configurations.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	working_as_designed	{PCF,CHF,SMF}		t	2026-05-27 18:47:59.034686+00	2026-05-27 19:04:08.645162+00	f	\N
