he reliability of charging validation across the 5GSA FN-IoT platform. The ability to distinguish between genuine core defects and observability infrastructure limitations is critical for release certification readiness and charging platform integrity. Establishing a validated troubleshooting methodology for signaling observability gaps strengthens cross-domain stabilization and ensures that future charging validation activities are not delayed or mischaracterized due to probes layer deficiencies.	The converged charging signaling between SMF and CHF was confirmed to be operationally intact at the core NF layer ΓÇö the SMF was generating CreateConvergedCharging requests as expected following the DSSTI/DAI to DSSTI/DPRI policy transition. The root cause was isolated to the probes/observability infrastructure, which failed to capture the signaling between SMF and CHF, creating a false impression of missing charging behavior. The critical distinction was between signaling generation (application layer ΓÇö working correctly) and signaling observability (probes/capture infrastructure ΓÇö broken). This is a textbook observability layer failure, not an application or configuration defect, and the structured domain isolation approach prevented misclassification and unnecessary multi-domain escalation.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{SMF,CHF}		f	2026-05-27 20:57:31.649637+00	2026-05-27 20:57:31.649637+00	f	Root cause confirmed: no defect exists in the core SMF or CHF charging logic. The CreateConvergedCharging signaling was being generated and transmitted correctly between SMF and CHF, but the probes/capture infrastructure failed to record this signaling, creating a false visibility gap. Issue ownership transferred to the Probes team for remediation of capture integrity.
