itical validation for traffic-classification stability and redirect/landing-page consistency across the UPF Γåö IPPE Γåö APPID chain. Direct dependency for confirming UC 5.1.0.18 behavioral improvements and establishing a validated baseline required for OEM onboarding validation reliability. Failure to validate would have left previously observed IPPE synchronization defects, redirect anomalies, and landing-page failures unverified ΓÇö posing risk to production deployment confidence and downstream integration activities.	Established validated behavioral baseline for PFD synchronization, APPID propagation, and IPPE execution under UC 5.1.0.18 ΓÇö directly confirming resolution of previously observed landing-page and redirect defects. Accelerated release certification confidence by isolating and verifying three critical propagation scenarios (rule changes, new rule addition, BIG PFD) within a controlled lab environment. Prevented potential production regression by proactively validating traffic-classification tagging accuracy post-upgrade. Delivered structured evidence that UC 5.1.0.18 improvements operate as intended, enabling downstream onboarding and integration activities to proceed with verified platform behavior.	Validation completed and ticket closed (04/15/2026). Recommended follow-on actions: (1) Preserve validated baseline results (GM-4102-7 rule propagation, BIG PFD tagging) as reference artifacts for future UC version upgrades and regression testing; (2) Leverage confirmed PFD/IPPE synchronization behavior to support OEM onboarding validation activities in production environments; (3) Monitor for any recurrence of landing-page or redirect inconsistencies in production deployments running UC 5.1.0.18 or later; (4) Extend BIG PFD validation scenarios to additional Consumer PODs if cross-pod consistency verification is required; (5) Document validated behavior as input for QBR release certification readiness reporting.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Release certification readiness ΓÇö this initiative directly validated that UC 5.1.0.18 resolves previously identified IPPE/PFD synchronization defects, traffic-classification anomalies, and redirect/landing-page instabilities. The validated baseline enables confident release progression and establishes verified platform behavior for OEM onboarding enablement. Additionally contributes to cross-domain stabilization by confirming correct E2E propagation across the UPF Γåö IPPE Γåö APPID chain.	Validation confirmed that under UC 5.1.0.18 (SMF 56a / UPF 60f), the PFD-to-IPPE propagation chain operates correctly across three critical scenarios. APPID PFD rule modifications (e.g., adding URLs to GM-4102-7) are accurately reflected in IPPE upon DNN attachment. New PFD rules associated with APP IDs propagate consistently. BIG PFD changes, once synchronized to IPPE, result in correct traffic-attempt tagging ΓÇö confirming that the classification engine processes large rule sets as designed. This validates that previously observed defects (IPPE synchronization failures, redirect inconsistencies, landing-page errors) are attributable to pre-5.1.0.18 behavior and are resolved in the current UC version. The root cause of prior issues was application-layer synchronization behavior in earlier UC builds, not infrastructure or configuration defects.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,SMF}		t	2026-05-27 18:51:00.370881+00	2026-05-27 19:03:54.400685+00	f	\N
63	1	3	2026-03-24-00063	CTAP-61094	2026-03-24	\N	Redirection / OEM Validation	Stellantis / adn2 / adn4 / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	A redirection execution failure was identified within the Stellantis Enterprise IoT validation environment affecting adn2 and adn4 DNN scenarios. Observed behavior indicated that users were being redirected to the SNAP page instead of the expected MyVehicle OEM landing page, confirming that redirect signaling was triggering but final landing-page delivery was failing. The disruption impacted the full captive portal execution chain, blocking REDIR validation, OEM onboarding verification, and Enterprise IoT E2E readiness activities for Stellantis use cases. Initial troubleshooting focused on redirect execution consistency, UPF/IPPE behavior, traffic classification, and PFD synchronization conditions. The affected flow spans the UPF ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ PFD ΓåÆ REDIR ΓåÆ OEM Landing Page delivery path, with the failure isolated to the IPPE layer where PFD modifications were not being properly applied due to an incomplete code vector deletion bug.	Root cause was identified and confirmed. Microsoft performed an IPPE reboot which restored expected behavior. The RCA determined that the issue was directly related to a known defect tracked under CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348, where PFD modifications pushed via PFDM were not being incorporated into multiple PDRs due to an incomplete code vector deletion within the IPPE. This defect was originally identified in UC 5.1.0.15 and the permanent fix is included in UC 5.1.0.18. Prior to RCA confirmation, redirect signaling was validated as operational (SNAP behavior was successfully triggering), isolating the failure specifically to the IPPE PFD handling layer rather than policy generation, charging, provisioning, or IMS domains. The issue was resolved following IPPE reboot and is closed as of 04/02/2026.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Stellantis REDIR validation was fully blocked across adn2 and adn4 Enterprise DNN scenarios. Captive portal execution and onboarding validation were incomplete, directly affecting OEM user-experience certification. The failure introduced delays in Enterprise IoT E2E readiness activities and posed a risk to Stellantis onboarding milestone delivery. The issue exposed a recurring platform vulnerability in IPPE PFD synchronization that, if unpatched, could affect broader OEM redirect validation campaigns.	Successfully isolated the root cause to the IPPE PFD handling layer, distinguishing between operational redirect signaling and failed OEM landing-page execution ΓÇö preventing unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, IMS, or policy-generation domains. Correlated the observed behavior with a known defect (CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348), accelerating time-to-resolution by linking the incident to an existing RCA and confirmed fix path in UC 5.1.0.18. Increased cross-domain visibility into recurring SNAP-vs-OEM-landing-page behavior patterns, enabling proactive detection of IPPE PFD synchronization failures in future OEM validation cycles. Enabled targeted remediation through IPPE reboot coordination with Microsoft, restoring Stellantis onboarding validation readiness without broader platform disruption.	{"Validate that UC 5.1.0.18 deployment permanently resolves the IPPE PFD incomplete code vector deletion defect across all affected DNN scenarios","Execute controlled re-testing of Stellantis adn2 and adn4 REDIR flows post-IPPE reboot to confirm sustained MyVehicle landing-page delivery","Compare current behavior against previously observed OEM redirect inconsistencies to confirm pattern closure","Monitor SNAP vs MyVehicle redirect execution behavior over sustained test cycles to confirm no regression","Coordinate with Microsoft on IPPE patch deployment timeline for UC 5.1.0.18 to eliminate dependency on manual IPPE reboots","Update CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348 with cross-reference to CTAP-61094 for defect tracking completeness"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö TPM-led investigation with cross-domain RCA coordination across UPF, IPPE, and Microsoft infrastructure teams. Escalation to Microsoft for IPPE reboot and correlation with known defect CTAP-17630 managed directly by C├⌐sar Villagra.	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This incident directly impacted Stellantis Enterprise IoT validation readiness and exposed a recurring IPPE PFD synchronization vulnerability that affects the platform's ability to deliver consistent OEM captive portal experiences. Resolution and permanent patching via UC 5.1.0.18 are critical to ensuring Enterprise IoT E2E certification milestones and cross-OEM redirect validation campaign stability. The incident reinforces the need for proactive IPPE PFD health monitoring as a platform resiliency initiative.	The IPPE layer failed to incorporate PFD modifications into multiple PDRs due to an incomplete code vector deletion bug (identified in UC 5.1.0.15, fix in UC 5.1.0.18). This caused the redirect execution chain to default to SNAP instead of delivering the Stellantis MyVehicle OEM landing page ΓÇö even though redirect signaling from the policy layer was functioning correctly. The failure was not in policy generation (PCF), charging (CHF), provisioning, or IMS ΓÇö it was isolated entirely to the UPF/IPPE PFD handling path. The IPPE reboot by Microsoft restored PFD state consistency as a temporary remediation, but the permanent fix requires UC 5.1.0.18 deployment to address the root cause code vector deletion defect tracked under CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348. This pattern of IPPE PFD desynchronization represents a systemic risk to all OEM redirect validation scenarios until the patch is deployed.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,IPPE,PCF,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27 18:50:31.250884+00	2026-05-27 19:03:56.970784+00	f	\N
