ecture alignment discussions are ongoing while the DS26.04 deployment timeline is being finalized. No lab validation has been executed to date due to the release dependency.	Observability Validation Blocked | Architecture Migration Decision Pending ΓÇö The absence of summary trace support in the current AON UDM release directly blocks UDM ΓåÆ BSA integration validation, observability readiness certification, and production migration planning. Downstream impact extends to Chicago and Detroit FFA testing timelines (targeted June/July), DS26.02 Ericsson migration readiness, and the long-term observability architecture evolution for AON environments. Without resolution, the organization risks delaying the transition from probe-based to UDM log-based observability, impacting future troubleshooting capabilities and observability standardization across production environments.	Identified and surfaced a critical observability capability dependency before it could silently delay downstream lab certification and FFA testing timelines. Elevated what originated as a straightforward logging validation dependency into a strategic architecture alignment discussion, ensuring stakeholders converged around DS26.04 dependencies, migration sequencing, and the coexistence model between probe-based and UDM log-based observability. Separated short-term operational needs (immediate lab validation) from long-term architecture goals (production migration and observability standardization), enabling parallel workstream planning. Framed the migration path and transition approach to prevent misalignment between lab certification activities and production rollout planning, accelerating cross-domain decision-making across UDM, BSA, and observability architecture teams.	{"Await and track deployment of DS26.04 release in AON lab environments (Darkstar and Blackrim)","Execute enablement MOP post-DS26.04 deployment to activate summary trace functionality in UDM","Validate UDM summary trace log generation and BSA ingestion behavior in AON lab","Confirm observability readiness and end-to-end UDM ΓåÆ BSA integration integrity","Define and formalize migration timeline from probe-based observability to UDM log-based observability for production environments","Align production rollout approach with DS26.02 Ericsson migration activities","Validate FFA readiness for Chicago and Detroit testing activities (targeted June/July)","Close JIRA upon successful observability validation and architecture migration alignment"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No | Role: Technical Project Leadership ΓÇö owning end-to-end coordination of observability validation, release dependency tracking, and architecture migration alignment across UDM, BSA, and AON stakeholder teams	Observability readiness | Architecture impact | Release certification readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly supports the AON observability transformation roadmap by enabling UDM log-based troubleshooting capabilities as the strategic replacement for probe-based observability. It introduces critical migration planning for production environments, demonstrating leadership in cross-domain architecture alignment discussions. Successful completion validates DS26.04 readiness, contributes to observability standardization across AON environments, and de-risks FFA testing timelines for Chicago and Detroit. The outcome will define the long-term observability architecture model governing production environments.	The current AON UDM release deployed in Darkstar and Blackrim labs does not support summary trace logging, which is a prerequisite for BSA integration validation. The enabling release is DS26.04, and post-deployment an enablement MOP is required to activate summary trace functionality. This creates a hard blocking dependency for all observability validation activities. Beyond the immediate dependency, the initiative surfaced a strategic architecture decision point: the organization must define the coexistence and transition approach between probe-based observability (currently operational) and UDM log-based observability (target state). DS26.02 Ericsson migration activities in lab and production must be sequenced against DS26.04 lab certification to avoid conflicting rollout timelines. The broken layer is observability capability at the application level ΓÇö the UDM software itself lacks the required functionality, not an infrastructure or configuration issue. Chicago and Detroit FFA testing (June/July) depends on successful resolution of both the release dependency and the architecture alignment decision.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{UDM,BSF,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27 18:57:08.926385+00	2026-05-27 19:03:24.532173+00	f	\N
