maintained, and no service degradation was observed. RCA conclusion: preferred PCF (RD2WA65) suspension triggered expected BSF failover to an equivalently configured alternate PCF, confirming platform resiliency mechanisms are functioning as intended.	PCF Discovery / Failover Validation ΓÇö No Functional Service Impact. The anomaly generated initial confusion regarding expected PCF binding behavior in Darkstar Line Up 4, but did not result in service interruption, policy establishment failure, or routing degradation. The platform maintained full routing continuity, policy delivery integrity, and operational stability through the automatic BSF failover mechanism. No test case failures were recorded, and no downstream charging or subscriber impact was identified.	Successfully differentiated expected BSF failover behavior from a genuine PCF discovery defect, preventing unnecessary escalation toward BSF and PCF development teams. Validated platform resiliency mechanisms by confirming BSF automatic PCF selection logic under preferred-instance suspension conditions. Confirmed locality configuration consistency since Darkstar Day 1 deployment, reinforcing infrastructure configuration integrity. Improved cross-domain understanding of Darkstar failover architecture and PCF selection logic, contributing to enhanced operational troubleshooting governance and reducing future false-positive escalation risk for similar BSF routing observations.	No additional actions required. Failover behavior validated successfully. BSF routing logic confirmed as working as designed. Locality assignment verified. Ticket closed on 05/13/2026. Findings documented to serve as reference baseline for future BSF-driven PCF discovery investigations within the Darkstar environment.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Platform Resiliency Validation ΓÇö This investigation validates BSF resiliency mechanisms and confirms PCF failover continuity behavior within the Darkstar Line Up 4 architecture. The outcome improves organizational understanding of BSF-driven PCF discovery and failover routing, prevents false-positive escalations toward PCF discovery logic defects, and reinforces confidence in the Darkstar platform's ability to maintain policy delivery continuity under preferred-instance unavailability conditions. Directly contributes to release certification readiness and cross-domain stabilization by confirming that failover architecture operates as designed.	Observed Behavior: BSF returned rdmwa25 PCF instead of the expected RD2WA65 PCF during Darkstar Line Up 4 policy discovery. Root Cause: The preferred PCF instance (RD2WA65) was in a suspended state. System Behavior: BSF automatically selected the next available PCF instance (rdmwa25), which carried equivalent configuration and correct locality assignment. The alternate PCF successfully handled policy establishment without degradation. Validation Confirmed: (1) Locality assignment correct since Day 1, (2) BSF failover logic functioning as designed, (3) PCF routing continuity maintained, (4) test case passed without failure. Classification: Working as designed ΓÇö BSF failover mechanism correctly responded to preferred PCF suspension by routing to an equivalently configured alternate instance. Impacted Domains: BSF / PCF discovery and failover architecture. Layer: No defect identified ΓÇö behavior confirmed at the application design layer as an intended resiliency response.	Tier 1	t	working_as_designed	{BSF,PCF,SMF}		t	2026-05-27 18:56:32.689664+00	2026-05-27 19:03:27.090298+00	f	\N
101	1	3	04/02/2026-00102	CTAP-64430	2026-04-02	\N	Policy / PCF / Charging	Northrim / Darkstar Labs ΓÇö PCF / CHF / Redirect Policy Flow	On Hold	Observed behavior: Redirect policy enforcement is failing to produce the expected end-user redirect experience despite successful upstream processing across the CHF ΓåÆ PCF Spending Limit Control (SLC) chain. The redirect policies and redirect URLs are confirmed as generated and delivered by the PCF, yet the final redirect behavior is not being realized at the subscriber level. Expected behavior: Upon successful SLC evaluation triggered by CHF charging authorization, the PCF should generate redirect policies and URLs, which are then enforced downstream to produce the correct redirect experience for the subscriber session. Technical context: The investigation spans the full redirect policy lifecycle ΓÇö from CHF charging authorization, through PCF SLC evaluation and redirect policy generation, to downstream redirect handling and enforcement. Network functions involved include CHF (charging authorization), PCF (SLC processing and redirect policy generation), and the downstream redirect chain (redirect enforcement and URL handling). Affected flow: CHF ΓåÆ PCF (SLC) ΓåÆ Redirect Policy Generation ΓåÆ Redirect URL Delivery ΓåÆ Downstream Redirect Handling ΓåÆ Subscriber Redirect Experience. The disruption point has been isolated to the downstream redirect handling segment of this E2E path, with all upstream components validated as functioning correctly.	Executive Status: Investigation is on hold pending further downstream redirect chain analysis. All upstream charging and policy generation components have been conclusively validated as operational. Troubleshooting Progress: Systematic RCA narrowing has eliminated Spending Limit Control failure and CHF authorization failure as candidate root causes. Per subject matter expert confirmation (Tushar), the successful delivery of redirect policies and redirect URLs by the PCF constitutes definitive proof that SLC processing completed successfully ΓÇö since SLC failure would have prevented policy delivery entirely. RCA Evolution: Initial investigation scope encompassed four candidate failure domains: (1) Spending Limit Control execution, (2) CHF charging authorization, (3) PCF policy generation, and (4) downstream redirect processing. Domains 1, 2, and 3 have been systematically ruled out through evidence-based validation. The RCA has been narrowed to domain 4 ΓÇö downstream redirect handling and redirect chain enforcement. Validated Components: CHF ΓåÆ PCF SLC interaction Γ£à | Redirect policy generation Γ£à | Redirect URL delivery Γ£à. Current RCA Direction: The failure exists downstream from the SLC process ΓÇö specifically in redirect handling, redirect chain enforcement, or redirect URL consumption after successful PCF policy delivery.	E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Redirect policy enforcement chain is incomplete despite successful upstream charging authorization and policy generation. While CHF and PCF SLC domains are confirmed operational, the inability to achieve correct redirect behavior downstream impacts final validation closure for the redirect policy flow. This creates a Release Certification Risk as redirect policy validation cannot be formally closed until downstream redirect handling is fully investigated and confirmed. Additionally, the open investigation introduces a Policy Routing Issue classification given that correctly generated policies are not producing the expected enforcement outcome in the redirect chain.	Eliminated Spending Limit Control and CHF charging authorization as suspected root causes by leveraging policy delivery evidence as definitive proof of upstream processing success, significantly narrowing the investigation scope from four candidate failure domains to one. Accelerated troubleshooting by preventing unnecessary escalation toward the charging domain, avoiding cross-team mobilization of CHF and SLC resources that would have been unwarranted. Enabled precise RCA focus on downstream redirect components rather than core charging logic, reducing investigation cycle time and preserving charging team bandwidth. Demonstrated systematic evidence-based RCA methodology that strengthens troubleshooting governance and prevents false root cause attribution across multi-domain policy and charging interactions.	1. Continue downstream redirect chain investigation to identify the specific component or handoff point where redirect enforcement fails after PCF policy delivery. 2. Validate redirect handling behavior at each stage downstream from the PCF ΓÇö including redirect URL consumption, redirect enforcement at the policy enforcement point, and subscriber session redirect execution. 3. Analyze remaining redirect flow dependencies to determine whether the failure is in configuration, application logic, or infrastructure connectivity within the downstream redirect path. 4. Engage the appropriate downstream redirect handling team (policy enforcement / session management) to perform targeted trace analysis on redirect URL processing. 5. Confirm final redirect behavior after policy enforcement through controlled end-to-end test execution in the Northrim / Darkstar Labs environment. 6. Document validated upstream components (CHF, PCF SLC, redirect policy generation) as confirmed-operational for future reference and close upstream investigation threads. 7. Close JIRA CTAP-64430 after full redirect validation and downstream RCA completion.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support. Tier 1 leads the active investigation and downstream redirect chain analysis. C├⌐sar Villagra provides coordination support, RCA methodology governance, and ensures systematic elimination of candidate root causes to prevent false escalation toward unrelated domains.	Release certification readiness ΓÇö Redirect policy validation is a critical component of policy and charging flow certification, and the open investigation directly impacts the ability to formally close redirect policy validation milestones. Cross-domain stabilization ΓÇö The systematic RCA narrowing methodology demonstrated in this investigation prevents false attribution of redirect failures to the charging domain (CHF/SLC), preserving cross-domain trust and avoiding unnecessary mobilization of charging platform resources. Charging platform integrity ΓÇö By conclusively validating the CHF ΓåÆ PCF SLC interaction chain, this investigation contributes to the overall confidence baseline for the charging platform's operational integrity. The findings reinforce that the charging authorization and policy generation layers are stable and functioning as designed, which is a key data point for QBR reporting on platform health.	The critical technical finding is that successful delivery of redirect policies and redirect URLs by the PCF constitutes definitive proof that Spending Limit Control processing completed successfully ΓÇö since SLC failure would have prevented policy delivery entirely. This insight, confirmed by SME analysis, allowed the investigation to conclusively rule out three of four candidate failure domains (SLC execution, CHF authorization, PCF policy generation) and isolate the issue to the downstream redirect handling layer. The CHF ΓåÆ PCF SLC path is confirmed operational at the application layer, meaning the failure is not in charging logic, not in policy generation, and not in SLC evaluation. The root cause hypothesis at this point is that the downstream redirect chain ΓÇö the components responsible for consuming the redirect URL and enforcing the redirect after PCF policy delivery ΓÇö contains either a configuration gap, an application-level processing defect, or a redirect chain handoff failure. The investigation boundary has been precisely defined: everything upstream of and including PCF redirect policy delivery is working as designed; the defect exists in the redirect enforcement path that follows.	Tier 1	t	application	{CHF,PCF}		t	2026-05-27 19:18:45.403067+00	2026-05-27 20:41:42.726238+00	f	\N
135	1	3	2026-03-24-00138	CTAP-61094	2026-03-24	\N	Redirection / OEM Validation	Stellantis / adn2 / adn4 / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Observed behavior: Users accessing Stellantis Enterprise DNN scenarios on adn2 and adn4 were being redirected to the SNAP page instead of the expected MyVehicle OEM landing page, indicating a break in the final-stage redirect execution chain. Expected behavior: Captive portal redirection should deliver users to the Stellantis MyVehicle landing page as part of OEM onboarding validation flows. Technical context: The issue impacted the UPF ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ PFD-based redirect execution pipeline, where redirect signaling was confirmed operational (SNAP was triggering successfully), but the final OEM landing-page delivery was failing due to an IPPE-level PFD synchronization defect. Affected flow: Enterprise IoT E2E onboarding validation ΓÇö REDIR execution ΓåÆ UPF/IPPE traffic classification ΓåÆ PFD-driven OEM landing-page delivery for Stellantis adn2 and adn4 DNN scenarios.	Investigation concluded and issue resolved. Root cause was confirmed as an IPPE-level PFD modification handling defect, directly correlated with known issue CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348. The IPPE instances failed to incorporate PFD modifications because the PFDM PFD was not being properly associated with multiple PDRs due to an incomplete code vector deletion ΓÇö a defect identified in UC 5.1.0.15. Microsoft performed IPPE reboots as an interim remediation, and the permanent fix is delivered in UC 5.1.0.18. Redirect signaling was validated as operational throughout (SNAP behavior confirmed functional), isolating the failure specifically to the final OEM landing-page execution stage driven by stale PFD state on the IPPEs. Issue closed on 04/02/2026.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Stellantis REDIR validation was blocked across adn2 and adn4 Enterprise DNN scenarios. Captive portal and onboarding validation activities were incomplete, directly delaying Enterprise IoT E2E readiness certification. OEM user-experience validation for the MyVehicle landing page was affected, impacting Stellantis onboarding timeline and partner-facing deliverables.	Successfully isolated the failure boundary between operational redirect signaling (SNAP execution confirmed) and the broken OEM landing-page delivery stage, narrowing the investigation scope to UPF/IPPE/PFD execution domains. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, IMS, or policy-generation teams by demonstrating that policy behavior and redirect triggering were functioning correctly. Correlated the observed behavior with a known PFD handling defect (CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348), accelerating root cause confirmation and enabling targeted remediation via IPPE reboot and identification of the permanent fix in UC 5.1.0.18. Increased organizational visibility of recurring SNAP-vs-OEM-landing-page behavior patterns, contributing to a reusable troubleshooting baseline for future IPPE/PFD-related redirect anomalies.	Validate that UC 5.1.0.18 deployment permanently resolves the PFD modification handling defect across all IPPE instances in the Stellantis IoT lab environment. Execute controlled end-to-end re-testing of Stellantis adn2 and adn4 DNN scenarios to confirm MyVehicle landing-page delivery post-fix. Monitor SNAP vs MyVehicle redirect execution behavior over a sustained period to confirm no regression. Compare post-fix behavior against previously observed OEM redirect inconsistencies documented under CTAP-17630 to validate full defect closure. Update Enterprise IoT E2E readiness tracking to reflect unblocked Stellantis REDIR validation status.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacted Stellantis Enterprise IoT onboarding validation, a critical partner-facing deliverable. Resolution confirms platform readiness for OEM captive portal and redirect execution flows, enabling certification of Enterprise DNN scenarios. The correlation with a known IPPE/PFD defect and identification of the permanent fix in UC 5.1.0.18 strengthens cross-domain stabilization posture and contributes to release certification readiness for the UC 5.1.0.18 upgrade path.	The root cause was an IPPE-level defect where PFD modifications pushed via PFDM were not being incorporated into multiple PDRs due to an incomplete code vector deletion within the IPPE software (UC 5.1.0.15). This caused the IPPEs to operate with stale PFD state, resulting in traffic being classified and redirected to the generic SNAP page instead of the Stellantis MyVehicle OEM landing page. Critically, redirect signaling itself was fully operational ΓÇö the failure was isolated to the PFD-driven traffic classification layer within the IPPE, not the redirect triggering or policy execution layers. Microsoft performed IPPE reboots as interim remediation to force PFD re-synchronization, and the permanent fix addressing the incomplete code vector deletion is delivered in UC 5.1.0.18. This defect is directly correlated with CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348, confirming a known and tracked platform issue rather than an environment-specific anomaly.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,IPPE,PCF}		f	2026-05-27 20:58:57.928177+00	2026-05-27 20:58:57.928177+00	f	Root cause confirmed: IPPE instances failed to apply PFD modifications because the PFDM PFD was not being associated with multiple PDRs due to an incomplete code vector deletion ΓÇö a defect identified in UC 5.1.0.15 and tracked under CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348. Microsoft rebooted the IPPEs as interim remediation to force PFD re-synchronization, and the permanent fix is delivered in UC 5.1.0.18.
