tion defect, charging defect, or policy routing issue was identified. (4) The charging logic, Ericsson SMF behavior, and conditional CDR generation were all validated as functioning correctly. The case-sensitivity provisioning gap in UDR was identified as the contributing factor for the 404 error path, which itself is part of the expected failure-triggered CDR generation chain.	Charging Behavior Clarification | False Positive Defect Elimination ΓÇö The investigation eliminated a potential false-positive defect classification that could have triggered unnecessary escalation across Ericsson SMF, CHF, UDM/UDR, and charging application domains. Additionally, the discovery of the UDR case-sensitive DNN provisioning mismatch clarified an upstream data integrity consideration that, if left unaddressed in future environments, could lead to repeated misdiagnosis of charging flow failures. No production impact; lab validation environment only.	Validated working-as-designed behavior, preventing misclassification of expected charging logic as a platform defect. Isolated the UDR DNN provisioning case-sensitivity mismatch as the root cause of the 404 Not Found error in the SMF ΓåÆ UDM ΓåÆ UDR query path, accelerating troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope to the data provisioning layer. Eliminated unnecessary escalation toward Ericsson SMF, CHF, and charging application teams. Strengthened cross-domain operational knowledge of conditional SID 60 CDR generation logic, TCP handshake dependency, and UDR provisioning integrity requirements. Contributed to charging domain operational maturity by documenting trigger conditions and expected behavior for future reference.	No additional actions required. Behavior confirmed as working as designed and ticket is closed. Recommended documentation actions for operational maturity: (1) Document SID 60 conditional CDR generation trigger logic (TCP handshake failure dependency) in the charging operations knowledge base. (2) Add UDR DNN 