ific handset used during initial testing. When the test was repeated on a different device, the landing page was delivered successfully via the notification flow. Network and core platform behavior validated as fully operational. No network-side corrective actions were required.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Inconsistent landing page validation behavior introduced delays in Subaru onboarding validation activities, reduced confidence in notification-triggered redirect consistency across device types, and surfaced potential client-side compatibility concerns that could affect future OEM onboarding certifications if not properly documented and mitigated.	Successfully differentiated network-side behavior from device/client-side behavior through structured comparative testing, preventing unnecessary escalation toward UPF, PCF, policy, or charging domain teams. Accelerated root cause identification by narrowing investigation scope to the client-side domain within a single session through cross-device SUPI validation. Established a reusable troubleshooting methodology for future client-side redirect failures during OEM onboarding scenarios. Validated core platform integrity under real-UE conditions, preserving confidence in the notification-triggered redirection architecture.	Preserve the comparative validation methodology (cross-device, cross-SUPI testing) as a standard troubleshooting pattern for future notification-triggered redirect investigations. Document device/browser compatibility findings and share with OEM onboarding validation teams to preempt similar issues during future partner onboarding cycles. Continue monitoring landing page behavior consistency across diverse device and browser combinations during subsequent Subaru and broader OEM validation activities. Reuse troubleshooting findings and RCA documentation as a reference baseline for future client-side redirect issue triage.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This inv