48	1	3	2026-02-04-00048	CTAP-45589	2026-02-04	\N	REDIRECTION / UPF	UPF / IPPE / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Captive portal and landing page redirection disruption impacting IoT OEM validation flows across UPF/IPPE data-plane execution domain. During E2E validation of captive portal flows, SNAP interactions, and UPF/IPPE traffic handling, users were intermittently redirected to incorrect URLs, unable to reach the expected landing page, or experiencing inconsistent redirection behavior. Expected behavior was deterministic, consistent redirection to the correct captive portal landing page upon session initiation, with proper PFD propagation and traffic classification across all involved components. The investigation scope spanned PCF policy behavior, UPF/IPPE execution logic, PFD propagation integrity, and traffic classification consistency to determine the originating domain of the failure. The affected E2E path encompassed PCF ΓåÆ PFD propagation ΓåÆ UPF/IPPE traffic classification ΓåÆ captive portal redirection ΓåÆ landing page delivery, with downstream impact on OEM onboarding validation activities.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed. Initial analysis confirmed that control-plane signaling was operating correctly while data-plane execution exhibited inconsistent behavior, narrowing the investigation to UPF/IPPE and PFD handling domains. Structured domain isolation methodology was applied, systematically separating signaling behavior, policy logic, and traffic execution layers to accelerate root cause identification. The UDR Ericsson team ultimately confirmed that the observed error did not impact registration or PDU session creation, and that both flows were restored to normal operation. The precise initial trigger was not fully confirmed by the vendor, but the issue was classified as transient given that corrective actions restored stability and no recurrence was observed. Landing page redirection behavior was stabilized, and all E2E validation activities resum