imelines by rapidly isolating a data-plane execution disruption and preventing cascading delays across dependent certification activities. The structured domain isolation approach strengthened platform troubleshooting maturity and established reusable methodology for future captive portal investigations, contributing to overall platform resiliency and release certification readiness.	The redirection inconsistency was isolated to the data-plane execution domain (UPF/IPPE), with control-plane signaling confirmed as operating correctly. This critical separation eliminated PCF policy behavior and charging domains from the investigation scope. The UDR Ericsson team confirmed that the observed error did not impact registration or PDU session creation, and operations were restored to normal ΓÇö however, the precise initial trigger was never definitively confirmed by the vendor, classifying this as a transient issue. The most probable hypothesis centers on a temporary PFD synchronization or traffic classification inconsistency within the UPF/IPPE layer that self-resolved or was corrected through operational intervention. The key architectural takeaway is that redirection reliability in captive portal flows is critically dependent on consistent PFD propagation and traffic classification alignment across UPF/IPPE components, and future monitoring should target this specific interaction path.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	transient	{UPF,PCF,UDM,IPPE}		t	2026-05-27 18:43:12.129015+00	2026-05-27 19:04:31.338524+00	f	\N
46	1	3	02/02/2026-00046	CTAP-44776	2026-02-02	\N	AUTHENTICATION / ENTERPRISE	Enterprise PODs / AT&T 5G SA / Northrim / NR RAN	Closed	A platform capability limitation was identified where CHAP (Challenge-Handshake Authentication Protocol) authentication is not supported within the current Enterprise POD architecture operating on AT&T 5G SA with NR RAN. The observed behavior is that enterprise customer devices configured with CHAP-based authentication mechanisms on specific DNNs within Enterprise SMF/UPF environments fail to authenticate successfully through the expected E2E path. The expected behavior is full CHAP authentication support for Enterprise IoT use cases requiring this mechanism during onboarding and session establishment flows. The technical context spans the Enterprise SMF Γåö UPF Γåö DNN authentication chain, where the current POD implementation model does not accommodate CHAP requirements. This limitation surfaced during onboarding and E2E validation activities for Enterprise IoT customers, revealing a structural gap rather than an isolated configuration defect. The affected flow encompasses the entire Enterprise IoT onboarding and session authentication pipeline across 5G SA NR RAN environments.	Investigation concluded and ticket closed as of 04/21/2026. Root cause was successfully isolated to a platform architecture limitation inherent to the current Enterprise POD implementation model ΓÇö not a device-level, provisioning, or individual NF configuration defect. During the investigation phase, only specific Enterprise SMF/UPF DNN scenarios were observed where customer devices attempted CHAP authentication, confirming that the gap is structural. Platform architecture evolution toward Aqua-based Enterprise PODs was identified as the remediation path, with all Enterprise PODs expected to be launched as or converted to Aqua environments to natively support CHAP authentication. The issue was ruled out as an SMF logic error, PCF policy misconfiguration, provisioning gap, or charging domain problem ΓÇö narrowing the scope exclusively to the Enterprise POD architecture model. Remediation strategy aligned with the broader Aqua migration roadmap.	Enterprise Onboarding Limitation ΓÇö CHAP authentication gap blocks specific Enterprise IoT customer onboarding and E2E validation on AT&T 5G SA with NR RAN. Customers requiring CHAP-based authentication mechanisms cannot be fully validated or launched on current Enterprise POD architecture. This creates a dependency on future platform evolution (Aqua-based Enterprise PODs) and introduces delays in certifying Enterprise IoT use cases that mandate CHAP support. The impact extends beyond individual customer scenarios to the broader Enterprise onboarding pipeline and platform readiness posture.	Isolated root cause to a platform architecture limitation rather than an individual NF or provisioning defect, preventing unnecessary and costly troubleshooting escalations across SMF, PCF, provisioning, and charging domains. Accelerated problem classification by clearly distinguishing between a structural capability gap and an operational configuration issue. Enabled strategic alignment discussions around the Aqua Enterprise POD migration strategy, directly informing the future onboarding roadmap for customers requiring CHAP authentication. Defined the remediation dependency path, ensuring stakeholder clarity on timeline and platform evolution requirements. Prevented misclassification of the issue as a transient or isolated defect, preserving engineering resource allocation for genuine operational incidents.	{"Continue alignment activities toward Aqua-based Enterprise POD deployment and migration strategy","Monitor Enterprise POD evolution roadmap for milestones enabling native CHAP authentication support","Re-evaluate CHAP authentication capability once Aqua migration activities are completed for target Enterprise PODs","Support future Enterprise IoT customer onboarding validations requirin