chestration led directly by C├⌐sar Villagra across SMF, CHF, and validation teams.	Charging platform integrity ΓÇö This initiative directly protected IoT validation and certification readiness by rapidly isolating and remediating a charging flow disruption caused by cross-domain interaction between SMF load testing and CHF transaction processing. The resolution reinforced cross-domain stabilization practices and established a reusable troubleshooting framework for future charging platform incidents. The findings highlight the need for operational guardrails around load testing activities that share charging infrastructure, contributing to overall platform resiliency posture.	The root cause was an SMF-originated transaction overload condition: concurrent load testing activities on SMF pods generated excessive charging transactions that included retries for stale/obsolete sessions. These retry storms propagated into CHF, overwhelming its processing capacity and causing intermittent charging inconsistencies and downstream visibility degradation. The CHF application logic itself was functioning correctly ΓÇö the failure was induced by upstream volume anomalies. The critical differentiator in RCA was isolating that CHF processing and downstream reporting were victims, not originators, of the failure. Remediation required bouncing the affected SMF charging pods to flush the retry queue for expired sessions. Post-bounce retesting confirmed complete restoration. This pattern ΓÇö load-test-induced retry storms creating cross-NF charging disruption ΓÇö represents a recurring risk in shared lab environments and warrants SMF-side rate limiting or session expiry enforcement during load testing windows.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{SMF,CHF,ACC}		t	2026-05-27 18:41:19.861556+00	2026-05-27 19:04:40.44327+00	f	\N
