inding, and IoT service continuity. Successful validation reduced risk for future IoT production onboarding scenarios and improved confidence in fallback behavior continuity across coexisting interface models.	Validated architectural alignment between Rx and N5 EPS Fallback implementations, eliminating ambiguity in lab-to-production behavioral expectations. Isolated root cause to a PLMN configuration removal (311180) by the CHF offshore team during a deployment on Azure-CHF_E2E01, preventing misclassification as a platform defect. Prevented future rework and potential production incidents by confirming architectural assumptions early in the IoT integration lifecycle. Enabled more accurate troubleshooting baselines and established a reusable validation reference for upcoming IoT onboarding scenarios.	Preserve validated findings as the architectural baseline for future EPS Fallback validations across IoT integration scenarios. Reuse confirmed Rx vs N5 behavioral alignment as a reference for upcoming IoT production onboarding activities. Continue alignment efforts between lab and production charging and policy models to ensure ongoing parity. Enforce change management controls around PLMN configuration changes on CHF instances to prevent recurrence of unintended removals during deployments.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement and architecture impact ΓÇö This initiative directly de-risked IoT production onboarding by validating that EPS Fallback behavior is architecturally consistent between Rx and N5 implementations. The root cause finding (PLMN removal during CHF deployment) further highlights the need for cross-domain change management governance to protect charging platform integrity during integration cycles.	The root cause was traced to the CHF offshore team inadvertently removing the 311180 PLMN configuration from the Azure-CHF_E2E01 instance (107.121.213.16) during a deployment. This configuration removal disrupted the expected EPS Fallback signaling chain. Once restored, validation confirmed that both Rx-based and N5-based EPS Fallback implementations produced architecturally aligned behavior across the SMF ΓåÆ PCF ΓåÆ CHF path. The failure was at the configuration layer ΓÇö not application logic or infrastructure ΓÇö and the fallback mechanism itself was operating as designed. This finding establishes that PLMN configuration integrity on CHF instances is a critical dependency for EPS Fallback correctness in IoT environments.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{CHF,PCF,SMF}		t	2026-05-27 19:07:27.316184+00	2026-05-27 20:42:31.582784+00	f	\N
