ot be closed, impacting release certification readiness for redirect policy flows. Although core charging and SLC domains are confirmed functional, the unresolved downstream redirect behavior blocks full end-to-end validation closure for the redirect policy use case.	Eliminated Spending Limit Control and CHF authorization as suspected root causes by leveraging redirect policy delivery evidence as a definitive diagnostic signal, significantly narrowing the investigation scope from four potential failure domains to one. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward the charging domain by validating that CHF ΓåÆ PCF SLC interaction was functioning correctly, avoiding false attribution to core charging logic. Accelerated cross-domain troubleshooting by redirecting investigation focus to downstream redirect handling components, enabling Tier 1 to concentrate efforts on the actual failure domain rather than re-investigating already validated upstream flows.	{"Continue downstream redirect chain investigation beyond PCF policy delivery point ΓÇö Tier 1 to lead analysis of redirect handling components","Validate redirect enforcement behavior after PCF successfully delivers redirect policies and URLs to downstream consumers","Analyze remaining redirect flow dependencies including any intermediate proxies, redirect servers, or enforcement points in the redirect chain","Confirm final redirect behavior after policy enforcement and capture evidence of success or failure at the downstream enforcement layer","Document validated upstream components (CHF, SLC, PCF policy generation) as confirmed working to prevent regression in future investigations","Close JIRA after full end-to-end redirect validation is completed and downstream root cause is identified and resolved"}	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	This initiative directly supports redirect policy validation readiness and release certification for the PCF redirect policy use case. It demonstrates systematic RCA narrowing methodology that prevents false escalation toward CHF/SLC domains, preserving charging platform integrity by avoiding unnecessary rework in confirmed-functional components. The investigation contributes to cross-domain stabilization by clearly delineating domain boundaries between charging authorization (CHF), policy generation (PCF/SLC), and downstream redirect enforcement ΓÇö improving organizational troubleshooting governance and accelerating future investigations in overlapping policy and charging domains.	Critical diagnostic signal validated: the successful delivery of redirect policies and redirect URLs by the PCF constitutes definitive proof that Spending Limit Control (SLC) processing completed successfully and CHF ΓåÆ PCF charging authorization functioned correctly. This is because SLC failure would have prevented the PCF from generating redirect policies entirely. Validated layers: CHF authorization (application ΓÇö confirmed working), PCF SLC processing (application ΓÇö confirmed working), redirect policy generation (application ΓÇö confirmed working), redirect URL delivery (application ΓÇö confirmed working). The failure domain has been conclusively isolated to downstream redirect handling ΓÇö the layer beyond PCF policy delivery where redirect enforcement or redirect chain processing occurs. The root cause hypothesis at this stage points to a downstream redirect processing component (potentially redirect server, enforcement proxy, or redirect chain intermediary) failing to act on correctly delivered redirect policies. This is an application or configuration issue in the downstream redirect domain, not a charging or SLC defect.	Tier 1	t	application	{CHF,PCF}		f	2026-05-27 21:00:36.235226+00	2026-05-27 21:00:36.235226+00	f	
84	1	3	02/04/2026-00085	CTAP-45933	2026-02-04	\N	ACC / Visibility	ACC / Control Center / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	Charging visibility disruption identified across the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center reporting chain during IoT validation activities. Session visibility and charging reporting inconsistencies were observed, where charging signaling appeared partially successful at the CHF layer, but corresponding records were either incomplete or absent in ACC and Control Center downstream platforms. The expected behavior was full end-to-end visibility of session information, charging records, and usage reporting across all downstream systems following successful SMF-initiated sessions. The investigation spanned multiple domains ΓÇö charging generation at the CHF level, ACC ingestion behavior, and Control Center reporting synchronization ΓÇö to isolate whether the root cause was upstream (charging record generation), midstream (CHF processing and delivery), or downstream (ACC ingestion and reporting rendering). The affected end-to-end flow encompassed the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center visibility pipeline, with downstream impact on IoT validation confidence and session-level reporting integrity.	Investigation concluded and issue fully resolved. Initial analysis revealed that charging signaling was partially successful but downstream visibility in ACC and Control Center was incomplete or inconsistent, triggering a structured multi-domain troubleshooting effort across SMF, CHF, ACC, and testing teams. Through systematic domain isolation, the investigation progressively ruled out ACC ingestion failures, CHF processing defects, and reporting synchronization issues. The root cause was ultimately identified by Microsoft as being linked to a known UPF IPPE issue requiring a reboot due to PFD (Packet Flow Description) vector refresh inconsistency present in Lab 8's software version 5.1.0.15 ΓÇö a defect resolved in version 5.1.0.18. Following the UPF IPPE reboot, Kiranmai successfully retested and confirmed that the landing page was displayed correctly, session visibility was restored in Control Center, and charging reporting stabilized across all downstream platforms. No additional visibility inconsistencies were observed after retesting.	Visibility Loss ΓÇö Missing session and charging visibility in Control Center disrupted end-to-end IoT validation activities. Incomplete reporting reduced confidence in the charging and session visibility pipeline, blocking validation sign-off and introducing delays in IoT certification workflows. The issue temporarily undermined observability integrity across the SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center chain, affecting stakeholder confidence in platform readiness for IoT use-case enablement.	Successfully isolated the root cause through structured multi-domain investigation, systematically narrowing the scope from ACC ingestion, CHF processing, and reporting synchronization layers down to the UPF IPPE PFD vector refresh inconsistency ΓÇö a known software defect resolved in a newer release. This structured domain isolation approach prevented unnecessary escalation toward unrelated network functions (CHF, ACC, SMF) and accelerated root cause identification by enabling Microsoft to correlate the behavior to a known UPF defect. The investigation methodology preserved cross-domain troubleshooting findings for reuse in future visibility-related incidents, improving organizational troubleshooting maturity across the charging and observability pipeline.	{"Monitor ACC ingestion stability and Control Center reporting behavior post-resolution to confirm sustained visibility integrity","Track Lab 8 UPF software upgrade path to version 5.1.0.18 or later to permanently eliminate PFD vector refresh inconsistency","Preserve and document the structured troubleshooting methodology (domain isolation across charging generation, downstream ingestion, and ACC visibility layers) for reuse in future visibility-related investigations","Validate that IoT end-to-end certification activities can proceed without residual visibility gaps following the UPF IPPE reboot","Coordinate with Microsoft to confirm whether additional lab environments running 5.1.0.15 are susceptible to the same PFD vector refresh behavior"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Investigation ownership, cross-domain coordination between SMF/CHF/ACC/Microsoft teams, and structured RCA isolation led by C├⌐sar Villagra through the full lifecycle of the incident.	Observability readiness and Charging platform integrity ΓÇö This initiative validated the resilience and diagnostic maturity of the end-to-end charging visibility pipeline (SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC ΓåÆ Control Center) within the IoT lab environment. The root cause attribution to a known UPF software defect (PFD vector refresh inconsistency in 5.1.0.15, resolved in 5.1.0.18) reinforces the importance of software version alignment across lab environments and highlights a dependency between UPF software maturity and downstream charging/observability platform integrity. The structured domain isolation methodology established during this investigation strengthens cross-domain troubleshooting readiness for future visibility incidents and supports IoT validation confidence for OEM onboarding and release certification activities.	The charging visibility disruption was not caused by any defect in the ACC, CHF, or Control Center platforms. The root cause was traced to the UPF layer ΓÇö specifically, a PFD (Packet Flow Description) vector refresh inconsistency inherent to UPF software version 5.1.0.15 running in Lab 8. This inconsistency caused the UPF IPPE component to require a reboot to properly refresh PFD vectors, which in turn disrupted upstream session establishment and downstream charging record generation, propagating as incomplete or absent visibility in ACC and Control Center. The defect is a known issue resolved in UPF version 5.1.0.18. Af