89	1	3	2026-03-19-00090	CTAP-59219	2026-03-19	\N	REGISTRATION / ATTACH	Darkstar Lab 4 / Tesla Hedy DNN	Closed	A registration and attach failure was identified in Darkstar Lab 4 using the Tesla Hedy DNN, where devices were unable to successfully complete the attach procedure into the targeted environment. The expected behavior was a seamless attach and registration flow enabling IoT E2E validation and Darkstar Line Up continuity. The observed behavior revealed that a 4G idle device performing TAU toward 5G was being routed through N26 procedures, during which MME6 was selecting an incorrect AMF (RDM52d AMF associated with Northrim Lab 1) instead of the expected Darkstar Line Up 4 AMF (RD2WA65 AMF). This incorrect AMF selection, combined with TAC-related configuration inconsistencies, resulted in attach failures that blocked IoT E2E validation activities. The affected flow spans the 4G ΓåÆ N26 ΓåÆ 5G mobility and registration path, involving AMF selection logic, MME behavior, TAC configuration, and inter-lab mobility dependencies within the Darkstar integration pipeline.	Issue fully resolved and closed as of 03/23/2026. Root cause analysis confirmed that the attach failure originated from two converging factors: (1) incorrect AMF selection by MME6 through the N26 interface, routing the device to Northrim Lab 1 (RDM52d AMF) instead of the intended Darkstar Line Up 4 AMF (RD2WA65 AMF), and (2) TAC-related configuration contributing to the attach inconsistency. The AMF team identified that the TAC range being used for the 4G idle to 5G attach was incorrect, and upon adjusting the TAC range as recommended and also shifting to a 5G direct attach approach, the tester was able to attach successfully. Re-testing confirmed no additional attach inconsistencies. Darkstar Lab 4 validation activities have resumed normally with the corrected configuration baseline in place.	Critical Testing Blocker ΓÇö Attach validation was completely blocked in Darkstar Lab 4, interrupting IoT E2E validation activities and delaying Darkstar integration readiness. Incorrect AMF selection behavior through the N26 mobility path caused testing continuity disruption across the 4G-to-5G registration flow, impacting lab certification timelines and inter-lab mobility validation confidence.	Isolated root cause across multiple intersecting domains ΓÇö mobility handling, N26 interface behavior, AMF selection logic, and TAC configuration ΓÇö through structured domain isolation methodology. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, or policy domains by rapidly narrowing the investigation scope to the mobility and infrastructure configuration layer. Improved organizational understanding of inter-lab mobility dependencies and N26-driven AMF selection behavior. Accelerated troubleshooting by coordinating directly with the AMF team and validating their TAC range recommendation, restoring Darkstar validation continuity within four days of issue identification.	Preserve the validated TAC configuration baseline for Darkstar Lab 4 as a reference for future attach and registration validations. Continue monitoring AMF selection behavior during subsequent 4G-to-5G mobility and N26-driven procedures to ensure no regression. Incorporate troubleshooting findings and TAC range guidance from the AMF team into the knowledge base for future mobility and N26 investigations. Validate that 5G direct attach approach remains stable as an alternate path for Darkstar Line Up testing scenarios.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	This initiative directly supports cross-domain stabilization and release certification readiness for the Darkstar Lab 4 environment. The resolution of TAC and AMF selection behavior across the N26 mobility path strengthens inter-lab mobility confidence and ensures IoT E2E validation pipelines remain unblocked. The structured isolation methodology applied here establishes a reusable troubleshooting framework for future mobility-related attach failures, reducing mean time to resolution for similar scenarios and protecting Darkstar integration timelines.	The attach failure was caused by a dual-factor configuration issue at the mobility and infrastructure layer. MME6, when processing a 4G idle device performing TAU toward 5G via the N26 interface, was selecting the wrong AMF ΓÇö routing to RDM52d AMF (Northrim Lab 1) instead of RD2WA65 AMF (Darkstar Line Up 4). The AMF team confirmed that the TAC range used during testing was outside the expected scope for the target environment, which directly influenced the incorrect AMF selection. Upon adjusting the TAC range per AMF team guidance and additionally validating via a 5G direct attach approach (bypassing N26 altogether), the attach succeeded consistently. This was a genuine configuration defect ΓÇö not working as designed ΓÇö where TAC misconfiguration cascaded into incorrect inter-lab AMF routing through the N26 mobility path. The root cause was fully isolated to the TAC/mobility configuration domain with no involvement from charging, policy, or provisioning layers.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{Infrastructure,AMF}		t	2026-05-27 19:12:40.114159+00	2026-05-27 20:42:08.07842+00	f	\N
88	1	3	2026-03-18-00089	CTAP-59151	2026-03-18	\N	CHARGING / ACC	Azure / Lab 8 / Enterprise DNN (d50012.etr)	Closed	A charging visibility disruption was identified within the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain for the Enterprise DNN d50012.etr (Honda Enterprise DNN) in the Azure Lab 8 environment. Observed behavior indicated that while the SMF was successfully generating charging traffic and the CHF was responding operationally, no session information, usage history, or charging visibility was being reflected downstream in ACC / Control Center. Expected behavior required the full E2E charging interaction ΓÇö SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC ΓÇö to produce proper session visibility and usage records in Control Center. The affected flow spans the enterprise charging path involving SMF origination, CHF processing, Kafka-based CDR transport, and ACC ingestion for downstream visibility. The disruption impacted enterprise IoT E2E validation activities dependent on accurate charging record propagation.	Investigation concluded and the issue has been resolved. Structured domain isolation confirmed that the SMF was generating charging traffic correctly and the CHF was processing and responding as expected, with CDRs present in the output topic. Root cause was identified during parallel investigation of CTAP-60539, where the CHF team discovered a Kafka issue that was preventing CDR propagation to ACC. The Kafka issue was corrected, and the test team subsequently confirmed that charging traffic and session visibility were successfully appearing in Control Center. All upstream domains ΓÇö SMF, policy, and provisioning ΓÇö were validated as operational and ruled out during the troubleshooting process. The issue is now classified as resolved with full enterprise charging visibility restored.	Charging Impact | Visibility Loss | E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö Missing session visibility in ACC / Control Center resulted in incomplete enterprise charging validation for the Honda Enterprise DNN