fka transport-layer root cause discovery reinforces the criticality of cross-domain observability in the charging platform and informs infrastructure stabilization priorities for Kafka-dependent CDR delivery pipelines.	The root cause was a Kafka transport-layer issue that prevented CDR propagation from CHF to ACC, despite both the SMF and CHF operating correctly at the application level. The CHF was generating CDRs and placing them on the output topic, but a Kafka malfunction ΓÇö discovered during parallel investigation of CTAP-60539 ΓÇö was blocking downstream ingestion by ACC. This is a critical distinction: the failure was not in charging generation (SMF), charging processing (CHF), or ACC application logic, but in the Kafka messaging layer that bridges CHF output to ACC input. Once the Kafka issue was resolved, the test team confirmed full session visibility and usage history in Control Center. This pattern highlights that charging visibility disruptions in the ACC domain should trigger Kafka transport validation as an early troubleshooting step before escalating to application-layer teams.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	observability	{CHF,SMF,ACC,Kafka}		t	2026-05-27 19:12:13.828147+00	2026-05-27 20:42:10.186299+00	f	\N
140	1	3	04/07/2026-00143	CTAP-66464	2026-04-07	\N	Charging / Working as Designed	Darkstar Labs ΓÇö Ericsson SMF/UPF, CHF, ACC, Charging Flows	Closed	Validation and root cause analysis of SID 60 CDR generation behavior within Ericsson SMF charging environments. The investigation was initiated after the absence of SID 60 CDRs was observed under specific testing scenarios, raising concerns about a potential charging defect. The objective was to determine whether the missing CDR generation represented an application or charging logic defect, or whether the behavior was consistent with the expected conditional CDR generation design. The analysis encompassed TCP handshake behavior between the UE and Ericsson SMF, charging trigger conditions, conditional CDR generation logic, and the upstream interaction between eSMFe1-rdmwa65 and cUDM-rdmwa75. The affected flow spans the E2E path: UE ΓåÆ Ericsson SMF ΓåÆ UDM/UDR ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC charging reporting chain. During investigation, an additional upstream issue was identified involving DNN resolution between SMF and UDM/UDR, which contributed to the observed behavior.	Investigation closed with full root cause confirmed. The SID 60 CDR generation behavior was validated as working as designed: SID 60 CDRs are generated exclusively when the TCP handshake with the Ericsson SMF fails; when the handshake completes successfully, no SID 60 CDRs are produced, which is the expected conditional charging logic. Additionally, root cause analysis uncovered that the eSMFe1-rdmwa65 queried cUDM-rdmwa75 for dnn=attdemo5g01, but the UDM responded with a 404 Not Found error. Further investigation by Bic confirmed that the UDR had the DNN provisioned with uppercase characters, creating a case-sensitivity mismatch that caused the lookup failure. Both the charging behavior clarification and the UDR configuration root cause were fully resolved. No application defect, charging defect, or policy issue was identified. Ticket closed on 05/12/2026.	Charging Behavior Clarification | False Positive Defect Eliminated | Configuration-Driven UDR Lookup Failure. The investigation clarified expected conditional CDR generation behavior and prevented unnecessary escalation toward Ericsson SMF, CHF, and charging application domains. The identification of the UDR case-sensitivity mismatch resolved a configuration-driven lookup failure that impacted the SMF ΓåÆ UDM ΓåÆ UDR query path for DNN resolution.	Validated working-as-designed behavior, avoiding misclassification of expected conditional CDR generation as a platform defect. Isolated root cause of UDR 404 Not Found response to a case-sensitivity mismatch in DNN provisioning, preventing unnecessary escalation toward Ericsson SMF, CHF, or charging application teams. Accelerated troubleshooting by narrowing investigation scope across charging trigger logic, TCP handshake dependency, and UDR data provisioning layers. Strengthened operational knowledge of conditional SID 60 generation logic and Ericsson SMF charging flow behavior, contributing to charging domain operational maturity and improved troubleshooting efficiency for future validations.	No additional actions required. Charging behavior confirmed as working as designed. UDR DNN case-sensitivity root cause identified and resolved. Ticket closed. Recommend documenting the DNN case-sensitivity requirement as a provisioning best practice to prevent recurrence in future UDR configurations across lab and production environments.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Charging Platform Integrity | Cross-Domain Stabilization | Operational Maturity Enablement. This initiative clarifies expected charging platform behavior and eliminates false-positive defect classifications. The root cause identification of UDR case-sensitivity mismatch strengthens provisioning governance and prevents recurrence across environments. Improves troubleshooting efficiency, reduces unnecessary escalation burden, and contributes to Ericsson SMF charging flow understanding ΓÇö directly supporting charging domain operational maturity and release certification readiness.	SID 60 CDR generation is conditionally triggered only upon TCP handshake failure with Ericsson SMF ΓÇö successful handshakes produce no SID 60 CDRs by design. The upstream root cause was identified in the SMF ΓåÆ UDM ΓåÆ UDR query path: eSMFe1-rdmwa65 queried cUDM-rdmwa75 for dnn=attdemo5g01, but UDR returned 404 Not Found because the DNN was provisioned with uppercase characters, creating a case-sensitivity mismatch. The issue was a configuration-layer defect in UDR data provisioning, not an application or charging logic defect. Classification: working as designed for SID 60 CDR behavior; configuration defect for UDR DNN case mismatch. Impacted domains: Ericsson SMF conditional CDR generation logic and UDM/UDR DNN provisioning layer.	Tier 1	t	working_as_designed	{CHF,SMF,UPF,UDM,ACC}		f	2026-05-27 21:01:23.647716+00	2026-05-27 21:01:23.647716+00	f	Root cause confirmed: eSMFe1-rdmwa65 queried cUDM-rdmwa75 for dnn=attdemo5g01, but UDM returned 404 Not Found because the DNN was provisioned in UDR with uppercase characters, causing a case-sensitivity mismatch in the lookup. SID 60 CDR generation behavior separately confirmed as working as designed ΓÇö CDRs are only generated upon TCP handshake failure with Ericsson SMF.
94	1	3	2026-03-23-00095	CTAP-60539	2026-03-23	\N	CHARGING / AZURE / CHF	Azure CHF / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	A critical charging flow disruption was identified in the Azure CHF environment where CreateConvergedCharging requests were systematically failing across multiple enterprise DNNs. Observed behavior: SMF-initiated charging transactions were being rejected or erroneously processed by the Azure CHF instance (Azure-CHF_E2E01 ΓÇö 107.121.213.16), resulting in complete session visibility loss in ACC / Control Center and downstream charging validation failures. Expected behavior: CreateConvergedCharging requests initiated by the SMF should be successfully processed by the Azure CHF, with session records properly generated and propagated through the Kafka pipeline to ACC / Control Center for full charging visibility. Technical context: The failure chain spanned the SMF ΓåÆ Azure CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC reporting path, impacting the end-to-end IoT charging validation flow across multiple DNNs. The root cause was ultimately traced to a Kafka schema misconfiguration on the CHF side, which disrupted the downstream data pipeline and prevented session information from being correctly published and consumed. Affected flow: SMF ΓåÆ Azure CHF (CreateConvergedCharging) ΓåÆ Kafka (schema-dependent event publishing) ΓåÆ ACC / Control Center (charging session visibility and reporting).	Issue has been resolved and the ticket is closed as of 03/27/2026. Root cause was identified and remediated by Arun Balgi from the CHF Team, who diagnosed and corrected a Kafka schema misconfiguration on the Azure CHF side. The Kafka schema issue was causing charging transaction data to be improperly serialized or rejected at the event publishing layer, which broke the downstream propagation chain to ACC / Control Center. Prior to RCA confirmation, the investigation systematically ruled out provisioning errors, transport/connectivity failures, and UE-side issues, narrowing the scope exclusively to 