date ACC / Control Center session visibility completeness for all previously impacted IoT charging scenarios. (3) Execute regression testing of CreateConvergedCharging flows across the full multi-DNN matrix to confirm no residual failures. (4) Coordinate with CHF team to document Kafka schema configuration baseline and establish preventive validation checks for future Azure CHF deployments. (5) Update IoT E2E charging validation test results to reflect restored platform behavior.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö Investigation coordination, domain isolation, and escalation to CHF team were driven by C├⌐sar Villagra. CHF team (Arun Balgi) executed the technical remediation under TPM-coordinated troubleshooting framework.	Charging platform integrity | Cross-domain stabilization | Observability readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly impacts the confidence level in Azure CHF as a viable charging platform for IoT E2E validation. The Kafka schema root cause highlights a critical dependency between CHF processing and downstream observability infrastructure. Resolution validates that the Azure CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC pipeline can be stabilized and relied upon for continued IoT certification activities. The pattern of Azure-specific charging instability, if recurrent, carries strategic implications for platform architecture decisions and environment parity between Azure and non-Azure CHF deployments.	Root cause was a Kafka schema misconfiguration on the Azure CHF side, identified and remediated by Arun Balgi (CHF Team). The schema issue caused the CHF to improperly publish charging event data to the Kafka pipeline, which broke the downstream propagation chain to ACC / Control Center. Critically, CreateConvergedCharging requests were successfully reaching the CHF ΓÇö the failure was not at the SMF ΓåÆ CHF interaction layer but at the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka event publishing layer. This means the application-level charging logic was functional, but the observability/event pipeline configuration was broken. The multi-DNN blast radius was a direct consequence of the schema being a shared configuration element across all DNN-specific charging flows processed by the Azure CHF instance. The defect layer is classified as configuration (Kafka schema) with observability impact (ACC visibility loss). This is a genuine defect ΓÇö not working as designed, not transient ΓÇö and was definitively resolved through schema correction.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	configuration	{CHF,SMF,Kafka,ACC}		t	2026-05-27 19:15:11.070562+00	2026-05-27 20:41:56.692125+00	f	\N
92	1	3	2026-03-20-00093	CTAP-59419	2026-03-20	\N	Redirection / Client Behavior	Real UE / Subaru Validation Environment	Closed	A captive portal redirection failure was identified during Subaru landing page validation, where notification-triggered redirection scenarios resulted in an error_timeout condition. Observed behavior: the landing page failed consistently when triggered through the notification/redirection flow on a specific device, despite manual browsing to the landing page URL succeeding without issue. Expected behavior: notification-triggered redirection should seamlessly render the Subaru landing page as part of the captive portal onboarding flow. Technical context: the issue surfaced within the notification ΓåÆ redirection ΓåÆ captive portal landing page chain, implicating the intersection of network-triggered redirect behavior and client-side browser/device handling. Comparative testing with an alternate SUPI on a different device completed the flow successfully, confirming the network path and core NF behavior were operational. Affected flow: end-to-end Subaru OEM onboarding validation, encompassing notification delivery, redirect handling, and captive portal rendering.	Investigation closed with root cause confirmed. Initial troubleshooting engaged Microsoft teams, validation/testing groups, and client-side behavioral analysis. Comparative testing across devices and SUPIs demonstrated that the network flowΓÇöincluding notification delivery and redirectionΓÇöwas fully operational, as alternate devices successfully rendered the landing page. This pivoted the investigation away from core network functions (UPF, PCF, policy, charging) and toward device-level behavior, browser handling, and client-side timeout conditions. David from Microsoft confirmed the issue was likely browser/client related. Final RCA was conclusively determined: the failure was caused by a device release issue on the specific handset used during initial testing. Replacing the device resolved the error_timeout condition entirely, validating that no network-side or platform-side corrective action was required.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Inconsistent landing page validation behavior introduced delays in Subaru onboarding validation activities and reduced confidence in the consistency of notification-triggered redirect flows. The failure risked misclassification as a network or policy defect, which would have triggered unnecessary escalation across UPF, PCF, and charging domains. Potential client-side compatibility concerns were surfaced that have broader implications for multi-device OEM onboarding certification.	Successfully differentiated network-side operational behavior from device/client-side failure, preventing unnecessary escalation toward UPF, PCF, policy, or charging domains. Accelerated root cause identification through structured comparative testing across devices and SUPIs, narrowing investigation scope from a broad E2E platform concern to an isolated device release issue. Established a reusable troubleshooting methodology for future client-side redirect validation scenarios, directly improving the efficiency of OEM onboarding certification workflows. Validated working-as-designed behavior across the notification ΓåÆ redirection ΓåÆ captive portal chain, preserving platform integrity confidence.	{"Preserve comparative validation methodology (multi-device, multi-SUPI testing) as a standard troubleshooting protocol for future OEM onboarding redirect investigations.","Continue monitoring landing page behavior consistency across diverse device and browser combinations during subsequent Subaru and other OEM validation cycles.","Reuse troubleshooting findings and RCA pattern to accelerate future client-side redirect issue identification.","Document device release compatibility requirements for captive portal redirection flows to proactively mitigate similar issues during future OEM onboarding campaigns."}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö TPM led cross-domain coordination between Microsoft teams, validation groups, and client-side analysis, driving RCA to closure without Tier 1 escalation.	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This initiative validated that the core notification-triggered redirection and captive portal infrastructure is fully operational for Subaru onboarding flows. By isolating the failure to a device-level release issue, the investigation preserved confidence in platform readiness and established a reusable diagnostic framework for client-side compatibility challenges across future OEM partner validations. The methodology directly supports cross-domain stabilization and release certification readiness for multi-OEM captive portal onboarding.	The error_timeout failure on the Subaru landing page was conclusively isolated to a device release issue on the specific handset used during testing, not to any network function or platform component. The notification ΓåÆ redirection ΓåÆ captive portal chain operated correctly end-to-end, as validated by successful completion of the same flow on an alternate device with a different SUPI. The client-side browser on the affected device was unable to properly handle the redirect-triggered page load within the timeout window, while direct URL access bypassed the redirect mechanism and succeeded. This confirms that UPF, PCF, policy enforcement, and charging paths were all working as designed. The root cause resided entirely in the client/device domain ΓÇö specifically the device's software release affecting browser redirect handling behavior. No network-side or platform-side corrective actions were required.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	working_as_designed	{UPF,PCF}		t	2026-05-27 19:14:03.323053+00	2026-05-27 20:42:00.691195+00	f	\N
