ty validation and release certification readiness by confirming that the RGID/SID tagging and ACC reporting pipeline operates correctly under nominal conditions. Reinforces observability readiness across the charging domain by validating that transient anomalies are properly triaged and classified rather than escalated as persistent defects.	During initial testing, charging usage associated with RGID 4103 / SID 831 was not reflected in ACC despite traffic generation from SMF auk65a with DSSTI and DAI values observed as APPCON Default. Upon structured retesting of the identical RGID/SID combination, SMF auk65a successfully transmitted usage to CHF and the data was correctly reflected in ACC ΓÇö confirming the full SMF ΓåÆ CHF ΓåÆ ACC reporting chain was operational. The issue was classified as transient and non-reproducible, with no evidence of a persistent defect at the charging processing layer, traffic tagging layer, or ACC observability layer. All impacted domains ΓÇö SMF, CHF, and ACC ΓÇö were validated as functioning correctly. This outcome underscores the importance of systematic retest cycles before triggering cross-domain escalation, as transient charging visibility anomalies can mimic persistent platform defects if not properly triaged.	Tier 1	t	transient	{SMF,CHF,PCF,ACC}		f	2026-05-27 21:01:49.104803+00	2026-05-27 21:01:49.104803+00	f	Initial test showed charging usage for RGID 4103 / SID 831 not reflected in ACC. Structured retest confirmed SMF auk65a successfully sent usage to CHF and data was correctly reflected in ACC. Root cause classified as transient and non-reproducible ΓÇö no persistent defect identified across the SMF, CHF, or ACC domains.
99	1	3	2026-01-16-00100	CTAP-40426	2026-01-16	\N	VALIDATION / UPF / IPPE / PFD	Lab 3 Consumer POD / UC 5.1.0.18	Closed	Comprehensive validation initiative launched to verify PFD (Packet Flow Description) behavior, APPID rule propagation, and IPPE synchronization consistency within the Lab 3 Consumer POD running UC 5.1.0.18. The observed concern stemmed from previously identified IPPE/PFD inconsistencies ΓÇö including landing-page failures, traffic classification anomalies, and redirect execution instability ΓÇö which required definitive behavioral verification under the updated UC version. The expected behavior is that APPID PFD rule changes propagate correctly to IPPE upon DNN attachment, new PFD rules associated with APP IDs are reflected accurately, and BIG PFD scenarios execute with correct traffic tagging. The affected flow spans the SMF 56a ΓåÆ UPF 60f ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ APPID ΓåÆ traffic-classification ΓåÆ redirect execution chain, with direct implications for traffic steering accuracy, landing-page rendering, and OEM onboarding readiness.	Validation was successfully completed and the ticket has been closed as of 04/15/2026. The Lab 3 Consumer POD (SMF 56a / UPF 60f, UC 5.1.0.18) was selected as the validation target given its already-upgraded state. Three core validation scenarios were executed: (1) APPID PFD rule changes in IPPE were validated ΓÇö URLs such as https://www.cnn.com and https://www.google.com were added to rule group GM-4102-7 and confirmed to be correctly reflected in IPPE upon DNN attachment; (2) New PFD rules were added to an APP ID and validated with consistent propagation behavior; (3) BIG PFD scenarios were tested and confirmed that when changes are reflected in IPPE, traffic attempts are tagged as expected. All validation activities confirmed that UC 5.1.0.18 resolves previously observed IPPE synchronization bugs, redirect inconsistencies, and landing-page failures. The validated baseline has been established for future onboarding and integration activities.	Release Certification Risk | E2E Flow Disruption | OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö This validation was critical for confirming traffic-classification stability and redirect/landing-page consistency under UC 5.1.0.18. Failure to validate PFD propagation and IPPE synchronization would have left previously observed defects unconfirmed, jeopardizing OEM onboarding validation reliability and release certification confidence for the upgraded UC version. The initiative directly impacts the SMF ΓåÆ UPF ΓåÆ IPPE traffic-classification chain that underpins subscriber traffic steering accuracy.	Established definitive validated baseline for PFD synchronization, APPID propagation, and IPPE execution behavior under UC 5.1.0.18, confirming resolution of previously observed landing-page and redirect defects. Accelerated release certification confidence by executing targeted validation scenarios across APPID rule changes, new PFD rule propagation, and BIG PFD handling ΓÇö all confirmed to operate as expected. Prevented recurrence of traffic-classification instability through proactive root-cause prevention validation. Enabled OEM onboarding readiness by providing a verified behavioral baseline for future integration activities. Delivered cross-domain validation insight spanning SMF, UPF, IPPE, and APPID layers, improving platform-wide understanding of PFD propagation mechanisms.	Validation completed and ticket closed. Residual actions include: (1) Preserve validated baseline documentation (GM-4102-7 rule group behavior, BIG PFD tagging results) for reference in future UC upgrades and OEM onboarding cycles; (2) Leverage validated behavior as regression benchmark for subsequent IPPE/PFD-related changes; (3) Communicate validation outcomes to UPF and SMF teams to confirm UC 5.1.0.18 behavioral improvements are certified; (4) Apply learnings to production deployment readiness assessments for UC 5.1.0.18 rollout beyond Lab 3.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	Release certification readiness ΓÇö This initiative directly validates UC 5.1.0.18 behavioral improvements in the PFD/IPPE/APPID domain, confirming resolution of previously observed synchronization and redirect defects. The validated baseline is essential for OEM onboarding enablement and platform resiliency, ensuring traffic-classification accuracy and redirect execution stability are certified before broader deployment. The effort strengthens cross-domain stabilization across UPF, SMF, IPPE, and APPID layers.	Validation confirmed that UC 5.1.0.18 resolves previously observed IPPE/PFD inconsistencies across three critical scenarios in Lab 3 Consumer POD (SMF 56a / UPF 60f): (1) APPID PFD rule changes ΓÇö URLs added to rule group GM-4102-7 are correctly reflected in IPPE upon DNN attachment, confirming propagation path integrity; (2) New PFD rule addition to APP IDs ΓÇö propagation behavior is consistent and accurate; (3) BIG PFD scenarios ΓÇö traffic attempts are correctly tagged when IPPE reflects the updated rules. The root cause of previously observed landing-page failures and redirect inconsistencies was tied to IPPE synchronization behavior in prior UC versions, and this validation confirms the application-layer fix in UC 5.1.0.18 is effective. No infrastructure or configuration layer issues were identified ΓÇö the defect was purely application-level PFD handling logic that has been corrected in the updated UC release.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,SMF,IPPE}		t	2026-05-27 19:17:33.315845+00	2026-05-27 20:41:46.946606+00	f	\N
98	1	3	2026-03-24-00099	CTAP-61094	2026-03-24	\N	Redirection / OEM Validation	Stellantis / adn2 / adn4 / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	A redirection execution failure was identified within Stellantis Enterprise DNN scenarios (adn2 and adn4), where users were being directed to the SNAP page instead of the expected MyVehicle OEM landing page. The observed behavior indicated that redirect signaling was operational ΓÇö as evidenced by successful SNAP page delivery ΓÇö but final OEM landing-page execution was failing downstream. The affected flow spans the UPF ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ PFD synchronization ΓåÆ captive portal redirect execution chain. This disruption blocked REDIR validation, captive portal onboarding testing, and Stellantis OEM user-experience certification activities within the IoT Lab Environment. Initial troubleshooting focused on redirect execution consistency, UPF/IPPE behavior, and traffic classification accuracy across the impacted DNNs.	Root cause analysis has been completed and the issue is now closed. Initial investigation confirmed that redirect triggering was operational (SNAP behavior was functional), isolating the failure to the final OEM landing-page delivery layer. The RCA determined that the issue was caused by IPPE nodes failing to properly incorporate PFD modifications due to a code vector incomplete deletion defect ΓÇö specifically, PFDM PFD entries were not being included as part of multiple PDRs. This defect was traced to UC 5.1.0.15 and is directly related to CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348. Microsoft performed IPPE reboots as an immediate corrective action, and the permanent fix is included in UC 5.1.0.18. The issue was resolved and closed on 04/02/2026.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Stellantis REDIR validation was fully blocked for adn2 and adn4 Enterprise DNN scenarios. Captive portal and onboarding validation activities were incomplete, directly affecting OEM user-experience certification. This created delays in Enterprise IoT E2E readiness activities and posed a risk to Stellantis onboarding milestones within the IoT Lab validation cycle.	Isolated root cause between redirect signaling and final OEM landing-page execution, precisely narrowing the investigation scope to UPF/IPPE/PFD handling domains. Prevented unnecessary escalation toward charging, provisioning, IMS, and policy-generation domains ΓÇö saving cross-domain teams significant troubleshooting effort. Identified correlation with known defect CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348, accelerating RCA closure by linking to a previously characterized code vector incomplete deletion issue. Increased organizational visibility of recurring SNAP-vs-OEM-landing-page behavior patterns, contributing to a pattern library that strengthens future troubleshooting velocity for redirect execution issues across OEM onboarding scenarios.	{"Validate that UC 5.1.0.18 deployment permanently resolves PFD modification handling within IPPE nodes across adn2 and adn4","Execute controlled re-testing of Stellantis MyVehicle landing-page delivery post-fix to confirm E2E redirect execution consistency","Verify traffic classification and PFD synchronization behavior under sustained load to rule out regression","Compare post-fix redirect execution behavior against previously observed OEM redirect inconsistencies cataloged under CTAP-17630","Monitor SNAP vs MyVehicle redirect execution behavior over a defined observation window to confirm stability","Update Stellantis OEM onboarding validation tracker to reflect issue closure and readiness status"}	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No ΓÇö RCA isolation, cross-domain coordination with Microsoft/UPF/IPPE teams, and defect correlation to CTAP-17630 were driven end-to-end by C├⌐sar Villagra.	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This issue directly impacted Stellantis Enterprise IoT readiness within the captive portal and redirect validation workstream. Resolution ensures that REDIR certification activities can proceed for adn2/adn4 DNN scenarios, unblocking a critical OEM onboarding milestone. The identification of a recurring PFD synchronization defect pattern (linked to CTAP-17630) strengthens platform resiliency posture by enabling proactive defect tracking and targeted version upgrades across the UPF/IPPE redirect execution layer.	The root cause was a known IPPE defect in UC 5.1.0.15 where PFD modifications pushed via PFDM were not being incorporated into multiple PDRs due to a code vector incomplete deletion issue. This caused the IPPE to retain stale PFD state, resulting in traffic being classified against outdated rules ΓÇö redirecting users to the generic SNAP page instead of the Stellantis MyVehicle OEM landing page. The redirect signaling layer (PCF ΓåÆ UPF policy push) was fully operational; the failure was isolated to the IPPE PFD consumption layer. Microsoft's IPPE reboot served as an immediate workaround by forcing PFD state refresh, while the permanent fix in UC 5.1.0.18 addresses the incomplete deletion logic. This is a direct recurrence of the pattern documented in CTAP-17630 / ICM 697505348, confirming that environments running pre-5.1.0.18 code remain vulnerable to this class of redirect execution failure.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,IPPE,PCF,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27 19:17:04.728497+00	2026-05-27 20:41:48.61426+00	f	\N
97	1	3	11/18/2025-00098	CTAP-31749	2025-11-18	\N	UPF / IPPE / PFD	UPF / IPPE / Honda Gas OEM / d50013.etr / IoT Lab Environment	Closed	A redirect validation disruption was identified within the UPF ΓåÆ IPPE ΓåÆ PFD propagation chain during Honda Gas OEM onboarding testing for destination d50013.etr. Observed behavior: the UE was being redirected to the SNAP URL page instead of reaching the expected Honda OEM landing page, indicating a breakdown in traffic flow classification and captive portal redirect execution. Expected behavior: upon redirect trigger, the UE should be presented with the Honda Gas OEM-specific landing page as part of the captive portal onboarding flow. Technical context: the issue was traced to PFD propagation inconsistencies within IPPE, where updated PFD information failed to synchronize correctly into UPF IPPE instances, resulting in incorrect traffic classification and redirect behavior. Affected flow: UPF traffic classification ΓåÆ IPPE PFD synchronization ΓåÆ REDIR flow execution ΓåÆ Honda OEM captive portal landing page delivery. The disruption impacted end-to-end REDIR validation, captive portal behavior, and OEM onboarding certification activities within the IoT Lab environment.	Root cause analysis has been completed and the ticket is closed as of 04/08/2026. Investigation successfully isolated the failure to a known PFD bug within IPPE that prevented updated PFD information from propagating correctly into UPF IPPE instances. This propagation failure caused traffic flow identification and classification inconsistencies, directly impacting redirect behavior and landing page execution for the Honda Gas OEM scenario. Critical ruling-out: PCF policy generation, charging behavior, provisioning domains, and IMS domains were all validated as unrelated to the issue ΓÇö the defect was confined entirely to the IPPE/PFD synchronization layer. A permanent remediation path was defined via a UC patch, and a temporary workaround was validated through rebooting the affected IPPE instances. Both remediation strategies were confirmed, and final validation was completed prior to closure.	OEM Enablement Risk ΓÇö Honda OEM landing-page validation was blocked, preventing end-to-end onboarding certification for d50013.etr. Traffic classification inconsistencies within UPF/IPPE disrupted REDIR flow execution and captive portal behavior. The PFD propagation failure reduced confidence in IPPE synchronization consistency across onboarding scenarios, posing a systemic risk to future OEM validation activities dependent on PFD-driven traffic classification.	Isolated root cause to IPPE/PFD synchronization behavior, preventing unnecessary escalation toward PCF, charging, provisioning, or IMS domains ΓÇö significantly reducing cross-team investigation overhead. Identified and validated both a temporary workaround (IPPE instance reboot) and a permanent remediation strategy (UC patch), accelerating the path to resolution. Improved organizational understanding of UPF/IPPE dependency behavior and PFD propagation limitations, contributing to a more resilient onboarding validation framework. Enabled precise defect classification, ensuring the issue was tracked as an infrastructure/application-level PFD bug rather than being misattributed to policy or charging domains.	Apply UC patch to permanently remediate the PFD propagation bug across all affected IPPE instances. Validate PFD synchronization consistency post-remediation through targeted regression testing. Re-test redirect and landing-page behavior for d50013.etr to confirm Honda Gas OEM captive portal flow is fully restored. Monitor IPPE propagation behavior across future OEM onboarding validations to confirm systemic resolution and prevent recurrence. Document PFD propagation dependency and IPPE reboot workaround as a known recovery procedure for future reference.	Led by: C├⌐sar Villagra | Tier 1 Involvement: No	OEM onboarding enablement ΓÇö This initiative directly impacts the reliability of PFD-driven traffic classification within the UPF/IPPE stack, which is foundational to captive portal redirect flows and OEM landing page delivery. Resolution strengthens platform readiness for Honda Gas OEM certification and establishes a validated remediation path (UC patch) that de-risks future OEM onboarding activities dependent on IPPE PFD synchronization. The findings also contribute to cross-domain stabilization by clarifying the boundary between IPPE infrastructure behavior and upstream policy/charging domains, improving RCA precision for future incidents.	The root cause was a known PFD bug within IPPE that broke the propagation of updated PFD information into UPF IPPE instances. When PFD data was updated, the synchronization mechanism failed to deliver the changes to the UPF layer, causing traffic flow identification and classification to become inconsistent. This inconsistency manifested as the UE being redirected to the SNAP URL page instead of the expected Honda OEM landing page ΓÇö a failure at the UPF traffic classification layer, not at the policy or charging layer. The defect is application-level within IPPE, not an infrastructure connectivity issue. A temporary mitigation was validated by rebooting the affected IPPE instances (which forces re-synchronization), while the permanent fix requires a UC patch that addresses the underlying PFD propagation logic. PCF policy generation, charging behavior, and provisioning were all confirmed as functioning correctly ΓÇö the failure boundary was strictly within the IPPE/PFD synchronization path feeding the UPF classification engine.	C├⌐sar Villagra	f	application	{UPF,IPPE,PCF}		t	2026-05-27 19:16:37.169275+00	2026-05-27 20:41:50.300342+00	f	\N
142	1	3	04/24/2026-00145	CTAP-72094	2026-04-24	\N	IMS / SBC / PROVISIONING	Northrim Labs | IMS Core | SBC: wnv5a0cncs301c | EPS Fallback Validation	Closed	EPS Fallback validation failure impacting IoT E2E testing continuity within the IMS signaling domain. Observed behavior: SIP Invite message was not generated following the UE Register Request, and no TCP Handshake was observed after IMS registration attempts. Initial packet traces confirmed that the Registration Request was not being answered by SBC wnv5a0cncs301c. Expected behavior: Upon successful IMS registration, the SBC should process the Register Request, complete the SIP registration sequence, and generate the corresponding SIP Invite to continue the EPS Fallback call flow. Technical context: The investigation scope included IMS signaling integrity, SBC provisioning state, SIP routing configuration, and post-upgrade configuration consistency on the affected SBC node. Affected flow: UE ΓåÆ IMS Registration ΓåÆ SBC (wnv5a0cncs301c) ΓåÆ SIP Invite Generation ΓåÆ EPS Fallback Call Setup ΓÇö the entire E2E IoT EPS Fallback validation chain was disrupted due to SBC-level provisioning loss.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed. The investigation determined that the root cause was a post-upgrade provisioning gap on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c. Following a software upgrade on the SBC, GLS provisioning became unavailable, and associated IMS configurations failed silently. This caused the SBC to stop responding to IMS Registration Requests, which in turn prevented SIP Invite generation and broke the EPS Fallback signaling sequence entirely. RCA evolution: Initial hypothesis considered UE behavior, application-layer SIP defects, and SIP routing misconfigurations ΓÇö all were systematically ruled out. The investigation narrowed the scope to the SBC provisioning layer, where missing GLS entries were identified as the definitive root cause. After restoring the GLS provisioning on the SBC, IMS signaling normalized immediately, SIP Invite generation resumed, and the EPS Fallback test case executed successfully. Validation was completed end-to-end with no residual issues.	E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö EPS Fallback validation failure blocked IoT E2E testing activities within Northrim Labs. IMS registration flows, SIP Invite generation, and EPS Fallback call setup were all interrupted, halting validation continuity and creating risk to IoT certification timelines. The disruption spanned the full IMS signaling chain from UE registration through SBC-mediated SIP call flow establishment.	Isolated root cause to a post-upgrade provisioning gap within the SBC domain, preventing misclassification as a UE behavior issue or application-layer SIP defect. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically narrowing the investigation scope from broad IMS signaling analysis to SBC-specific GLS provisioning loss. Enabled rapid restoration by identifying the exact provisioning dependency, reducing downtime for IoT E2E validation activities. Exposed a critical gap in post-upgrade verification processes, contributing to improved operational governance for future SBC maintenance windows.	No additional actions required. GLS provisioning was restored successfully on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c. EPS Fallback validation completed successfully with end-to-end signaling confirmed. Ticket closed. Recommendation: Incorporate GLS provisioning validation into the standard post-upgrade checklist for SBC nodes to prevent recurrence during future upgrade cycles.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	IMS platform stability and post-upgrade verification governance. This initiative reinforces the critical dependency between SBC provisioning integrity and IMS signaling continuity, directly impacting IoT E2E validation stability. The findings highlight the need for formalized post-upgrade provisioning validation procedures within the IMS/SBC domain, supporting release certification readiness and cross-domain stabilization. Contributes to IoT EPS Fallback troubleshooting governance and strengthens operational maturity for future SBC maintenance activities.	Root cause confirmed: GLS provisioning was lost following a software upgrade on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c, causing the SBC to fail to respond to IMS Registration Requests. The missing GLS entries broke the SIP signaling chain ΓÇö no SIP Invite was generated after the Register Request because the SBC could not complete its provisioning-dependent processing. The failure was at the configuration/provisioning layer, not application or infrastructure. Once GLS provisioning was restored, the SBC resumed normal behavior and the EPS Fallback test case passed successfully. This confirms a provisioning persistence gap in the SBC upgrade process ΓÇö GLS state was not preserved or re-applied post-upgrade, exposing a procedural vulnerability in IMS maintenance operations.	Tier 1	t	configuration	{SBC,GLS}		f	2026-05-27 21:02:17.110488+00	2026-05-27 21:02:17.110488+00	f	Root cause confirmed: GLS provisioning was missing on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c following a software upgrade, causing IMS registration failures and preventing SIP Invite generation. After restoring the GLS provisioning and correcting the associated configurations, EPS Fallback validation completed successfully.
