106	1	3	2026-04-29-00107	CTAP-72831	2026-04-29	\N	CHARGING / CHF / INFRASTRUCTURE	Northrim Labs ΓÇö Consumer DNN ΓÇö PCF / CHF / Azure CHF / Cookies Infrastructure	Closed	CreateConvergedCharging session establishment failures were observed during Consumer DNN validation activities, disrupting the charging flow initialization path. Observed behavior: CreateConvergedCharging requests failed intermittently, preventing successful charging session creation for Consumer DNN subscribers. Expected behavior: CreateConvergedCharging requests should complete successfully, establishing charging sessions through the PCF ΓåÆ Azure CHF communication path without interruption. Technical context: The failure impacted the PCF Γåö Azure CHF connectivity layer, with initial symptoms manifesting as CHF interaction instability. The investigation spanned CHF application behavior, PCF charging interactions, infrastructure routing, and supporting network component connectivity. Affected flow: Consumer DNN E2E charging establishment ΓÇö PCF ΓåÆ Cookies ΓåÆ Azure CHF CreateConvergedCharging path. The issue was ultimately isolated to infrastructure connectivity instability rather than CHF application logic, correlating temporally with recent firewall policy changes in the environment.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed. Executive summary: CreateConvergedCharging failures were traced to infrastructure-level connectivity instability between PCF and Azure CHF environments, not to a CHF application defect. RCA evolution: (1) Initial hypothesis considered CHF application failure, PCF charging logic issues, or connectivity disruption as potential root causes. (2) Investigation identified intermittent connectivity failures between CHF and PCF, coinciding temporally with recent FW policy changes. (3) Although the FW owner stated the policy changes should not affect the PCF Γåö Azure CHF connectivity path, the temporal correlation was the strongest environmental differentiator. (4) After environmental stabilization, CreateConvergedCharging flows resumed normal operation and charging validation completed successfully. Key findings: The problem was definitively isolated to the infrastructure/connectivity layer rather than the CHF application domain, eliminating the need for CHF development team escalation.	Critical Charging Validation Blocker ΓÇö Consumer DNN E2E Testing Impacted. The infrastructure connectivity instability directly blocked CreateConvergedCharging processing, halting charging session establishment validation for Consumer DNN. E2E testing activities were suspended during the failure window, impacting charging visibility continuity and delaying Consumer DNN certification progress. The disruption affected the full charging establishment chain from PCF through Azure CHF, representing a systemic infrastructure dependency risk for charging platform operations.	Isolated root cause to the infrastructure/connectivity layer, definitively ruling out CHF application domain as the failure origin. Accelerated troubleshooting by differentiating infrastructure behavior from charging application logic, narrowing the investigation scope and preventing unnecessary escalation toward CHF development teams. Enabled cross-domain coordination between infrastructure and charging teams by identifying the temporal correlation with FW policy changes. Restored Consumer DNN charging validation capability through focused stabilization efforts, avoiding prolonged testing delays.	No additional actions required. Connectivity between PCF and Azure CHF has been stabilized successfully. CreateConvergedCharging validation completed with successful results. Ticket closed. Recommended follow-up for governance: (1) Document FW change management correlation for future PCF Γåö Azure CHF connectivity incidents. (2) Consider proactive connectivity health checks during FW policy change windows. (3) Incorporate infrastructure dependency awareness into Consumer DNN charging validation runbooks.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Infrastructure Stabilization / Charging Platform Integrity. This initiative highlights a critical infrastructure dependency in the PCF Γåö Azure CHF charging establishment path, demonstrating that charging flow reliability is directly contingent on underlying connectivity stability. The RCA evolution ΓÇö from initial CHF application suspicion to definitive infrastructure/connectivity isolation ΓÇö validates the importance of layered troubleshooting governance and cross-domain diagnostic discipline. The resolution supports Consumer DNN charging reliability, improves PCF Γåö CHF troubleshooting playbooks, and reinforces the need for FW change management coordination to protect charging flow continuity.	Initial symptom presented as CreateConvergedCharging failures, suggesting potential CHF application or PCF charging logic defects. Root cause was isolated to infrastructure connectivity instability between PCF and Azure CHF environments. The only environmental change identified was recent FW policy modifications; however, the FW owner stated these changes should not impact the PCF Γåö Azure CHF path, creating an unresolved contributing factor hypothesis. Classification: infrastructure connectivity issue, not application defect. The temporal correlation between FW changes and charging failures represents the strongest diagnostic signal, though definitive FW causality was not confirmed by the FW team. After environmental stabilization ΓÇö without explicit FW rollback ΓÇö charging flows resumed normally, suggesting either a transient infrastructure condition exacerbated by the FW changes or a self-resolving connectivity disruption. Layer broken: infrastructure/connectivity. Working path: post-stabilization PCF ΓåÆ Azure CHF CreateConvergedCharging. Failed path: pre-stabilization PCF Γåö Azure CHF communication during FW change window.	Tier 1	t	infrastructure	{CHF,PCF,Infrastructure}		t	2026-05-27