114	1	3	2026-05-19-00116	CTAP-80611	2026-05-19	\N	CHARGING / CHF / ACC VISIBILITY	Northrim Labs ΓÇô ACC / CHF / Kafka / ISBUS / Charging Visibility & Streaming Infrastructure	In Progress	Charging visibility disruption identified in the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC observability pipeline within the Northrim Labs environment. Despite successful completion of CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy transactions ΓÇö confirming that the charging core generation layer was functioning correctly ΓÇö downstream visibility toward ACC was completely absent. Session information, usage records, and charging visibility data were not appearing in ACC. The investigation scope encompassed the full downstream integration chain: CHF charging generation, Kafka broker health, Kafka Schema Registry connectivity, ISBUS Private Endpoint (PE) approval workflows, CHF streamer application behavior, and ACC ingestion components. The root cause direction was progressively narrowed from a generalized charging generation suspicion to a multi-layered downstream streaming and integration failure affecting the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ Schema Registry ΓåÆ ACC observability path.	Investigation has progressed through multiple phases with significant findings at each layer. Phase 1 ΓÇö Charging Core Validation: CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy flows were confirmed successful, definitively ruling out any charging generation defect. Phase 2 ΓÇö Kafka Broker Issue: The CHF/CCS team identified and resolved an issue affecting the Kafka broker. Phase 3 ΓÇö Schema Registry / ISBUS Connectivity: A critical connectivity gap was discovered ΓÇö the Private Endpoint (PE) request for the Kafka Schema Registry had NOT been approved by ISBUS due to a misunderstanding. ISBUS incorrectly assumed the PE request was intended for the Confluent Platform Kafka Broker rather than the Schema Registry component. This resulted in a SocketTimeoutException (java.net.SocketTimeoutException: Connect timed out) when the CHF streamer attempted HTTPS requests to the Schema Registry endpoint (cl001.eastus2.uat.iebus.3pc.att.com:8082). The PE approval was subsequently completed, restoring Schema Registry connectivity. Phase 4 ΓÇö CHF Streamer Code Defect: An additional code-level defect was identified within the CHF streamer component. The CHF development team provided a fix that corrected the streamer behavior. Current state: After all three remediation actions (Kafka broker fix, Schema Registry PE approval, CHF streamer code fix), Kafka output topics are now populated successfully. End-to-end ACC visibility restoration is pending final retest and validation.	Charging Visibility Disruption | ACC Observability Failure | E2E Validation Blocker. The issue directly impacted session visibility, charging observability, usage tracking, and all E2E validation activities dependent on ACC reporting. Although charging transactions were generated and processed successfully at the core layer, the complete absence of downstream visibility toward ACC created a critical observability gap ΓÇö effectively blinding operational teams from monitoring charging behavior. This disruption affected lab certification activities and blocked any validation workflow requiring ACC-based charging confirmation. The multi-layered nature of the failure (Kafka broker + Schema Registry PE + CHF streamer defect) compounded the impact and extended the resolution timeline.	Isolated root cause beyond charging core generation by systematically validating CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy success, definitively separating charging generation health from downstream streaming failure. Accelerated cross-domain troubleshooting by differentiating between multiple concurrent failure layers ΓÇö Kafka broker health, Schema Registry connectivity, ISBUS PE approval workflows, and CHF streamer application logic ΓÇö preventing generalized blame attribution to the charging platform. Identified a critical process gap in the ISBUS PE approval workflow where a misunderstanding between Confluent Kafka Broker and Schema Registry components caused a connectivity blockage that would have remained undetected without targeted investigation. Enabled coordinated remediation across CHF, CCS, ISBUS, Kafka infrastructure, and CHF development teams, reducing mean-time-to-resolution by narrowing investigation scope from full charging stack to specific streaming integration layers. Prevented unnecessary escalation against the charging core by proving charging generation was functioning correctly throughout the incident.	{"Execute end-to-end retest of the full CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC observability pipeline to validate complete charging visibility restoration","Validate ACC session information, usage records, and charging visibility data are accurately populated and accessible","Confirm stable and sustained Kafka topic population under normal and stress transaction volumes","Validate downstream ACC ingestion behavior to ensure records are consumed and displayed correctly","Monitor CHF streamer stability post-fix to confirm no regression or intermittent failures","Validate ISBUS PE approval for Schema Registry remains active and connectivity is persistent","Document ISBUS PE approval process gap and recommend process improvement to prevent recurrence of misclassification between Kafka Broker and Schema Registry PE requests","Close JIRA CTAP-80611 after successful E2E visibility confirmation and stability observation period"}	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support. Tier 1 owns investigation execution, CHF/CCS team coordination, and remediation validation. C├⌐sar Villagra provides cross-domain coordination support, escalation management, RCA narrative governance, and executive reporting alignment across CHF, Kafka, ISBUS, and development teams.	This initiative directly reinforces Charging Platform Observability Stabilization and Streaming Infrastructure Operational Maturity within the Northrim Labs environment. The multi-layered root cause ΓÇö spanning Kafka broker health, Schema Registry PE approval workflows, ISBUS process gaps, and CHF streamer application defects ΓÇö highlights critical dependencies between charging generation and downstream observability integration layers. Resolution of this issue strengthens the CHF ΓåÆ Kafka ΓåÆ ACC observability pipeline, improves cross-domain troubleshooting governance, and exposes process vulnerabilities in ISBUS PE approval workflows that affect broader platform connectivity. The separation between charging core health and downstream streaming visibility establishes a reusable diagnostic framework for future observability incidents. This contributes to platform-wide observability readiness and streaming infrastructure resilience for upcoming release certification and OEM onboarding activities.	The charging core generation layer was validated as fully functional ΓÇö CreateConvergedCharging and CreateSMPolicy transactions completed successfully throughout the incident, confirming no defect at the charging application level. The root cause was a compound downstream streaming integration failure consisting of three concurrent issues: (1) Kafka Broker Issue ΓÇö identified and resolved by the CHF/CCS team, restoring broker-level health; (2) Schema Registry PE Approval Gap ΓÇö the Private Endpoint request for Kafka Schema Registry was rejected by ISBUS due to a misunderstanding where ISBUS assumed the request was for the Confluent Platform Kafka Broker rather than the Schema Registry component, resulting in a java.net.SocketTimeoutException (Connect timed out) when the CHF streamer attempted HTTPS connections to the Schema Registry endpoint at cl001.eastus2.uat.iebus.3pc.att.com:8082. PE approval was subsequently completed, restoring connectivity; (3) CHF Streamer Code Defect ΓÇö the CHF streamer component contained a code-level issue that was fixed by the CHF development team. After all three remediations, Kafka output topics are now populated successfully. Classification: Downstream streaming / observability integration issue ΓÇö NOT a charging core generation failure. The critical distinction is that charging generation and downstream observability are independent layers, and failure at the streaming integration layer can create complete ACC visibility loss while charging transactions continue to succeed.	Tier 1	t	observability	{CHF,Kafka,ACC,ISBUS}		t	2026-05-27 19:25:42.875003+00	2026-05-27 20:41:19.092761+00	f	\N
