111	1	3	2026-05-07-00112	CTAP-75206	2026-05-07	\N	POLICY / BSF / PCF	Darkstar ΓÇô Line Up 4 | BSF / PCF | rdmwa25 / RD2WA65 | Policy Discovery & Routing	Closed	BSF-driven PCF discovery failover behavior investigation in Darkstar Line Up 4 environment. Observed behavior: The BSF returned rdmwa25 PCF as the selected policy control function instance during PCF discovery. Expected behavior: The BSF was expected to return RD2WA65 PCF as the preferred PCF instance bound to Darkstar Line Up 4. Technical context: The investigation targeted the BSF ΓåÆ PCF discovery and binding path, evaluating whether the observed PCF selection represented an incorrect PCF binding, a BSF routing defect, a locality misconfiguration, or an expected failover/fallback mechanism within the Darkstar architecture. Affected flow: BSF PCF discovery ΓåÆ PCF selection ΓåÆ Policy establishment path across Darkstar Line Up 4, impacting the SMF ΓåÆ BSF ΓåÆ PCF policy routing chain.	Investigation completed and ticket closed as of 05/13/2026. Initial observations indicated Darkstar Line Up 4 BSF was returning rdmwa25 PCF instead of the expected RD2WA65 PCF instance. Collaboration with SMF support confirmed that the preferred PCF instance (RD2WA65) was in a suspended state. When the preferred PCF became unavailable, the BSF automatically selected another available PCF instance (rdmwa25) as part of its designed failover logic. Additional validation confirmed: (1) the alternate PCF instance contained identical configuration to the preferred instance, (2) locality had been correctly assigned since Day 1 per the overall Darkstar project plan, and (3) the behavior aligned fully with the Darkstar architecture design. The test case did not fail ΓÇö policy establishment continued successfully, and routing continuity was maintained through the alternate PCF. RCA conclusion: behavior classified as working as designed. No defect identified in BSF routing logic, PCF binding, or locality configuration.	PCF Discovery / Failover Validation ΓÇö No Functional Service Impact. The observed behavior generated initial confusion regarding expected PCF binding behavior in Darkstar Line Up 4, but did not result in service interruption, policy establishment failures, or test case failures. The platform maintained routing continuity, policy delivery, and operational stability through automatic BSF-driven failover behavior. No charging, observability, or E2E flow disruption was identified.	Successfully differentiated actual PCF discovery defects from expected BSF failover behavior, preventing unnecessary escalation toward BSF or PCF development teams. Validated platform resiliency mechanisms by confirming BSF automatic failover logic operated correctly when the preferred PCF instance was suspended. Confirmed locality configuration consistency across PCF instances since Day 1, reinforcing confidence in the Darkstar architecture baseline. Improved cross-team understanding of Darkstar failover architecture, PCF selection logic, and BSF routing governance. Avoided misclassification of working-as-designed behavior as a platform defect, saving engineering investigation cycles and protecting release certification timelines.	No additional actions required. BSF failover behavior validated successfully. Locality configuration confirmed consistent. PCF routing continuity verified. Ticket closed on 05/13/2026. Findings documented to serve as reference for future PCF discovery behavior inquiries in Darkstar environments and to prevent recurrence of false-positive escalations against BSF or PCF routing logic.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Platform Resiliency Validation ΓÇö This investigation directly validates BSF resiliency mechanisms and PCF failover continuity behavior within the Darkstar architecture. Confirms that the BSF-driven PCF discovery path maintains routing continuity when preferred instances become unavailable, a critical attribute for production readiness and release certification. Improves organizational understanding of Darkstar routing architecture and prevents false-positive escalation toward PCF discovery logic, strengthening operational troubleshooting governance. Contributes to cross-domain stabilization by confirming alignment between BSF routing design, locality assignment, and the overall Darkstar project plan.	Observed Behavior: BSF returned rdmwa25 PCF instead of the expected RD2WA65 PCF during PCF discovery in Darkstar Line Up 4. Root Cause: The preferred PCF instance (RD2WA65) was in a suspended state. System Behavior: BSF automatically selected another available PCF instance (rdmwa25) that contained identical configuration and correct locality assignment. The failover was seamless ΓÇö policy establishment succeeded, and the test case passed without interruption. Validation Confirmed: (1) Locality assignment was correct since Day 1, (2) BSF failover logic operated as designed, (3) PCF routing continuity was maintained through the alternate instance, (4) configuration parity between PCF instances ensured no functional degradation. Classification: Working as designed. The BSF failover path is an intentional resiliency mechanism ΓÇö when the preferred PCF is unavailable, the BSF derives traffic to the next available PCF with equivalent configuration. This is not a routing defect but a designed fallback behavior aligned with the overall Darkstar project architecture. Impacted Domains: BSF / PCF discovery and failover architecture. Layer: Application-level failover logic (no infrastructure, configuration, or observability defect identified).	Tier 1	t	working_as_designed	{BSF,PCF,SMF}		t	2026-05-27 19:23:18.563997+00	2026-05-27 20:41:24.715904+00	f	\N
