s and demonstrates mature infrastructure vs. application RCA differentiation capability. Highlights critical dependency on Azure CHF connectivity stability for Consumer DNN policy establishment workflows. Contributes to improved policy establishment troubleshooting governance and strengthens infrastructure change management awareness across the platform. Directly relevant to Consumer DNN validation reliability and platform resiliency posture for QBR reporting.	503 Service Unavailable errors during CreateSMPolicy were traced to infrastructure connectivity instability between PCF and Azure CHF ΓÇö not to PCF policy logic or CHF application processing. The only infrastructure modification observed during the affected timeframe was a set of FW policy/environment changes. Despite the FW owner's assessment that those changes should not have impacted connectivity, the temporal correlation was direct and no other contributing factors were identified. After environmental stabilization, all CreateSMPolicy requests completed successfully and PCF Γåö CHF communication normalized. Classification: infrastructure connectivity issue at the network/FW layer, not an application defect. The working path (PCF Γåö Azure CHF) was disrupted at the infrastructure layer while both application endpoints remained functionally healthy, confirming that the failure domain was entirely below the application layer.	Tier 1	t	infrastructure	{PCF,CHF}		t	2026-05-27 19:21:27.305054+00	2026-05-27 20:41:31.453096+00	f	\N
105	1	3	2026-04-24-00106	CTAP-72094	2026-04-24	\N	IMS / SBC / PROVISIONING	Northrim Labs | IMS Core | SBC: wnv5a0cncs301c | EPS Fallback Validation	Closed	EPS Fallback signaling disruption impacting IoT E2E validation within the IMS domain following SBC upgrade on wnv5a0cncs301c. During EPS Fallback validation, the expected SIP signaling sequence was not observed after UE registration. Specifically, the SIP Invite message was not generated after the Register Request, and the TCP Handshake was absent following IMS registration attempts. Initial trace analysis revealed that the Registration Request was not being answered by SBC cncs301. The investigation scope encompassed IMS signaling integrity, SBC provisioning consistency, SIP routing behavior, and post-upgrade configuration state to isolate the root cause across the SBC ΓåÆ IMS ΓåÆ SIP Invite generation path. Observed behavior: SIP Invite not generated post-registration; SBC cncs301 not responding to Register Requests; TCP Handshake absent in IMS registration flow. Expected behavior: Successful UE registration triggering SIP Invite generation through the IMS signaling chain, completing the EPS Fallback validation sequence end-to-end. Technical context: IMS SBC wnv5a0cncs301c, GLS provisioning dependency, SIP signaling path, EPS Fallback flow. Affected flow: UE Registration ΓåÆ SBC Registration Response ΓåÆ TCP Handshake ΓåÆ SIP Invite Generation ΓåÆ EPS Fallback Completion.	Issue fully resolved and ticket closed as of 05/21/2026. The investigation conclusively determined that a software upgrade performed on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c resulted in the loss of GLS provisioning data, which caused downstream IMS configuration failures. The missing GLS provisioning prevented the SBC from correctly processing IMS registration requests, which in turn blocked the entire SIP signaling chain including SIP Invite generation. RCA evolution: initial hypothesis considered UE behavior, application-layer SIP defects, and SIP routing issues ΓÇö all were systematically ruled out. Investigation narrowed to SBC provisioning state post-upgrade, where GLS provisioning was confirmed missing. After restoring the GLS provisioning on the SBC, IMS signaling normalized immediately, the SBC resumed correct behavior, and the EPS Fallback test case executed successfully end-to-end. No residual issues observed post-restoration.	Critical Testing Blocker | IMS Signaling Disruption | E2E Flow Disruption ΓÇö The post-upgrade provisioning gap directly blocked IoT E2E EPS Fallback testing activities within Northrim Labs. IMS registration flows were completely interrupted, SIP Invite generation was halted, and validation continuity for the EPS Fallback test campaign was disrupted. The failure prevented certification progress on IoT EPS Fallback scenarios until GLS provisioning was restored, impacting lab testing velocity and IMS domain validation readiness.	Isolated a post-upgrade provisioning gap within the IMS/SBC domain, preventing misclassification of the issue as a UE behavior defect or application-layer SIP failure. Accelerated troubleshooting by systematically ruling out SIP routing and application-layer hypotheses, narrowing the investigation scope directly to SBC provisioning consistency and GLS dependency. Enabled rapid restoration by identifying the exact provisioning artifact lost during the SBC upgrade cycle. Established a precedent for post-upgrade provisioning verification governance within IMS/SBC environments, reducing future risk of similar disruptions. Prevented unnecessary escalation to application or UE teams by conclusively attributing the failure to infrastructure-layer provisioning loss.	No additional actions required. GLS provisioning has been fully restored on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c. EPS Fallback validation completed successfully with expected SIP signaling behavior confirmed end-to-end. Recommendation: incorporate GLS provisioning verification as a mandatory post-upgrade checkpoint within SBC upgrade runbooks to prevent recurrence. Consideration for future cycles: validate IMS configuration integrity as part of SBC upgrade acceptance criteria before releasing the node back to lab testing activities.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Directly supports IMS platform stability validation and reinforces the criticality of post-upgrade verification processes within SBC environments. Highlights a provisioning dependency between GLS and IMS/SBC configurations that, if unaddressed, poses a systemic risk to IoT E2E validation campaigns. Contributes to EPS Fallback troubleshooting governance maturity by establishing a documented case where upgrade-induced provisioning loss caused full signaling chain disruption. Strengthens the operational baseline for IoT E2E validation stability and informs upgrade acceptance criteria improvements for IMS infrastructure. Relevant to QBR themes: Infrastructure Stabilization, Release Certification Readiness, Cross-domain Stabilization.	Root cause was definitively identified as missing GLS provisioning on SBC wnv5a0cncs301c following a software upgrade. The upgrade process failed to preserve or restore GLS provisioning data, which is a critical dependency for IMS configuration integrity on the SBC. Without GLS provisioning, the SBC could not process IMS registration requests, breaking the entire downstream signaling chain: UE Register Request ΓåÆ SBC Response ΓåÆ TCP Handshake ΓåÆ SIP Invite generation. The failure was at the configuration/provisioning layer, not the application layer ΓÇö SBC software was functioning correctly but operating against an incomplete provisioning state. Classification: post-upgrade provisioning/configuration loss. The working path vs. failing path distinction was clear: pre-upgrade SBC behavior was nominal; post-upgrade behavior failed immediately due to absent GLS data. Restoration of GLS provisioning fully normalized all IMS signaling flows, confirming the provisioning gap as the sole root cause. Impacted domains: IMS / SBC / SIP signaling / EPS Fallback / GLS provisioning. This case underscores that SBC upgrades carry provisioning persistence risk that must be validated as part of upgrade acceptance procedures.	Tier 1	t	configuration	{SBC,GLS,IMS}		t	2026-05-27 19:20:35.446001+00	2026-05-27 20:41:35.416874+00	f	\N
