g correctly; the root cause resides in the Probes layer, which failed to capture the SMF Γåö CHF signaling. The Testing Team has been directed to follow up with the Probes Team for remediation of capture visibility.	Charging Visibility Loss ΓÇö Missing observability of converged charging signaling between SMF and CHF led to reduced confidence in charging validation results, created risk of false-positive interpretation of core charging behavior, and introduced delays in FN-IoT charging verification activities. Without resolution, this observability gap could have triggered unnecessary escalations toward SMF, CHF, policy, and charging-processing domains, consuming cross-domain engineering resources on a non-existent core defect.	Successfully differentiated actual core NF charging behavior from probes/capture observability limitations, preventing unnecessary escalation toward SMF, CHF, policy, and charging-processing domain teams. Accelerated root cause identification through structured domain isolation methodology ΓÇö systematically validating signaling generation versus signaling observability to conclusively narrow the investigation scope to the Probes layer. Improved organizational troubleshooting methodology by establishing a reusable diagnostic framework that distinguishes between core function defects and observability infrastructure gaps, directly applicable to future charging investigations. Preserved cross-domain engineering bandwidth by eliminating false-positive core defect hypothesis early in the investigation cycle.	{"Probes Team to investigate and remediate the signaling capture gap affecting SMF Γåö CHF converged charging visibility","Testing Team to follow up directly with Probes Team on capture integrity restoration and validation","Validate probes/capture integrity during subsequent FN-IoT charging investigation cycles to confirm observability restoration","Preserve and document the structured domain isolation troubleshooting methodology for reuse i