ly impacted SM policy creation, disrupted PCF Γåö CHF charging interactions, blocked Consumer DNN E2E validation, and interrupted charging/policy testing continuity across the affected environment.	Isolated root cause to infrastructure/connectivity behavior, preventing unnecessary escalation toward PCF development or CHF application teams. The investigation differentiated infrastructure instability from application-layer failures through systematic RCA, accelerated stabilization efforts for Consumer DNN policy validation activities, and validated that PCF policy logic and CHF processing were functioning correctly ΓÇö avoiding misclassification of a connectivity issue as an application defect.	No additional actions required. Connectivity stabilized successfully. CreateSMPolicy validation completed successfully. Consumer DNN E2E validation resumed. Ticket closed. Recommend monitoring for recurrence if future FW policy changes are applied in the Azure CHF connectivity path.	Led by: Tier 1 | TPM Role: C├⌐sar Villagra ΓÇô Project Management Support	Supports PCF Γåö CHF cross-domain stabilization activities and demonstrates infrastructure vs. application RCA differentiation capability. Highlights critical dependency on Azure CHF connectivity stability for policy establishment flows. Improves policy establishment troubleshooting governance by establishing precedent for infrastructure-first investigation when 503 responses are observed in PCF Γåö CHF paths. Contributes to Consumer DNN validation reliability and reinforces the need for change-impact correlation analysis during infrastructure modifications.	503 Service Unavailable responses during CreateSMPolicy were conclusively traced to infrastructure connectivity instability between PCF and Azure CHF ΓÇö not to PCF policy logic or CHF application processing. The only infrastructure change observed during the failure window was FW policy/environment modifications. Although the FW owner stated those changes should not have 